<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneDoorHearing 2ndLd-Writethru a0785 04-27 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Door Hearing, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0785,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Did Not Fully Inspect Ill-Fated Cargo Door</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to recast, emphasizing that FAA was unaware
of cargo door problems. Picks up 10th graf pvs, `Another FAA...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal inspector who oversees United
Airlines' Boeing 747 fleet testified Thursday he had not been aware
the airline had a problem with a cargo door that later blew off in
flight, killing nine passengers.
   Inspector George Batiza also said the Federal Aviation
Administration had failed to ensure that United complied with a
federal rule that took effect last July 1, requiring airlines to
inspect cargo doors after they were manually operated because of
electrical problems.
   Testimony on the final day of a three-day hearing into the
accident held by the National Transportation Safety Board also
centered on Boeing's design for the door. But the hearing failed to
unearth any definite cause for the accident.
   On Wednesday, the airline testified that it was unaware of the
FAA's inspection rule and was not in compliance for about nine
months.
   But by coincidence, company mechanics made a partial inspection
of the ill-fated cargo door in late December, two months before the
Feb. 24 disaster, a United executive said Thursday. The inspection
followed repairs made to the door, which had failed to open and
close electrically.
   ``I am convinced the check ... verified that the door was
working,'' said Robert Doll, United vice president for technical
services.
   He added, however, that the inspection was not as thorough as
the Federal Aviation Administration required under the new rule.
   Batiza testified that he was unaware of the repairs at the time
and had not found any deficiencies in United's maintenance program
recently.
   Ray Ramakis, manager of aircraft maintenance for the FAA,
testified later that agency inspectors were required to review rule
changes with airlines to see if airline plans for responding to the
changes were adequate.
   Ramakis declined to comment when asked to explain how Batiza,
who oversees United's 31-plane 747 fleet, could not know that
United was failing to follow the new rule.
   Another FAA inspector, Robert Sanchez, said Thursday he was
unaware that United was using power tools to operate some cargo
doors, despite recommendations from Boeing not to do so for fear of
damaging the mechanisms.
   Sanchez, who oversees maintenance for United's entire 412-plane
fleet, said he was unaware until just a few weeks ago that the
company had received FAA approval to use the power tools.
   The NTSB hearing was being held to gather evidence on why the
door and part of the fuselage tore off United Flight 811 as the 747
was climbing to 23,000 feet. Nine passengers were sucked out of the
plane over the Pacific Ocean, 85 miles southwest of Honolulu as the
plane headed for Australia.
   Speculation has focused on a possible malfunction in the locking
mechanism of the cargo door, which remains on the bottom of the
Pacific Ocean. The NTSB has not decided whether to retrieve it.
   Boeing was sharply criticized by an accident investigator for
the Air Line Pilots Association for insisting 747 cargo doors are
safe despite two incidents since 1987 of the doors opening in
mid-flight.
   A door on a Pan Am flight out of London partially opened in 1987
and the plane had to return to London, with no loss of life. No
definite cause has ever been established for that incident.
   ``We cannot explain the Pan American incident, and we have the
United accident where the door failed, but we steadfastly are
saying the door is safe,'' Capt. Douglas Robinson of ALPA
complained.
   Boeing engineering manager James Fitzgerald spent two hours in
the witness chair defending the design and operation of the cargo
door, which has been the main focus of the investigation.
   ``I don't know how the door came open,'' Fitzgerald said. ``I
don't want to speculate on how it happened.''
   Under questioning, Fitzgerald told the NTSB that Boeing had not
done projections on the effect of cargo-door openings in mid-flight.
   ``You had no idea what would happen ... when the door came off
the airplane?'' an incredulous Robinson asked.
   ``The doors are not designed to come off the airplane,''
Fitzgerald replied. ``We had no way of knowing exactly what would
happen if a door came open in flight.''
   Boeing builds 747s in nearby Everett, Wash.
</TEXT>
