<FIRST>r a AM-RiteAidArrest     04-27 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rite Aid Arrest,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rite Aid President Charged With Bribing Pharmacy Board Member</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Rite Aid Corp., the nation's
largest retail pharmacy chain, was arrested Thursday on charges of
paying a $33,000 bribe to a state Pharmacy Board member,
authorities said.
   Martin Grass allegedly was videotaped saying the money was
intended to induce the board member to quit so a replacement of
Rite Aid's choosing could be appointed by the administration of
Gov. Richard Celeste, prosecutors said.
   Assistant Cuyahoga County Prosecutor William Caine said Grass
also promised the pharmacy board member family medical insurance
for four years if the member signed an undated resignation letter.
   Rite Aid, in a statement, said the arrest stemmed from a
vendetta by the pharmacy board against Rite Aid and said the
payment by check reflected money legally owed by the chain to the
board member.
   A spokesman for the governor denied Celeste intended to appoint
a pharmacy board member who would be supportive of Rite Aid, which
is based in Shiremanstown, Pa.
   The prosecutor's office did not identify the target of the
alleged bribe attempt but Rite Aid said Grass met with board member
Melvin Wilczynski of Toledo, who declined to comment on the
allegations.
   Caine said Grass brought six drafts of an undated resignation
letter, one of which the board member signed, and suggested that
the board member retire between June and October.
   ```We'll let you know,''' Caine quoted Grass as telling the
board member with regard to the effective date of the resignation.
   The pharmacy board is made up of eight voting members appointed
to staggered four-year terms by the governor subject to Senate
confirmation. The executive director only votes to break ties.
   Grass was charged with bribery and was freed after posting 10
percent of his $100,000 surety bond. His attorney, John S. Pyle,
declined comment.
   Garry South, Celeste's communications director, said the
governor knew nothing about the matter.
   ``He (the governor) has never heard of the guy (Grass),'' South
said. ``He is either using the governor for cover or using too many
drugs from his own drug store.''
   Suzanne Mead, assistant vice president for corporate
communications for Rite Aid, said the charge was ``totally without
merit and the payment in question was made in satisfaction of a
contract between a pharmacist, who also is an Ohio pharmacy board
member, and People's Drugstores, his former employer.''
   She said Rite Aid acquired the Lane Drug Division of Peoples
Drugstores on April 10 and was liable for the payment under the
contract. The payment was made in settlement of the contract and
was legal, she said.
</TEXT>
