<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Mellon     04-27 0114</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Mellon,110</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Pays Tribute to Art Philanthropist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush paid tribute Thursday night to
the late Andrew Mellon, the philanthropist and onetime Treasury
Secretary who founded the National Gallery of Art.
   Bush, just back from a four-day, cross-country trip, attended
the black-tie dinner at the National Gallery with his wife, Barbara.
   Bush said Mellon created a tradition that reaffirms the nation's
``decency and kindness.''
   The president also praised Mellon's son Paul, whose family
remains intimately involved in donating art and raising funds for
the gallery.
   Mellon announced that former Ambassador Walter Annenberg and his
wife will lend 50 of their Impressionist and post-Impressionist
works to the gallery next spring.
</TEXT>
