<FIRST>r a AM-AirForce-Discrimination     04-27 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Force-Discrimination,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds One of Largest Air Force Discrimination Settlements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court, spurning charges of
reverse discrimination, affirmed an agreement Thursday that calls
for the government to promote 240 black civilian workers at Robins
Air Force Base.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld a consent degree
issued by U.S. District Judge Wilbur Owens that also required the
government to pay $3.75 million in back pay to 3,200 black
civilians who were employed at the base between 1972 and 1979.
   The agreement, reached in 1984 on a lawsuit filed in 1975, was
one of the largest discrimination settlements in Air Force history.
   The three-judge appeals panel agreed with Owens that black
civilian workers were entitled to the promotions because of past
discrimination at the base near Warner Robins, about 100 miles
south of Atlanta.
   The appeals court earlier had ordered Owens to allow a group of
white and non-minority employees, called the Warner Robins
Constitutional Rights Fund, to intervene in the lawsuit and
challenge the promotions. That group had challenged Owens' decision
in October 1987 to reaffirm the 1984 decree.
   The court ruled on an appeal by the fund, upholding the consent
decree and saying the interveners had failed to present any
evidence that the decree would have hurt their own chances for
promotion.
   Robert T. Poss, president of the Warner Robins Constitutional
Rights Fund, said in a telephone interview that the group would
discuss the ruling before deciding whether to appeal future.
   But, he added, ``We thought from the beginning it would be a
case that would have to be decided by the Supreme Court.''
   Thursday's opinion, written by Circuit Judge Charles Clark,
noted that 169 promotions were granted to blacks under the decree
between December 1984 and October 1986 and that those promotions
``comprised only 4.3 percent of the promotions made at Warner
Robins during that period of time.''
   The court noted that the decree was narrowly written so the
promotions were made only to 38 target positions to which the
original black plaintiffs had ``demonstrated that black employees
were promoted in proportions less than their representation in the
work force or in lower grades.''
   Clark wrote that the white and non-minority employees ``did not
present any evidence that any one of them otherwise eligible for a
target position was denied that position.''
   Robins Air Force Base spokesman Dale Brinkman said Thursday
night that base officials had not had time to study the court's
ruling so it was ``premature for me to make any statement on it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
