<FIRST>r i PM-LibyanDefection     04-27 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libyan Defection,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libyan Airman Lands Helicopter, Requests Egyptian Asylum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Libyan air force officer split away from a
five-helicopter squadron flying to Sudan, landed his craft in
southern Egypt and requested asylum, a senior security source said.
   The incident Wednesday was the fourth defection-motivated
landing by Libyan military aircraft in Egypt in just over two
years. Relations between Egypt and Libya have been badly strained
since 1972.
   The security source, speaking by telephone from the southern
provincial capital of Aswan, identified the officer as Maj. Fat'hi
Miloud al-Saghir, 26.
   He said el-Saghir landed his Soviet-made helicopter about 62
miles south of Aswan and told Egyptian officers he wanted asylum
because he opposed participation in military operations in southern
Sudan and was ``unhappy'' with the regime of Libyan leader Col.
Moammar Gadhafi.
   Libya has been giving military aid to the Sudanese government of
Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi to fight a 6-year-old rebellion in three
southern regions.
   Libyan-Egyptian relations soured in 1972 after Cairo spurned a
bid by Gadhafi for immediate merger of the two countries.
   Five years later, the two countries fought a five-day border war
after a series of bombings in Egyptian cities that Cairo blamed on
Libyan agents. Relations chilled further after Gadhafi denounced
Egypt for signing a peace treaty with Israel in 1979.
   Libya expelled more than 40,000 Egyptian workers in 1986, but
tens of thousands of Egyptians continue to work there.
</TEXT>
