<FIRST>r a PM-LucyRemembrance     04-27 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lucy Remembrance,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lucy Always Credited Others And Never Knew How Great She Was</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Ball, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Thomas has covered Hollywood for The
Associated Press for 45 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By BOB THOMAS</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She never knew how great she was.
   Amid the blimp-size egos of the entertainment world, Lucille
Ball stood out like an orange beacon. She never bragged. She never
exercised her considerable power. She always seemed astonished,
even embarrassed, when honors inevitably came her way.
   When she was to receive a humanitarian award from Variety Clubs
on a CBS special five years ago, she told me: ``There comes a time
in your life when you get a lot of plaques. It's very flattering
and I'll go along with it, especially if it benefits children.''
   Whenever she was praised for ``I Love Lucy,'' she invariably
replied: ``Well, all of the credit should go to (writers) Madelyn
Pugh and Bob Carroll Jr.'' Or, ``Desi was a genius: He was
responsible for the show's success.'' Or she cited co-stars Desi,
Vivian Vance and Bill Frawley.
   Yes, the writing and producing and casting of ``I Love Lucy''
were marvelous, but Lucy's performance added the quantum force. Her
inspired pantomime could be written by no one: the growing panic as
the chocolate assembly line speeded up; her catalog of pained
expressions after tasting the patent medicine she was demonstrating.
   Unlike many stars, Lucille Ball rarely indulged in
self-analysis. But on one occasion she revealed why her feelings
about the ``I Love Lucy'' triumph might have been ambivalent:
   Living through the last five years of the show, she said, ``took
the edge off any enjoyment I might have had. Desi's drinking and
carousing were a terrible embarrassment, bad for a woman's
self-esteem. The talk around town was `poor Lucy.' Because I
couldn't face people, I became a recluse for more than 5{ years.
   ``I never demonstrated my unhappiness at the studio, and
actually, working together was a blessing. Desi had everything so
well organized that it was easy to do the work.''
   Lucy was late in reaching her comedy potential. She was 40 when
``I Love Lucy'' started on CBS and revolutionized television. And
although she spent many years in Hollywood, ``none of the studios
ever designed comedies for me the way MGM did for Red Skelton,
Paramount did for Bob Hope and Sam Goldwyn did for Danny Kaye,''
she once said.
   ``Television was the medium for me, the medium for anyone who
wanted to be well known a lot faster than waiting a year and a half
for a movie to come out,'' she said in an interview late in life.
``Television is an instant barometer, especially the way we did it.
   ``It was all new. Nobody knew anything about television. Nobody
was there to say, `No, don't do that, it's wrong!' We never knew
what was wrong and what was right. We were all feeling our way.
Desi was very innovative and very showmanship-conscious and was
very intent on going ahead and doing it: `That sounds all right,
let's go!' So we went.''
   Always the credit to someone else. But millions upon millions of
television watchers know otherwise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890427-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0052EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Georgia-Protester     04-27 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Georgia-Protester,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tbilisi Protest Organizer Still Detained Two Weeks After Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TBILISI, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When 200 officers in riot gear came to
arrest protest organizer Zviad Gamsakhurdia two weeks ago, they
stormed over the walls of his home _ actually a museum to his
poet-father.
   And when the heavily armed officers returned to search the
premises, they were stymied outside for four hours because
Gamsakhurdia's 9-year-old son refused to open the door when he was
home alone.
   Gamsakhurdia, 50, is one of Georgia's most prominent dissidents,
who helped organize demonstrations that ended April 9 in a bloody
confrontation between troops and protesters. At least 20 people
died in the unrest.
   One of the southern republic's most prominent activists, he is
following the example of his late father, Konstantin, a revered
writer who was involved in creating the independent republic of
Georgia that existed from 1918 to 1921.
   After the government confiscated some of his father's earnings
six years ago, his son persuaded authorities to use the disputed
funds to renovate the family home into a house-museum showcasing
Konstantin's life.
   The leaky roof and old linoleum are gone, according to Zviad's
wife, Manana. The family now lives in spacious rooms with carved
wooden shutters and a sweeping staircase.
   Mrs. Gamsakhurdia said in an interview Tuesday that her husband
is still being held, and she has not been allowed to see him or
heard from him since.
   Gamsakhurdia helped start the series of demonstrations that
culminated in the April 9 tragedy when he went on a hunger strike
March 11, with a list of 20 demands. Many of the demands involved
ethnic issues, such as vandalism of an antique church, allegedly by
Southern Ossetians, and anti-Georgian discrimination in Abkhazia, a
region of Georgia on the Black Sea.
   But in seeking a resolution to these disputes, he drew
accusations that he was inciting ethnic tensions himself.
   By the end of March, Abkhazians were holding mass meetings to
complain about discrimination against them by Georgians. The
Tbilisi demonstrations started as a response to the Abkhazian
demands for secession from Georgia, and evolved into a mass call
for Georgia's secession from the Soviet Union.
   On April 9, protesters helped Gamsakhurdia and other organizers
escape the Tbilisi clash because they assumed the leaders were the
targets of the soldiers, said Mrs. Gamsakhurdia.
   At 6 a.m. that day, Gamsakhurdia was at Tbilisi State
University, organizing a general strike, Mrs. Gamsakhurdia said.
   At 8:30 a.m., about 200 officers of the KGB, the Interior
Ministry and police descended on the family home in a neighborhood
of antique meandering streets, and scaled the 12-foot-high brick
wall rather than ring the bell, Mrs. Gamsakhurdia said. They had no
arrest warrant _ ``nothing at all,'' she said.
   The officers donned riot gear, burst through a door, attacked
her husband and dragged him off to jail, she said.
   The officers did not damage the shrine of books, photographs and
memorabilia of Gamsakhurdia's father and his involvement in
Georgia's heady three years as an independent nation. But in the
garden, the officers uprooted the crosses on the graves of
Konstantin, his wife and daughter.
   ``Why do they do that to dead people?'' Mrs. Gamsakhurdia asked.
   When the police returned April 15 for a search, only to be put
off by the 9-year-old, Mrs. Gamsakhurdia called the Communist Party
headquarters of Georgia. She said she threatened to release to the
world press a photograph of the troops swarming over her home if
such actions did not halt.
   On April 20, her home was searched _ by just four officials, she
said.
   Mrs. Gamsakhurdia says she does not believe new Georgian
Communist Party chief Givi Gumbaridze when he says he wants a
dialogue with opponents to replace the traditional party monologue.
   ``They still don't want a dialogue,'' she said. If officials
really wanted to talk with her husband and other activists, they
would release them from prison, she said.
   She also noted that her husband's 20 demands have never been
published in the local press, but Soviet TV ran daily reports last
year on an American hunger striker in front of the White House.
   Gamsakhurdia's other demands include halting construction of the
Transcaucasian Railway and several hydroelectric dams, closure of
the polluting oil refinery at Batumi on the Black Sea, return of
the deported Meskhetian minority from Central Asia to their
homeland in Georgia, and restoration of university-level Georgian
studies programs.
   Authorities have taken action on only one of his 20 demands:
conversion of the Metekhi chapel from a concert hall to a place of
worship, his wife said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
