<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--SoCalEarthquake     04-27 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--SoCal Earthquake,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Jolts Coast and San Fernando Valley</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quake rattled the metropolitan area,
including 30 people at an earthquake preparedness meeting who
thought the jolt was staged as part of their training.
   No injuries or damage was reported.
   The tremor, which measured 3.5 on the Richter scale, struck
Wednesday afternoon and was centered in the Pacific Ocean nine
miles west of El Segundo, said Bob Finn, a spokesman for the
California Institute of Technology.
   ``It was pretty strong. It was a rolling kind,'' said dispatcher
Kim Neil at the Santa Monica Police Department.
   The Santa Monica Emergency Services coordinator had just opened
the meeting in the City Council chambers when the tremor shook the
building.
   ``Everybody just looked at each other like, `Are they causing
this for the meeting?''' said Brenda Sweet, a reserve police
officer.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause
slight damage in the local area.
</TEXT>
