<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ANPA-BarbaraBush     04-27 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ANPA-Barbara Bush,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Urges Publishers: Press Onward With Campaign Encouraging
Literacy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush has called on the nation's newspaper
publishers to step up their efforts to fight illiteracy.
   ``We know the job of building a literate America is far from
done and newspapers have a crucial role to play,'' the first lady
told an audience of about 1,000 gathered at the American Newspaper
Publishers Association's 103rd annual convention on Wednesday.
   Mrs. Bush's talk came on the final day of the three-day meeting,
which President Bush addressed Monday.
   Mrs. Bush plans to direct much attention to the nation's
literacy problems during her husband's presidency.
   ``Tens of millions of Americans will never pick up a
newspaper,'' and that has obvious implications for the industry,
she told the publishers.
   She said one of the main thrusts of literacy programs should be
family literacy, ``where it all begins.''
   ``Parents are their children's first role models,'' and
illiterate parents are likely to raise children who cannot read or
write, the first lady said.
   ``To break this cycle of despair we have to establish literacy
as a value in every American family.''
   She gave several examples of disadvantaged people across the
country, who, with the help of literacy programs, have gotten off
welfare and continued their educations.
   One woman, Evelyn Vega, 29, of Stamford, Conn., was a
third-generation welfare mother who learned to read and got off
public aid last year with the help of a United Way literacy program.
   ``These are the stories of struggle and triumph that newspapers
nationwide have used to mobilize'' literacy efforts, Mrs. Bush said.
   Newspapers also should look within their own ranks in tackling
the problem, she said, citing the case of a typesetter at a
Washington, D.C., publication ``who could not read what she
produced.''
   The woman is an example of people who learn to cope and mask
their reading problems, but still must be helped, Mrs. Bush said.
   Los Angeles Times Publisher Tom Johnson, who spoke after the
first lady, cited his newspaper's efforts as an example of what the
industry can do to address the problem.
   The Times has organized a literacy program that includes centers
where children and their parents can learn to read, Johnson said.
   ``No profession is more affected by illiteracy than ours,'' he
said. ``The future of newspapers depends on the ability of our
citizens to read.''
   Johnson urged his colleagues to take part ``in an all-out
national campaign against illiteracy. Together,'' he said, ``we can
make a difference.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890427-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BeardCaucus Bjt   04-27 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beard Caucus, Bjt,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bearded Legislators Caucus, Deny They're Endangered Species</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beards, an ancient badge of wisdom and
virility, are vanishing from the halls of Congress. But a few of
the House members who are still sporting chin whiskers _ and proud
of it _ gathered to keep the faith.
   ``There'll always be beards,'' said Rep. David E. Bonior,
D-Mich., the undaunted chairman of the House Beard Caucus, whose
members convened in the House barber shop Wednesday to count noses
and admire each other's facial adornments.
   Only two others showed up _ Reps. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, and
Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif. The two remaining members, Reps. Ron
Dellums, D-Calif., and Floyd Flake, D-N.Y., sent their regrets.
   The dwindling ranks of the beard caucus, down to only five
members from about a dozen last year, surely make it one of the
smallest and least influential special-interest groups on Capitol
Hill.
   Indeed, Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., says with a laugh that he
recently shaved off his distinctive goatee, which he'd worn for 17
years, ``when I discovered there was no PAC (political action
committee) that was interested in the beard caucus.''
   Bonior, who also is chief deputy whip for House Democrats, says
the caucus is a ``fun group'' that meets ``anytime we can get a
photographer to come and give us some free publicity.'' Its sole
purpose, he says, is to ``allow members to fraternize about the
politics of having hair on your face.''
   Bonior confessed that he shaved off his 10-year-old beard
briefly during the Christmas holidays. ``My family hadn't seen me
for 10 years, so I shaved. They didn't like what they saw, so I
grew it back,'' he said.
   Beards may not be an endangered species, as Bonior claims, but
they have fallen on hard times. Washington is full of earnest,
clean-shaven yuppies. The Senate hasn't seen a beard since Philip
A. Hart, the liberal Democrat from Michigan, died in 1976. There
hasn't been a bearded president since Benjamin Harrison left office
in 1893.
   In the turbulent Sixties, beards enjoyed a brief renaissance as
symbols of antiwar liberalism, but Bonior says they are a
``non-ideological growth'' today.
   Bonior might be right. Although he, Dellums, Flake and Leland
are all liberal Democrats, the bearded Rohrabacher is a staunch
Reagan conservative who won a House seat last November with active
campaign support from Iran-Contra defendant Oliver L. North.
   ``The experts told me that if I had any chance of winning, I had
to shave my beard and stay away from Ollie North. I refused to do
either, and I won,'' Rohrabacher said.
   Another conservative California Republican, Rep. Robert K.
Dornan, shaved off his beard and won re-election handily. But when
liberal former Rep. Mike Lowry, D-Wash., tried the same trick in
his bid for a Senate seat last fall, he lost.
   ``I had my beard for six years,'' Lowry said in a telephone
interview from Seattle, where he is teaching college and
reassessing his political future.
   ``I had it so long I was becoming identified with it. I was
tired of being a Yasser Arafat look-alike. Also, my mother hated
it.''
   Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., shaved a beard he'd worn for six
months last year. ``During that time, I got more nasty mail over my
beard than over any other issue since I've been in Congress,'' he
said. ``Generally, they didn't like the way it looked, or thought
it was unclean.''
   Gejdenson, who intends to grow a new beard, believes the rise
and fall of their popularity has some mysterious connection with
the economy.
   ``When the stock market goes down, there are more beards, and
when the market goes up there are fewer beards,'' he observes.
``When I showed up for the 101st Congress, I was clean-shaven and
the economy was back up again.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Robert M. Andrews is an Associated Press
reporter in Washington who has sported a beard for the last 19
years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
