<DOCNO> AP890427-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AbortionDecision Bjt   04-27 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Decision, Bjt,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Breadth of Court's Abortion Ruling the Big Question Mark</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The future of abortion in America will be on
the Supreme Court's discussion agenda when its nine members gather
for a closed-door conference Friday morning.
   First item: Must the court, in resolving an abortion-regulation
controversy from Missouri, plunge into its landmark 1973 decision
that women have a constitutional right to end their pregnancies?
   Although Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist may conduct an
initial vote Friday and begin the opinion-writing process, the
court's final decision likely will not be announced until late June
or early July.
   Missouri officials and the Bush administration are urging the
court to overturn or curtail the 16-year-old ruling in Roe vs.
Wade. And while speculating about the Supreme Court's direction is
always tricky business, questions from the bench in Wednesday's
argument session indicated three key justices may be willing to
undertake a broad review of abortion rights.
   Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M.
Kennedy _ all appointees of former President Reagan _ pointedly
asked lawyers for both sides about the dimensions of abortion
rights.
   ``Do you say there is no fundamental right to decide whether to
have a child or not? A right to procreate?'' O'Connor asked the
administration's lawyer. ``Do you deny that the Constitution
protects that right?''
   Scalia asked the lawyer representing opponents of the Missouri
law, ``How can you derive (a fundamental right) without making a
determination as to whether the fetus is a human life or not?''
   The justice added, ``It is very hard to say it just as a matter
of basic principle that it must be a fundamental right unless you
make the determination that the organism that is destroyed is not a
human life.''
   Kennedy asked the administration's lawyer about a 1965 Supreme
Court decision striking down a state law that barred use of
contraceptives _ the high court's first enunciation of the
constitutional ``privacy'' right which served as the basis for Roe
vs. Wade.
   ``Does the (1965) case stand for the proposition that there is a
right to determine whether to procreate?'' Kennedy asked.
   Of the justices considered strong supporters of abortion rights
_ Harry A. Blackmun, William J. Brennan, Thurgood Marshall and John
Paul Stevens _ only Stevens participated fully in the session.
Brennan asked one question; Blackmun and Marshall none.
   Rehnquist and Justice Byron R. White, dissenters in and
consistent critics of Roe vs. Wade, each asked several questions
but seemed intent on giving the three junior justices as much time
as they needed.
   Their questions could have zeroed in on the particulars of the
Missouri law's regulations. Many of them did not.
   The court, however, still could resolve the Missouri case
without reconsidering Roe vs. Wade.
   Such a decision still would be read as a barometer of the
current justices' commitment to the 1973 ruling, but might not
affect many women outside Missouri. Higher stakes would be left for
a future case.
   But the possibility exists for a broader ruling, one that
includes in its scope a nation in which 1.5 million legal abortions
are performed each year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Carelli has covered the Supreme Court
for The Associated Press since 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890427-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Afghanistan     04-27 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Afghanistan,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviets In Bitter Exchange Over Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Soviet Union traded
charges of hypocrisy, lying and bad faith in a blistering finale to
three weeks of debate on Afghanistan in the Security Council.
   The meeting adjourned Wednesday without resolution and no
further meeting was scheduled.
   The debate marked the first full-fledged council discussion of
Afghanistan since January 1980, right after Soviet troops
intervened in Afghanistan, replacing one Marxist government with
another and staying on to help fight a Moslem insurrection.
   The session began April 11 and included more than 40 speakers,
all of them calling for a political settlement and
self-determination by the Afghan people.
   Ambassador Patricia Byrne, U.S. representative to the council,
told delegates Wednesday, ``It is the height, or should I say the
depth of hypocrisy for the representative of the Soviet Union to
claim that the regimes in Kabul and the U.S.S.R. are fulfilling
their obligations under the Geneva Accords of April 14, 1988, and
that the United States and Pakistan have failed to do so.
   ``The truth is precisely the opposite ... distortion and
falsehood will not work.
   ``The whole world knows full well who created the dreadful
situation by its invasion of Afghanistan. The Soviet Union has at
least withdrawn its troops but it is seeking to lay the blame for
the chaos and continued suffering at the feet of others.''
   Soviet Ambassador Alexander M. Belonogov earlier delivered an
extensive and stinging rebuke to the United States for arming the
Afghan guerrillas with weapons transported across the border from
Pakistan.
   ``The world community ... has formed a very clear idea about who
is hypocritical and who has been lying in this hall,'' he said,
jabbing his finger in the air for emphasis.
   Referring to U.S. arms being supplied to the rebels through
Pakistan, Belonogov gibed, ``We don't believe babies are borne by
storks or come from cabbage patches, so how did these arms from the
territory of Pakistan get there into Afghanistan?
   ``Did they fall out of the sky, or were they brought by some
other force?''
   Neither the United States nor Pakistan admitted supplying
weapons, including Stinger and Blowpipe missiles and other arms to
Afghan guerrillas.
   ``The United States is not setting the best example (of respect
for international agreements),'' Belonogov said during an hourlong
statement.
   ``By supplying the Afghan opposition with weapons on Pakistani
territory, the United States has thereby been pushing Pakistan
toward a violation of the bilateral agreement between Pakistan and
Afghanistan.''
   That U.N.-mediated agreement between the two west Asian
neighbors, guaranteed by Washington and Moscow, calls for
non-interference in domestic affairs of Pakistan and Afghanistan.
It also provided for the Soviet troop withdrawal, completed in
February.
   Afghanistan and the Soviet Union say Pakistan violated the
accords by arming and training Afghan rebels in Pakistan and
sending them into Afghanistan along with weapons convoys. They
claim the Pakistani military, intelligence units, logistics
officers and militia are involved _ both directly and indirectly _
in fighting within Afghanistan.
   Pakistan denies it and says Soviet supply of weapons to the
Kabul regime has continued the warfare and suffering in
Afghanistan. Most Afghans reject the Marxist government in Kabul,
Pakistan says.
   Pakistani Ambassador S. Shah Nawaz said in response to an Afghan
threat of retaliation issued in the council Monday that his
government will defend itself against any aggression from its
neighbor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
