<FIRST>r a PM-LottoLunacy     04-27 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lotto Lunacy,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lure of `Super-Mega-Jackpot' Fans Lottery Fever</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lottery Fever, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Why shouldn't a crack at the fattest jackpot in
North America create a ticket-buying frenzy? How else can you turn
a one dollar lottery chance into a $100 million payoff?
   ``The lure of great prizes fires people up. There's a kick of
anticipation,'' said Abe Kramer, a psychologist who counsels
compulsive gamblers in New York City. ``The bigger the prize the
better, even though they don't have a snowball's chance in hell of
winning.''
   Pennsylvania's Super 7 Lottery drawn Wednesday night was worth
more than $100 million, the world's largest prize outside Spain's
$159 million pot divvied up in last December.
   The Pennsylvania prize illustrates how popular lotteries have
become since New Hampshire opened its game in 1964.
   Lottery sales are expected to top $15 billion this year in 32
states and the District of Columbia, up from an estimated $14
billion last year. Sales in at least eight states exceed $1 billion.
   ``The lottery is the poor man's stock market. It let's you
fantasize about the lifestyles of the rich and famous,'' said J.
Blaine Lewis Jr., president of the North American Association of
State and Provincial Lotteries.
   For $1, players of Super 7 picked seven numbers from one to 80.
The winner must match them against 11 numbers drawn. The official
winning numbers were 06; 16; 24; 34; 35; 37; 40; 41; 45; 60; 71.
   The odds of winning were 9.6 million-to-one, and the pot grew
because there was no winner for six weeks.
   Tickets were sold at a rate of 500 a second. In a scene
reminiscent of a gold rush, rabid prospectors invaded Pennsylvania
by car, bus and plane to queue up. It was as if an entire state had
gone mad.
   ``It's a dream, the fantasy of getting rich, of never having to
work again,'' said Don Baucum, a professor of psychology at
Birmingham-Southern College in Alabama. ``People get to carry
around a little extra glow.''
   Part of the fascination was getting a piece of the action.
   ``Not many people really expect to win. But somebody's going to.
Everybody wants to be part of the fun,'' said Russ Gladieux, acting
director of the New York state lottery. ``It's generated a
super-mega-jackpot.''
   Gary Zurenda, owner of Ticket Plus Inc., in Wilkes-Barre, Pa.,
put in four extra phone lines and ran ads in newspapers for
out-of-staters. He charged $100 for a minimum order of 50 tickets,
twice the going rate.
   Madelyn Rose Wallace came in person, spending $796 for roundtrip
air fare from Houston to Pittsburgh. ``I had a vision a year ago
that I won the largest jackpot in jackpot history. This is my
chance,'' she said.
   Steve Harris of Phoenix, Ariz., jetted in for tickets. ``It's
only once in a lifetime that you get to participate in the largest
gambling action in the history of mankind,'' Harris said.
   Promoters bill lotteries as benign entertainment, but critics
say players can spend their life savings or write bad checks to
cover debts.
   ``There's a dramatic increase in lottery addicts,'' said Valerie
Lorenz, executive director of the National Center for Pathological
Gambling in Baltimore.
   ``Gambling used to be immoral, sinful and illegal, associated
with greed and crime. The lotteries are promoting it as an act of
civic responsibility because it supports education, transportation
and elderly programs,'' she said.
   Lotteries were introduced as a way to raise money without
raising taxes. In a way of using a vice to fund a virtue, lottery
proceeds pay for senior citizens programs in Pennsylvania,
education in Ohio and California, and economic development in Iowa.
   But states pocket an average of 35 percent of lottery sales, and
the games account for only a small percentage of a state's budget.
   ``The lottery is a rather inefficient and ineffective method of
general revenue. But nobody wants to raise taxes. That's a dirty
word,'' said Roy Kaplan of the Florida Institute of Technology, who
has studied state lotteries for 20 years.
   ``I look at the lottery as the flip side of work. Gambling gives
the tantalizing thought of achieving success without work,'' Kaplan
said. ``It's an innocent diversion for a few days.''
   The sheer magnitude of a $100 million treasure, and the chance
to chase rainbows and get rich instantly has a strong American
appeal. But while a dollar may make you rich, it can also cost you
your privacy.
   Glen Stanley, a coal miner, won $5.6 million in the West
Virginia lottery in 1986 and spent $6,000 for a chain-link fence
adorned with a ``no soliciting'' sign. One stranger asked him for
$10,000 so he could buy new cars for his kids. A woman asked for
$10,500 to have her breast enlarged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
