<FIRST>r a PM-WitnessWedding     04-27 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Witness Wedding,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused Of Murder Marries Potential Witness Against Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANSFIELD, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of murder and a potential
witness against him held hands through the jail bars that separated
them as they were married, and now she cannot be forced to testify
against him.
   Jacqueline Jonet Thomas on Wednesday married Cedric Burton, who
is charged with first-degree murder in the death of a car salesman.
The victim was kidnapped during a test drive, robbed and shot.
   DeSoto Parish District Attorney Don Burkett, who tried
unsuccessfully to get the courts to forbid the ceremony until after
the trial, said Burton will still be tried for the death of Michael
Wade Langton.
   ``It would not be appropriate for me to comment on the evidence
in a case before it is tried, but the marriage of the witness will
have absolutely no effect on the case going forward,'' Burkett
said. ``It is fixed for trial on June 26, and it will go to trial
on June 26.''
   Burkett had said earlier that Thomas was living with Burton when
Langton was slain, and her testimony could destroy Burton's alibi
against charges of murder, aggravated kidnapping and armed robbery.
   Under state law, someone cannot be compelled to testify against
a spouse.
   Thomas got a marriage license Tuesday at the parish clerk's
office. On Wednesday, state District Judge Claude R. Sledge waived
the required 72-hour waiting period. The couple said their vows a
few hours later before a Baptist clergyman.
   Two jailers served as witnesses and other jail employees
gathered around for the double-ring ceremony.
   The couple won the right to marry April 12, when the 2nd Circuit
Court of Appeal in Shreveport upheld Sledge's ruling that the state
lacked the authority to prevent someone from marrying.
   Jail Administrator Jerry Lowe spent several days calling
ministers before he found one willing to marry the couple.
   Burton said on April 19 that he had changed his mind and wanted
to postpone the wedding. But after talking with Thomas last
weekend, he told Lowe he was ready to proceed with the marriage.
</TEXT>
