<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Iran-Contra     04-27 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Iran-Contra,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Intelligence Committee to Investigate Non-Release of Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Intelligence Committee will try to
determine why congressional Iran-Contra investigators were not
given crucial Reagan administration documents that turned up during
the trial of Oliver North.
   The documents, which were missed during a supposedly thorough
search of administration files during the panel's 1987
investigation, portray far more clearly than previously known the
involvement of Reagan and then-Vice President George Bush in aid to
the Nicaraguan rebels throughout 1985.
   Three former members of the Senate investigating panel said in a
letter to Intelligence Committee Chairman David Boren, D-Okla., and
Vice Chairman William Cohen, R-Maine, that a quick staff review
found four documents introduced as evidence in North's trial that
they had never seen before.
   Two other documents released at the trial are similar to ones in
the committee's files, but include important attachments or
notations that are missing from the committee versions.
   One document, an April 25, 1985, memo from then-national
security adviser Robert McFarlane, recommends that Reagan telephone
Honduran President Roberto Suazo to reassure him of U.S. backing
for the Contras. Missing from the congressional copy is the
notation, ``cc Vice President,'' apparently showing that Bush was
sent a copy of the memo.
   ``These six documents are sufficient to raise questions about
the procedures followed by the executive branch in providing
documents to the Iran-contra Committee and the completeness of its
compliance with agreements on the provision of documents,'' the
letter stated.
   The request was signed by Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine, and Sens. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, and Warren
Rudman, R-N.H., the chairman and vice chairman of the Senate
Iran-Contra panel.
   Boren, in a statement, promised to ``look at this matter
expeditiously and in a businesslike, non-political manner.''
   Responding for the Bush administration, White House Counsel C.
Boyden Gray wrote Mitchell on Wednesday: ``We have confidence that
the last administration followed the agreed procedures (for
releasing the material) and that its representatives will be able
to address your concerns. We, of course endeavor to be as helpful
as we can.''
   The letter from the senators said some of the documents contain
key evidence about the way U.S. officials conducted policy in
Central America in 1985 ``and raise questions regarding ...
possible efforts to circumvent the provisions of the law'' which
barred direct or indirect U.S. aid to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   One of the documents, a Feb. 20, 1985, memo from North to
McFarlane, states it is ``very clear'' that the law forbids any
direct or indirect military aid for the Contras. That is at odds
with testimony by North and other administration during the
congressional hearings that they had believed they had found a
loophole to get around the law.
   A similar request for an investigation was made two weeks ago by
Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., who was chairman of the House
Iran-Contra committee. An aide to Hamilton said Wednesday that he
had not yet received a response to his request, which was directed
to Gray.
   Congressional investigators ultimately concluded in November
1987 that a ``cabal of ... zealots'' in the Reagan administration
seized control of policy in the affair which sent weapons to Iran
and profits from the sales to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Despite the documents released in the North case, former
committee counsel Mark Belnick, now a New York attorney, said he
does not believe that conclusion would have been much different had
the documents been turned over.
   ``The documents were clearly called for, we would like to have
had them and they would have led to additional questions,'' he
said. ``But if this is the sum and substance ... they wouldn't have
materially changed any of the conclusions'' reached by
investigators, he said.
   Among documents which the congressional panels did not receive:
   _A Feb. 19, 1985, memo for Reagan outlining a plan to step up
U.S. aid to Honduras in return for its support of the Contras, and
proposing that an emissary go to Honduran President Suazo and
``very privately'' outline the link between U.S. aid and help for
the rebels. Approval of the proposal is initialed, ``RR.''
   _A memo dated Feb. 20, 1985, from North and NSC official Raymond
Burghardt to McFarlane noting that the emissary to Honduras would
be needed to keep the request to aid the Contras secret from
Congress.
   _An Oct. 30, 1985, memo from North to McFarlane outlining plans
for reconnaissance flights over Nicaragua and mentioning plans to
airdrop two recoilless rifles to the rebels.
   _A Feb. 22, 1985 memo outlining plans for delivery to Suazo of a
Reagan letter promising support for Honduras if needed against
Nicaraguan military attack and saying, ``I hope that your
government will do all in its power to support those who struggle
for freedom and democracy.''
</TEXT>
