<FIRST>r w PM-Yost-OilSpill     04-27 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yost-Oil Spill,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Chief Says Valdez Was in Danger of Sinking After Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard commandant says the Exxon
Valdez likely would have sunk and created a worse problem if its
captain had succeeded in rocking the giant tanker off a reef where
it spilled 11 million gallons of oil.
   Adm. Paul A. Yost also praised Coast Guard Cmdr. Steve McCall,
who radioed a warning to Captain Joseph Hazelwood: ``I wouldn't
recommend doing much wiggling.''
   Yost told a news conference Wednesday that was sound advice for
the vessel that rested atop a pinnacle of reef in Alaska's Prince
William Sound with 42 million gallons of oil still in its hull.
   A transcript of the March 24 conversation between McCall and
Hazelwood was released on Tuesday after a Freedom of Information
request from the Anchorage Daily News.
   ``It's probable that had the ship gotten off the reef, it would
have sunk in position where it was in about 300 feet of water,''
Yost told a news conference.
   The remaining oil was transferred off the ship before it was
moved several days after the incident.
   It would have been much more difficult to remove the oil had the
ship sunk, Yost said.
   ``I don't know whether (Hazelwood's action) was
ill-considered,'' Yost said in response to a question, ``but I
think Commander McCall ... gave the captain some very sound advice.
I hope what (Hazelwood) ultimately did was in response to that
advice which was not to jerk that thing off the pinnacle.''
   The transcript showed that McCall warned Hazelwood to ``take it
slow and easy'' after the captain said he there was ``a little
problem here with the third mate, but we're working our way off the
reef.''
   The transcript shows that McCall warned, ``Before you make any
drastic attempt to get away, make sure you don't, you know, start
doing any ripping.'' He added that the tide was still rising.
   Hazelwood is charged with operating the vessel while
intoxicated, reckless endangerment and negligent discharge of
pollution into the water, all misdemeanors.
   Exxon earlier had estimated that 10.1 million gallons of crude
oil had spilled from the ship. State officials said it was 11.2
million and Yost confirmed it was more than 11 million.
   Exxon said Hazelwood was not on the bridge when the ship ran
aground but had turned over the tanker to his third mate, Gregory
Cousins, who was qualified to operate the ship but not licensed to
steer it through the sound.
   Yost said Hazelwood's reference to a ``little problem ... with
the third mate'' may have only been a reference to the ship's
having run aground rather than an indication of any other problem
with the third mate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
