<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     04-27 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Appointees Taking Over Some Career Civil Service Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a House panel dealing with
federal workers is calling on the Bush administration to reduce the
number of mid-level government jobs that are given to political
appointees.
   Rep. Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn., issued the plea on Wednesday along
with a congressional report that shows political appointees are
taking over mid-level federal jobs traditionally held by career
civil servants.
   Sikorski chairman of the human resources subcommittee of the
Committee on Post Office and Civil Service, released a General
Accounting Office report showing that 64 political appointees in 18
agencies had recently been converted to career status.
   ``The increasing number of conversions of political appointees
into career positions is troubling, especially where ... (they)
infiltrate mid-level management positions traditionally held by
long-time civil servants,'' Sikorski said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Bill Endorsed by House Interior Committee</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Interior Committee has sent to the
full House legislation to improve the transportation of coal from
mines to distant power plants through pipelines.
   The committee approved the bill, the Coal Pipeline Act, on a
22-13 vote on Wednesday. It allows coal pipeline companies approved
by the interior secretary to use the federal power of eminent
domain to gain access to land so they can lay pipes.
   The technology has existed for years to use pipes to transport
coal mixed with water. The bill, which has yet to be taken up in
the Senate, covers such ``slurry'' pipelines as well as those in
the future using other media, such as natural gas, to transport
coal.
   ``This legislation will increase our energy security, create new
jobs, and provide much needed competition in the coal
transportation market,'' said committee Chairman Morris Udall,
D-Ariz.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>FCC Allows Phone Company to Test Cable TV System</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California firm has won permission to build
a coaxial cable TV system and permission to test a state-of-the-art
fiber-optic system that will allow customers to order movies every
15 minutes by phone.
   Wednesday's ruling by the Federal Communications Commission was
challenged immediately by the National Cable Television
Association, which said it appears to violate federal rules
generally barring telephone companies from the cable TV business.
   The FCC, affirming a preliminary decision last year, will let
General Telephone Co. build and operate the coaxial (bundled copper
wire) cable system in the Los Angeles suburb of Cerritos. GTE of
California also provides phone service to Cerritos.
   The FCC said the permission was justified because there had been
no adequate bids submitted to the city of Cerritos for cable
service except from General Telephone. GTE is leasing the system to
Apollo CableVision to provide programming.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
