<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Highers, Share Prices In Tokyo Hit Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged up against the Japanese yen
Thursday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended at
yet another high.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
190.15 points for a 33,434.93-point record close Wednesday, added
another 65.90 points, or 0.20 percent, to finish at 33,500.83.
   The dollar closed at 132.05 yen, up 0.58 yen from the previous
day's 131.47-yen finish. It started at 131.90 yen and edged up
while ranging from 131.70 yen to 132.25 yen.
   Traders said the dollar opened higher in Tokyo following its
strength in New York, where a release of U.S. economic growth
figures boosted dollar-buying.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Wednesday the nation's
economy, as measured by its gross national product, expanded at a
robust annual rate of 5.5 percent during the first three months of
1989, the fastest pace in more than a year.
   Japanese investors were reluctant to make further purchase of
the currency due to speculation about an interest rate hike in
Japan as well as the Bank of Japan's market intervention if the
dollar rises further, said a trader with a major commercial bank in
Tokyo.
   Many investors are speculating that the central bank might raise
the nation's interest rate depending on the consumer price index
for March, which is to be released Friday.
   But a trader with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking anonymously, said
bullish sentiment for the dollar remains a basic trend.
   On the stock exchange, a moderate gain in the market's main
barometer followed a similar trend on overseas markets overnight,
dealers said.
   The Nikkei slowed down as some participants sold issues for
profit taking, said a dealer with a major securities firm in Tokyo.
