<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Prostate     04-27 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prostate,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Raises Questions about Common Prostate Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most common kind of prostate operation may not
be as effective as traditional surgery for relieving prostate woes
in older men, a study published today concludes.
   A form of surgery called transurethral prostatectomy has largely
replaced traditional open surgery to cut away enlarged prostate
glands. In the newer procedure, surgeons push a thin tube up the
urethra to the prostate, where a cutting loop slices the excess
tissue. Patients recover more quickly and have less pain with this
approach.
   However, new data from three countries suggests that men are
substantially more likely to require a second operation after the
transurethral procedure.
   In addition, the researchers said their data ``raise the
possibility'' that men are more likely to die in the years
immediately after the transurethral operation, although they said
more study is necessary to be sure this is true.
   The study, directed by Dr. Noralou P. Roos of the University of
Manitoba in Winnipeg, was published in today's New England Journal
of Medicine. It was based on the records of 36,703 men undergoing
prostate surgery in Denmark, 5,284 in England and 12,090 in Canada.
   The need for second operations ranged from 12 percent to 16
percent of patients in the three countries undergoing transurethral
surgery, compared with 2 percent to 5 percent of those getting open
surgery.
   The death rate during eight years of followup was higher in the
transurethral patients in all three countries. This difference was
most carefully analyzed in the Canadian patients, and the
researchers found that those getting the transurethral procedure
there had a 45 percent higher death rate. The excess of deaths was
due mainly to more heart attacks.
   In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Sheldon Greenfield of New
England Medical Center said the study ``does not provide convincing
evidence that open prostatectomy carries less risk than
transurethral prostatectomy.''
   He said men might have been more likely to get the transurethral
procedure if they already had heart disease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
