<DOCNO> AP890427-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Quake     04-27 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Quake,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Hits In Pacific Ocean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake centered in the Pacific ocean
shook islands south of Tokyo early today but no injuries or damage
were reported, the Central Meteorological Agency said.
   The agency said the quake, centered about 50 miles under the
seabed and 420 miles south of Tokyo, registered 6.4 on the Richter
scale. It said there was no danger of tsunami, or tidal waves.
   An agency official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
that on the nearest inhabited island, Chichi Jima, the quake
registered 2 on the Japanese scale of 7, meaning slight movement of
sliding doors was noticeable.
   A tremor measuring two on the Japanese scale means extremely
feeble shocks only felt by those at rest.
   The Richter scale measures the magnitude of a quake at its
epicenter, according to ground motion as recorded on seismographs.
An earthquake of 6 is considered ``severe,'' capable of widespread
damage near the epicenter.
   The Japanese scale measures the intensity of an earthquake at a
particular location and is not convertible to the Richter scale.
</TEXT>
