<FIRST>r a PM-AlteredResume     04-27 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Altered Resume,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Administrator Who Used False Resumes Sentenced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PETERSBURG, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who used false resumes in a
cross-country government career has been barred from taking a
government job for seven years and sentenced to 90 days in jail for
deceiving an Alaskan village.
   At his sentencing Wednesday, Carl Keyser Jr., 34, also was
ordered to pay $18,000 restitution. He was convicted of
first-degree theft stemming from his three-month tenure as city
administrator of Kake, a tiny fishing and timber village in
southeast Alaska about 100 miles south of Juneau.
   He pleaded no contest in February to the felony charge alleging
he took $28,680 in salary, benefits and expenses before he was
fired in December.
   Superior Court Judge Thomas Schultz of Ketchikan placed Keyser
on probation for seven years, ordered him not to accept any
government jobs during that time, and told him to write letters of
apology to Kake and Pikeville, Ky., where he also briefly worked.
   Keyser had listed academic degrees he hadn't received and jobs
he hadn't held on his resume, officials have said.
   District Attorney Mark Ells said a Kentucky charge of theft by
deception will be dismissed at the request of the Pikeville
prosecutor. Keyser sent the city $707 in restitution Tuesday,
closing that case, Ells said.
   The Pikeville restitution represented expense money Keyser was
paid in August during a six-day stint as city manager before he
resigned amid allegations he faked his resume.
   Keyser already has served 60 days in jail and asked to have the
30 remaining days waived, saying he had been unable to find a job
since he was released on bail.
   Schultz, however, said 90 days was not a harsh sentence
considering the crime. ``This is pretty reprehensible conduct,''
the judge said of Keyser's employment record.
   Keyser apologized for his conduct. He said he obtained the jobs
by lying so he could support his wife and four young daughters.
   ``What I did here was wrong,'' he said. ``I lied on my resume
because I needed a job to feed my family, and instead of doing it
the right way ... I took too many shortcuts.''
   Outside the courthouse, however, he denied allegations that he
obtained other jobs under false pretenses.
   Public defender Mary Treiber said Keyser was considering going
to Seattle to find employment.
   ``If Mr. Keyser stays in Alaska, it is unlikely he will be able
to pay the entire amount (of restitution), even in seven years,''
Treiber said.
   Kake residents became suspicous of Keyser shortly after he
arrived to take the $44,000-a-year administrator's job in October.
   He bought a luxurious $66,000 double mobile home, rifles and
1,000 rounds of ammunition with city money, and refused to release
his resume for public inspection.
   A police records check revealed the outstanding Kentucky warrant
in December and he was arrested.
   Interviews with prosecutors and city officials in several states
revealed that at least 19 of Keyser's jobs since 1980 were with
city or county governments. Records and the interviews showed
Keyser used false information to obtain at least 11 of the jobs.
   Keyser, a native of Huntington, W.Va., previously was placed on
a year's probation after pleading guilty to a misdemeanor perjury
charge in Oak Hill, Fla. The charge alleged he used false
information to get hired as Oak Hill police chief. He was fired
after four months when the discrepancies in his resume were
reported in the news media.
</TEXT>
