<FIRST>r a PM-Heroes     04-27 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heroes,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kentucky Man Among 18 Heroes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CASSANDRA BURRELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Clayton Bailey Jr. says he stripped to
his underwear and jumped into near-freezing water in the Tennessee
River to grab a deck hand who had fallen off a barge because ``I
just hated to see a man die.''
   The Paducah, Ky., man was among 17 Americans and one Canadian
recognized Wednesday by the Carnegie Hero Fund Commission. A $2,500
grant was awarded to each hero or their survivors.
   Bailey, a business manager for E.M. Bailey Co., his family's oil
business, said he had just walked out onto the company's river dock
in Calvert City, Ky., on Jan. 23, 1988, when a group of frightened
men told him 20-year-old Rockey A. Jobe had fallen into the river.
   Heavy clothing meant to protect dock workers from cold weather
was pulling Jobe further into the 38-degree water, and a 7 to 10
mph current was moving him toward midstream.
   Bailey stripped, grabbed a two-foot piece of plastic wrapping on
the ground and swam about 150 feet to Jobe.
   After pushing the plastic under the man, Bailey grabbed a chain
dock workers had lowered to the water from a crane and prepared to
be pulled to safety. Seconds later, however, the crane's boom
struck a utility pole, and Bailey, fearing electrocution, released
the chain.
   Struggling against the current, Bailey eventually reached the
bank, and several other men used rope to lift Jobe out of the
water. Jobe quickly recovered.
   ``I had been around the river and I knew I could stand cold
water at least for a little bit, and I just thought I could get to
him,'' Bailey, 42, said in a telephone interview Wednesday. ``I
just didn't want to stand around and watch a man die. ... I just
hated to see a man die.''
   The Carnegie Hero Fund Commission has recognized 37 people so
far this year and 7,331 since it was founded in 1904 by
industrialist Andrew Carnegie.
   Wednesday's other heroes were:
   _Michael J. Ruthemeyer, 26, of Houston and Gary C. Williams Sr.,
28, of Sugar Land, Texas, who pulled a father and son from a
burning car in Houston on April 27.
   _Eric J. Prindle, 35, of Xenia, Ohio, who pulled a woman from a
burning car in Xenia on June 25, 1988.
   _Geronimo M. Barreras, 37, of Mesquite, N.M., who rescued a
wounded woman from a man firing a semi-automatic pistol in Mesquite
on Dec. 2, 1987.
   _Thomas M. Booth, 35, of Cordova, Tenn., and C. Arthur Dimond,
39, of Pittsburgh, who saved Dimond's two children from drowning in
the Atlantic Ocean at Naggs Head, N.C. on July 7, 1988. Dimond
drowned.
   _Paul A. Thompson, 26, of Mount Vernon, N.Y., who saved a man
from a burning apartment in Mount Vernon on Sept. 4, 1988.
   _Michael S. Weatherhead, 32, of Jefferson, Maine, who pulled a
girl from the swift current of a stream in Jefferson on May 3, 1988.
   _John E. Roach, 43, of Tooele, Utah, who pulled three women from
a burning car in Tooele on Oct. 8, 1988.
   _Truman E. Nickell, 58, of Lebanon, Mo., who saved his
granddaughter and another girl from drowning in the Gulf of Mexico
near Galveston, Texas, on July 14, 1988.
   _Gerald Thomas Grimm, 30, of Morristown, N.J., who saved a
police officer struggling with a man who attempted to grab his gun
in Ridgefield Park, N.J., on Feb. 4, 1988.
   _Paul B. Dostie, 42, of Haverhill, Mass., and James G. Scott,
40, of Newburyport, Mass., who pulled a man out of a burning car in
Haverhill on Dec. 17, 1988.
   _Salvatore Silvestri, 36, of Toronto, who helped save a man who
had fallen off a chartered boat on Lake Ontario on Aug. 2, 1986.
Silvestri drowned.
   _Craig Wrolsen, 33, of West Camp, N.Y., and Jonathan D. Nitkin,
27, and Richard A. Bates, 29, both of Fort Lauderdale, Fla., who
helped pull a man out of the Atlantic Ocean near
Lauderdale-by-the-Sea, Fla. on March 24, 1988.
</TEXT>
