<FIRST>r a PM-ChildrenDecapitated     04-27 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children Decapitated,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Charged With Two Counts of Murder; Children Decapitated</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GILLETTE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who believed her children were
clones was charged with decapitating the two baby girls, according
to authorities.
   Laura Lee Rice, 37, told authorities she had to kill the
children to get her real babies back, according to a complaint
sworn out against her.
   She pleaded innocent by reason of mental illness to two counts
of first-degree murder on Wednesday and was ordered to the state
hospital in Evanston to undergo psychiatric testing.
   Sheriff's deputies on Monday found the bodies of 15-month-old
Danielle Lee Rice and 4-month-old Joan Rice in a mobile home south
of Gillette, which is in the northeast part of the state.
   The deputies were summoned to the trailer Monday evening by
Daniel Runyon, the girls' father. Runyon told the deputies that a
homicide had been committed in his mobile home.
   Asked how he knew, Runyon replied, ``I saw my daughter's head in
a plastic bag.''
   Runyon told deputies that Rice had said that ``Medussa had made
her do it.''
   At the mobile home the deputies confronted Rice, who told them
she had received a telephone call from a woman who told her she
``would have to kill the look-alike chidren'' if she wanted her
real children back, said Investigator Monty Trenary in a complaint
sworn out against Rice.
   ``The defendant further stated ... that she needed to cut the
look-alikes' arms and heads off and put them in different places so
that her children may be brought back in two days,'' Trenary said.
   Deputies found the children's bodies in plastic bags hidden in a
closet and beneath a crib. The complaint said Rice admitted
committing the killings with a large butcher knife.
   Sheriff Byron Oedekoven said the woman has several aliases and
that Rice may not be her legal name.
