<FIRST>r p PM-WyomingElection     04-27 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wyoming Election,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republican Wins Wyoming House Seat Vacated By Cheney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican faithful, shaken by election
losses in Indiana and Alabama earlier this year, saw GOP hopeful
Craig Thomas win a surprisingly easy victory to fill Wyoming's only
seat in Congress.
   Thomas, a state representative, defeated Democrat John Vinich in
Wednesday's special election by more than 13,000 votes.
   Even Thomas, 56, was amazed by the victory margin in the race
for the seat relinquished by Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
   ``I thought it would be close, for no other reason than, of
course, our campaign started 40 days ago, or less, and the other
campaign has been going off and on for nearly a year-and-a-half,''
said Thomas.
   Unofficial returns showed him with 74,258 votes, or 52 percent,
to Vinich's 60,821 votes, or 43 percent. Independent Craig McCune
received 5,921 votes, while Daniel Johnson, an independent who
espoused white separatist views, got 500.
   Thomas credited his victory to the voters' desire to maintain a
conservative approach in Washington.
   ``I think largely it was an expression of continuation of the
splendid job that's been done by Dick Cheney,'' he said. ``And a
voice for continued representation in that mode, of a conservative
voice in Washington for Wyoming.''
   Vinich, a state senator, had won the Democratic nomination for
the House seat after a 13-month campaign that ended with his losing
to U.S. Sen. Malcolm Wallop by just 1,322 votes last November.
   Vinich's widespread name recognition was a decided plus for the
Democrat, but in the House campaign the Republicans constantly
referred to him as a free-spending liberal beholden to out-of-state
labor groups.
   Indeed, labor groups contributed more than 80 percent of
Vinich's campaign funds. But the Democrat denounced the Republican
charges and countered by portraying Thomas as a pawn of the
national GOP, which appeared desperate for a victory after losing
special congressional elections in Indiana and Alabama.
   Vinich, 38, ran behind as the returns came in and never
recovered, winning just four of the state's 23 counties. In an
interview from his home, Vinich blamed the loss on voters who
stayed home.
   ``Close to 60,000 voters that didn't vote in this election ...
voted last November. That's where the difference was,'' he said.
``We just didn't get all the voters out that we hoped would have
voted.''
</TEXT>
