<FIRST>r w PM-FusionHearing 1stLd-Writethru a0456 04-27 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0456,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Fusion Researchers To Work With Federal Scientists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 14th graf pvs, bgng He said, with Oregon
researchers reporting successful experiment; picks up 15th graf pvs, Rep.
Marilyn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal scientists will monitor the operation
of a cold fusion experiment in an attempt to verify that University
of Utah researchers have captured the power of the sun in a test
tube.
   University of Utah chemist Stanley Pons testified Wednesday
before the House Science Committee that scientists from the Los
Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico will visit his campus to
watch the operation of a tabletop fusion cell.
   Later, Pons told the committee, the cell will be dismantled and
taken back to Los Alamos by the federal scientists.
   Pons and his collaborator, Martin Fleischmann of the University
of Southampton in England, arranged for the demonstration in an
effort to calm skepticism in the science community that the
room-temperature fusion apparatus actually works.
   Testimony by Pons and Fleischmann was followed by comments from
seven scientists at other university and federal laboratories who
told of great doubts among researchers about the Utah results.
   Mike Saltmarsh, head of the fusion energy program at the Oak
Ridge National Laboratory, said all of the federal laboratories had
tried to replicate the Utah cold fusion results.
   ``The results have all been negative,'' said Saltmarsh. ``We
have seen no heat'' generated by the process.
   The Utah delegation before the committee also included
University of Utah president Chase Peterson, who urged that the
government move swiftly to provide federal funds for the cold
fusion research.
   Other scientists who testified, however, cautioned against
federal support until the process has been verified.
   Pons and Fleischmann received a generally warm reception by the
science committee, but did face some sharp questioning about why so
many other laboratories have not been able to verify their
experiment.
   Pons' announcement of the Los Alamos participation came after
Rep. Sid Morrison, R-Wash., asked if the Utah experiment could be
performed before independent observers.
   ``We have 19 experiments being set up now,'' said Pons. One of
these, he said, will be monitored by the Los Alamos scientists.
   Committee members also asked why some other laboratories have
not been able to get details needed to replicate the Utah
experiment, and Fleischmann replied: ``We are very happy to tell
people how we have been able to do it.''
   He said, however, that those who don't succeed should ``publish
in full'' reports of their failures.
   Two researchers at Portland State University in Oregon reported
a successful experiment on Monday in which results of the cold
fusion experiment were duplicated using specifications and
materials described in an article by Pons and Fleischmann.
   Physics professor John Dash and graduate student Patrick Keefe
said ``at least'' 100 times more energy was produced than was used
to start the experiment, with the energy burst occurring in the
first second.
   Rep. Marilyn Lloyd, D-Tenn., noted at Monday's hearing that
reports of the Utah experiment have indicated the heat produced is
at a low level. She asked if they could achieve a ``useful
temperature'' with the reaction.
   ``We've had a cell warm up to the boiling point,'' said
Fleischmann. But he said to scale up to a useful level ``raises
many new problems.''
   ``We think it's feasible, but it will require a very high
effort,'' he said.
   Fleischmann and Pons spent about $100,000 of their own money to
develop the tabletop fusion cell, but they said to scale up to a
larger size will cost about 10 times more, and to produce useful
energy ``would cost millions.''
   Peterson urged the committee to provide federal funds to help
set up a fusion research center at the University of Utah. He said
the state already has allocated $5 million and another $1 million
has been raised from private sources.
   ``What level of funding do you believe is needed?'' asked Rep.
George E. Brown Jr., D-Calif.
   ``The figure that comes to mind is $25 million,'' said Peterson.
``We should move promptly. We should have proposals within a week.''
   Other scientists who testified, however, urged the committee not
rush into support of the effort.
   ``We need at least two months to evaluate the significance of
this process,'' said Steven Jones, a Brigham Young University
fusion researcher.
   Fusion research could be hurt if federal money were put into the
Utah effort before it is proven, said George Miley, a fusion expert
from the University of Illinois, Urbana.
   ``A failure could set fusion research back by years,'' he said.
``I urge us to not overreact and put all our eggs in one basket.''
</TEXT>
