<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-Richards     04-27 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Richards,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush: Ann Richards Was Right</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maybe, President Bush says, Ann Richards
was right.
   The Texas treasurer had ridiculed Bush at last summer's
Democratic National Convention, saying he had been ``born with a
silver foot in his mouth.''
   Bush referred to her remark after he flubbed a line in his
speech Wednesday to a joint session of the Texas Legislature.
   ``You know, I've been thinking about it. Ann Richards was
right,'' Bush said to appreciative laughter and applause.
   ``Look, I kept putting that silver foot in my mouth all along
the way,'' he said. ``But the bottom line is, when they ask,
`Where's George?' _ say he's in Austin, among friends, and very
proud to be back.''
   Ms. Richards, who had a front-row seat for the president's
address, wore the foot-shaped silver pin that Bush previously sent
her.
   ``I thought it was appropriate that I wear it today. When a
gentleman sends you jewelry and he comes to town, well, you want to
be sure and wear it.''
   Bush devoted much of his address to reminiscences about his 1948
move to Texas and his deep affection for the state.
   Raised in Connecticut and owner of a home in Kennebunkport,
Maine, Bush took some ribbing from Democrats during the 1988
campaign over his claim to Texas, where his address now is a
Houston hotel.
   ``Let me just say a few words about what it means to be a Texan.
My credentials,'' Bush said. ``I have my driver's license here. I
have my Texas hunting license here. And somewhere, my voter
registration slip.
   ``And it is true, I like Kennebunkport. But I am a Texan. I just
want to clear the air and say a few words about that.''
   Unlike Alamo hero Davy Crockett, Bush said, he didn't ride to
Texas on a horse but in a red Studebaker.
   ``I'll admit it. I didn't know if a chicken fried steak was a
chicken fried like a steak or a steak that tasted like a chicken.
But I've learned,'' he said.
</TEXT>
