<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0720EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TankerAdrift     04-27 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Adrift,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crippled Exxon Tanker Arrives in Port Angeles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Exxon tanker loaded with 22 million gallons of
oil lost power and drifted for nearly seven hours before it was
towed into harbor early today to undergo engine repairs, a Coast
Guard spokesman said.
   The 810-foot Exxon Philadelphia had drifted away from land, in
an area without reefs and in water 600 feet deep. Seas were calm
and winds were mild.
   Coast Guard Petty Officer Michael Cobb said the ship arrived at
Port Angeles at about 1 a.m. today, under tow by a tugboat. Two
other tugboats were dispatched and traveled alongside the tanker in
case of problems, Cobb said.
   The U.S. Coast Guard and the Canadian Coast Guard also sent
ships and planes to monitor the situation and to be available in
case of an emergency. Cobb said it may take a couple of days to
repair the damage to the tanker's propulsion system.
   The single-hulled tanker was about nine miles off Cape Flattery
and 12 miles west of the entrance to the Strait of Juan de Fuca
when a boiler tube failed about 8:30 a.m. Wednesday, shutting down
the propulsion system, said Joe Tucker of Exxon in Valdez, Alaska.
The crew of 20 never was in danger, Tucker said.
   The incident occurred about a month after the tanker Exxon
Valdez ran aground near Valdez, dumping 11.2 million gallons of
crude oil into Prince William Sound.
   The Philadelphia, built in 1970, was inspected in a shipyard a
month ago, Tucker said.
   The tanker left the Alaska pipeline terminal at Valdez early
Sunday to deliver crude oil to a refinery in Anacortes, about 65
miles north of Seattle, said Tucker.
   It carried 532,862 barrels of oil, or 22.38 million gallons,
according to the Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation in
Valdez.
</TEXT>
