<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     04-27 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>1 Killed, 32 Wounded In Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers today shot and killed one
Palestinian and wounded 32 in clashes in the occupied lands, Arab
reports said.
   Also today, an aide said Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir will not
offer an alternative to his election proposal for the occupied
lands now that it has been rejected by prominent Palestinians there.
   Hospital officials said Imad Muhammad Harbieh, 20, of the Askar
refugee camp near Nablus died of a gunshot wound to the chest. Arab
reporters said he was shot after troops trying to enter the camp
opened fire to disperse several masked youths throwing stones and
empty bottles.
   Twenty-six Palestinians, including an 11-year-old boy hit in the
left shoulder, were wounded by gunfire in a half-dozen clashes in
the Gaza Strip and six Palestinians were wounded in the West Bank,
Arab reports said.
   The army, which does not include victims treated for injuries
and released, said only three Palestinians were wounded in the West
Bank. It had no information on the death or the Gaza clashes,
spokesmen said.
   Palestinians observed a general strike to express solidarity
with their brethren killed in the nearly 17-month uprising against
Israeli occupation.
   The strike came a day after three Palestinian youths were shot
to death and about 60 wounded, most in Gaza.
   The deaths raised to 451 the number of Palestinians killed in
the uprising. Eighteen Israelis also have died during the unrest.
   On Wednesday, 83 local Palestinians issued the first formal
response to Shamir's election plan. They rejected the idea of
balloting before Israel withdrew its troops from occupied areas.
   Shamir's proposal calls for elections to be held to select
representatives to negotiate with Israel on an interim solution to
the occupied lands. The aim of the talks would be to agree on an
autonomy scheme for Palestinian self-rule in the occupied lands.
   Palestinians fear the temporary solution would become permanent.
   ``This is the best program we can suggest to them,'' said Shamir
spokesman Yossi Ahimeir. He said Shamir didn't view the rejection
as final and would ask U.S. officials to press Palestinians to
reconsider.
   Shamir was quoted by Israel radio as telling an audience
Wednesday night that his proposals were ``generous and logical''
and that Palestinians would be ``mistaken'' if they thought they
could hold out for more later.
   In taped remarks from the same gathering broadcast by army
radio, Shamir said: ``We have heard an announcement from some of
our neighbors that they reject our proposals. I hope this is not
their last word.''
   The Palestinians insisted on an international peace conference
with participation of the PLO, proposals Shamir has rejected. They
did not rule out elections entirely but said balloting should be
one step in a process toward an overall settlement that they want
to end in statehood.
   In a leaflet distributed today, the clandestine PLO-backed
Unified National Leadership of the Uprising turned down Shamir's
plan. ``Our people categorically reject the U.S.-backed plan and
the attempts to market it to the Palestinians and the Arabs,'' it
said.
   Underground leaders demanded in the leaflet that Arab states
convene a summit to press for an international conference
</TEXT>
