<FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh-Tornadoes 1stLd-Writethru a0522 04-27 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Tornadoes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0522,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tornado Kills 176, Rains Come After 2-Month Drought</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with death toll at 176. Pickup
8th graf, `Another tornado...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After people prayed for rain to relieve
a drought, two tornadoes and heavy rains battered rural Bangladesh,
killing at least 176 people and injuring hundreds, the state news
agency said today.
   The agency, Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha, did not cite a source
for the death toll but gave the figure in a story that said
President Hussain Muhammad Ershad had ordered relief and rescue
operations for victims of a tornado Wednesday night in the
Manikganj area.
   An independent news agency, United News of Bangladesh, put the
death toll at 42, citing reports from its correspondent in
Manikganj, 25 miles northwest of Dhaka. The tornado, with winds of
100 mph, hailstones, and drenching showers came hours after Ershad
ordered nationwide prayers for rain.
   In Dhaka alone, more than 75,000 people joined Ershad in a
prayer service.
   Two months of drought had threatened to destroy more than half
the rice crop in this poverty-stricken nation. Agriculture
officials said more rain would be needed in the coming week to save
the crops.
   The government news agency said 22 bodies were found in the
rubble of fallen mud and straw houses. The news agency did not give
details.
   At least 200 of the injured were hospitalized, the
government-owned newspaper Dainik Bangla said. It said scores of
people were missing after their boats capsized on the Padma River,
25 miles northwest of Dhaka.
   Another tornado hit the Narsingdi district, 25 miles east of the
capital, killing five people and injuring 500, the English-language
New Nation said. The independent daily said about 200,000 people
were affected by the tornadoes.
   The newspapers said thousands of mud-and-straw houses were swept
away. The tornadoes snapped communications links between Dhaka and
much of the country.
   Bangladesh, one of the world's poorest countries with a per
capita annual income of $160, alternates between flood and drought.
Agriculture is the main occupation of the majority of the country's
110 million people.
</TEXT>
