<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0909EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IranBooks     04-27 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran Books,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Publisher Pulls Out Of Tehran Book Fair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two American publishing companies that
planned to display books at a book fair in Iran next month has
withdrawn, citing questions about the fair's legitimacy.
   John Wiley &amp; Sons, a major publisher of technical and scientific
books, had agreed more than a year ago to be in the fair. It
shipped books for display to Iran soon afterward but had not
intended to send anyone to Tehran.
   Spokesman Leonard Harris said that because books already are in
Tehran, Wiley titles may be put on display, but the publisher was
disassociating itself from the fair because of what it has learned
recently.
   ``First, visas have not been granted by Iran to any members of
the European community or to Americans to participate in the fair
in Tehran,'' the publisher said in a statement Wednesday.
   ``Second, Iran is excluding the books of some publishers. Given
these facts, Wiley should not be considered a participant in the
fair,'' it said.
   The biennial fair May 7-19 is conducted by the Iran Ministry of
Islamic Culture and generally concentrates on scientific, medical
and technical books.
   McGraw-Hill, the other publisher planning to participate, will
be there through its company in England, McGraw-Hill Book Co. (UK)
Ltd., said spokesman Donald S. Rubin.
   ``We don't anticipate anyone going with the books,'' said Rubin.
``We have an independent sales agent who sells our books and those
of other publishers. He's an Iranian national.''
   Rubin said about 50 publishers worldwide would participate in
the fair.
   Wiley and McGraw-Hill were criticized by the Authors' Guild and
by the publisher of Salman Rushdie's books. Rushdie is the author
of ``The Satanic Verses,'' a fictional work many Moslems have found
offensive and that caused Iran's leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, to issue a death threat against him.
   Guild President Robert K. Massie said he was appalled that any
Western publisher ``would deal with any organization in Iran as
long as the death threat on Salman Rushdie is in place.''
   Viking Penguin, Rushdie's U.S. publisher, said in a statement it
doubted ``anyone could fail to recognize the moral questions''
raised by participating.
   ``Obviously we deplore the death threat that was made,'' Rubin
responded. ``But we don't think censorship is the answer to that.
Authors should be free to write and publishers free to distribute
their books. Anything less than that is a blow to anyone's
liberty.''
   Philosophy and safety both figured in decisions of publishers to
skip the Tehran fair, said Thomas D. McKee, executive vice
president of the Association of American Publishers.
   He said the modest-sized fair would have been a low priority for
most publishers anyway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
