<FIRST>u i PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0486 04-27 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0486,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede CANBERRA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vice President Lauds US-Australian Wartime Effort</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs with Quayle remarks at dinner; picks up at pvs 2nd
graf, Quayle, who</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle, noting he is the first
American vice president born after World War II, celebrated with
Australians today the allied effort 47 years ago to beat back
Japanese forces advancing toward this nation.
   Quayle, on a five-day visit to this island nation to commemorate
Australian-American Friendship Week, said the two countries must
dedicate their relationship ``to keeping peace in this region.''
   At a black-tie dinner, Quayle, 42, discussed the spirit of
cooperation that took place in May 1942 when American and
Australian naval forces turned back the Japanese at the Battle of
the Coral Sea off the northeast coast of Australia.
   The vice president, who arrived here from Canberra, read a
proclamation from President Bush that said the relationship between
the United States and Australia ``has thrived in peace because of
our mutual respect, shared ideals and coordinated strides toward a
more secure and prosperous world.''
   Earlier today, Quayle toured a National Aeronautics and Space
Administration facility deep in the Australian bush and called the
resignations of several top NASA officials a problem the
administration must confront.
   Quayle, on his second day in Australia on his trip to the
Pacific, visited the Tidbinbilla Space Tracking Station, which is
managed by Australia's space office on behalf of NASA.
   The station where three giant satellite dishes keep tabs on
satellites will track the Magellan satellite that is to be carried
into space by the space shuttle Atlantis on Friday.
   Quayle earlier met with Australian Prime Minister Bob Hawke and
his top Cabinet officials. In a speech after those meetings, he
praised the U.S.-Australia alliance and called on the Soviet Union
to take concrete steps to lessen military tensions in the Pacific
region.
   During his visit to the space tracking station, Quayle placed a
telephone call to Charles Bolden, an astronaut stationed at the
Kennedy Space Center in Cape Canaveral.
   ``How are you doing ... Any good?'' Quayle asked Bolden as the
two chatted about the upcoming Atlantis launch. ``We hope and pray
everything goes well,'' said Quayle, who has recently taken a keen
interest in space policy as the head of the National Space Council.
   Asked about the recent resignations of six top NASA officials,
including James Odom, head of the space station project, Quayle
said, ``It was an interesting problem.''
   The NASA officials cited low pay and potentially tougher ethics
legislation the Bush administration has asked Congress to consider.
Some of the rules are aimed at tightening the ``revolving door''
for federal workers, which would close job opportunities in the
private sector for NASA officials.
   ``We'll just have to work with Congress and work within the
administration to see if there is anything to adjust the
regulations,'' Quayle said.
   Higher pay for NASA workers should also be considered, he said.
   Before leaving the space complex, Quayle gave Thomas Reid, a
former head of Tidbinbilla, a NASA award.
   Quayle told reporters at the National Press Club after his
speech there that economic frictions should not harm the strong
alliance that has developed between the United States and Australia.
   ``Our relationship with Australia is as strong as ever ... our
alliance remains an essential part of the Western global and
pacific regional collective security system,'' he said in the
question-and-answer session.
   Quayle also said he hopes to hopes to see Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, the leader of the Cambodian anti-communist resistance, in
Jakarta on his Pacific trip.
</TEXT>
