<HEAD>Report: Tawana Brawley Told Friend Her Story Was A Hoax</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs final graf to UPDATE with unsuccessful efforts to obtain
comment today.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black teen-ager whose tale of abduction and
sexual assault by a group of white men led to months of legal
commotion reportedly told a friend that she and her mother made up
the story.
   Tawana Brawley told the friend that she and her mother, Glenda,
invented the story to keep the mother's live-in boyfriend from
beating Ms. Brawley, New York Newsday reported today.
   Ms. Brawley denied the friend's report, the newspaper said.
   She was 15 when found Nov. 28, 1987, in a plastic bag, smeared
with dog excrement and racial epithets. She said she had been
abducted and raped over four days by five or six white men, at
least one with a badge.
   Hospital tests did not show signs of rape, and witnesses later
said they saw her at a party during the four-day period.
   Activist lawyers C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox and the Rev.
Al Sharpton advised Miss Brawley and her family not to cooperate
with a grand jury or investigators, claiming white officials were
engaged in a racist cover-up.
   The grand jury concluded last fall after a seven-month
investigation that the charges were untrue and that her condition
when found was not inconsistent with ``having been self-inflicted.''
   Attorney General Robert Abrams, the special prosecutor in the
case, told Newsday that Daryl T. Rodriguez's tale was consistent
with the grand jury's findings.
   Rodriguez, who began dating Ms. Brawley in the fall of 1987,
told the newspaper that within the last two weeks Ms. Brawley told
him what happened during the time she was supposedly missing.
   According to Rodriguez, the invented story went awry when Mrs.
Brawley picked up her daughter at a condominium complex in
Wappingers Falls, north of New York City, and saw two neighbors
helping her out of the trash bag. The mother then reported to
police that her daughter had been missing for four days, Rodriguez
said.
   Ms. Brawley, who now lives in Virginia Beach, Va., denied the
report and told Newsday she has not talked to Rodriguez since last
summer.
   Maddox and Sharpton did not immediately respond to messages left
today asking them for comment. Mason was out of the country.
</TEXT>
