<FIRST>u i PM-BabyFoodTampering 2ndLd-Writethru   04-27 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baby Food Tampering, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0545,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Cases of Tampering In Ireland, Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with new cases reported, infants hospitalized,
newspaper saying gang that exorted supermarkets under suspicion. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New cases of baby food tampering were reported
today across England as well as in Ireland and Northern Ireland,
and three babies were treated by doctors after eating food tainted
by extortionists, officials said.
   Newspaper reports said food companies had paid $850,000 to
extortionists and that the culprits were demanding another $1.7
million.
   The Daily Telegraph said police believe a gang that extorted
$85,000 from a large supermarket chain this year was reponsible.
   Scotland Yard, which is coordinating a nationwide inquiry,
refused comment on the reports.
   According to police, parents today reported finding glass, pins,
needles and caustic baby soda in jars and cans of baby food and in
one case, powdered milk. They did not say how many new cases were
reported, but as of Wednesday there had been at least 28 cases in
England alone.
   Three babies were taken to hospitals in Leicester, Exeter and
Leeds and later released. One mother found food glass fragments in
her baby's food and another discovered two pieces of metal. The
third baby became ill when eating a banana dessert, police said.
   New cases turned up in the province of Northern Ireland as well
as across the border in the Republic of Ireland, police said.
   H.J. Heinz Co. Ltd. and Cow and Gate Ltd., two of Britain's
leading food manufacturers, on Wednesday offered a total of
$169,000 for information leading to the conviction of the
extortionists.
   Heinz, whose parent company is the Pittsburgh-based food giant,
and Cow and Gate said they had received extortion demands. They
refused to elaborate.
   The Daily Telegraph said police suspected a gang of
extortionists who reportedly got $85,000 from a supermarket chain
this year after threatening to poison food on its market shelves.
The gang threatened to spike baby food unless it was paid $1.7
million, the newspaper said. It did not name the victimized
supermarket chain.
   The London tabloid Today said without attribution that some
manufacturers had already paid $845,000 to the extortionists. It
did not name the companies.
   Today said the extortionists initially hid the money in various
accounts with the Halifax Building Society, one of Britain's
leading savings and loans groups, then used cash cards to draw it
bit by bit from Halifax cash dispenser machines.
   The paper did not say, but the implication appeared to be that
the gang used false identities to open the accounts.
   It said more than 4,000 police staked out 768 Halifax cash
dispenser machines around the country in a bid to trap the
extortionists but that they failed.
   The government said 28 incidents of tampering with jars and cans
of baby food have been reported since April 7, including 11 on
Wednesday.
   In addition to today's victims, a 9-month-old girl in Oxford cut
her mouth on a piece of razor blade in a yogurt container and two
mothers were cut by glass shards in jars of infant food. None
required hospital treatment.
   In one incident, sodium hydroxide, or caustic soda, was used to
contaminate a jar of baby food. The white substance is a strong
caustic base used in chemistry and oil refining.
   Heinz and Cow and Gate said internal investigations have
determined their baby food products were not tampered with during
production.
   Ted Smyth, director of corporate affairs for Heinz in
Pittsburgh, said Wednesday the parent company ``shares the
universal outrage'' over the tampering.
   He said, ``We have no reason at all to be concerned about
tampering of products in the United States.''
</TEXT>
