<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   04-27 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0532,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Says He'll Cooperate With Arab Observer Force In Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Arab League calling for cease-fire,
observers. Pickup 5th pvs, `Its main...;' Deletes last 2 grafs to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army commander Michel Aoun said today his
troops would cooperate with a cease-fire observer force that Arab
countries plan to deploy in Lebanon.
   In Tunisia, foreign ministers of the 22-member Arab League today
called for a cease-fire to begin Friday at noon. They did not say
how many observer troops would be deployed or when but said the
plan should be carried out immediately.
   A special committee made up of six ministers has recommended
stationing 312 officers from Arab armies in Lebanon.
   The observer force would be deployed along Beirut's dividing
Green Line and other flashpoints in the hills above the Lebanese
capital, according to a text of the committee's plan published
today in Beirut newspapers.
   Its main task would be monitoring the cease-fire, and officers
would have no right to use arms except in self-defense, according
to the text.
   The force's mandate is set for three months but could be
extended. The newspapers did not say which countries would
contribute to the force.
   ``We will cooperate positively with the Arab force on the
military level,'' Aoun said in a statement broadcast by
Christian-controlled radio stations in Beirut.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads a Moslem Cabinet
that rivals Aoun's Christian military government, has welcomed
setting up an Arab observer force. But his justice minister, Nabih
Berri, who heads the pro-Syrian Shiite Moslem Amal militia, has
rejected the plan.
   At least 272 people have been killed and 991 wounded in six
weeks of battles between Aoun's mainly Christian troops and an
alliance of the Syrian army and Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's
Progressive Socialist Party militia.
   Police said Syrian and Druse gunners sporadically shelled the
coast north of Beirut with rockets and mortars today, keeping
closed the only escape route for the 1 million Christians in their
enclave.
   No casualties were reported.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 40,000 troops
in northern, eastern and central areas as well as Beirut's Moslem
sector under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
   The newspapers said the Arab foreign ministers decided to
postpone the issue of political reforms in Lebanon and election of
a new president until after the observer force is in place.
   The presidency has been vacant since Sept. 22, when President
Amin Gemayel's six-year term ended with Parliament unable to elect
a successor.
   Before stepping down, Gemayel appointed Aoun, a Maronite
Catholic, head of an interim Cabinet to rule pending the election
of a new head of state.
   Moslem and leftist forces rejected Aoun's appointment and
pledged allegiance to the Hoss Cabinet, which governed under
Gemayel.
   Moslems also are seeking political reforms that would give them
an equal share of power with the traditionally dominant Christians.
   The current fighting broke out March 8 after Aoun clamped a
blockade on illegal ports run by Moslem militias south of Beirut.
   Jumblatt retaliated by shelling the 310-square-mile Christian
enclave. The Syrians joined the bombardment and sealed off the
area's land exits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
