<FIRST>r a PM-SouthsideSlayer     04-27 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Southside Slayer,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Worker Convicted Of Four Prostitute Murders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COMPTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An illiterate, unemployed construction
worker has been convicted of the murders of four prostitutes, two
of which had been listed as Southside Slayer killings.
   Louis Craine, 31, also was found guilty Wednesday of several
counts of sexual assault in the strangulation murders between
August 1985 and May 1987, but was acquitted on a fifth count of
murder.
   The jury is scheduled to return May 8 to decide if Craine should
be sentenced to death or life in prison without the possibility of
parole.
   It was the Los Angeles man's second trial. His first ended in
mistrial in August.
   Craine is one of three men arrested in connection with the
slayings of 18 women whose deaths were so similar homicide
detectives believed they may have been the work of a serial killer.
Most of the victims were prostitutes who had been stabbed or
strangled and their bodies dumped in south-central Los Angeles or
adjacent communities.
   In March 1986, before any arrests were made, police announced
the formation of what they called a South Side Serial Murder Task
Force to investigate slayings that dated to 1983.
   Craine was charged with three of those killings and two
unrelated slayings. He confessed to three murders when he was
arrested in 1987, but later recanted on the witness stand.
   The defense portrayed Craine as an illiterate man of low
intelligence who confessed during an aggressive interrogation
simply to tell investigators what they wanted to hear.
   Daniel Lee Siebert was charged with two killings last year, and
Charles Mosley was convicted of one slaying.
</TEXT>
