<FIRST>r a PM-North-ConcealedWeapon     04-27 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North-Concealed Weapon,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-North Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Judge Says North Has Permit to Carry Concealed Weapon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North possesses a permit to carry a
concealed weapon in Fairfax County, Va., because he feels
threatened by terrorists and what his attorney calls ``the nut
element,'' the chief judge of County Circuit Court said today.
   ``It's very unusual'' for anyone to be granted a permit to carry
a concealed weapon, said Chief Judge Lewis Griffith. But his
predecessor, Judge Barnard F. Jennings, granted North the original
one-year permit in October 1987 because he was convinced North
showed a legitimate need, Griffith said.
   Griffith, who became chief judge the following January, renewed
the license for two more years on Oct. 13, 1988, a month after
North re-applied.
   North, a former White House aide, is awaiting a jury's verdict
on charges stemming from the Iran-Contra affair. He was identified
last July as the target of a potential assassination plot involving
one of eight man charged with illegal pro-Libyan activities in the
United States.
   Just one other person received a concealed license permit in
1987, and of 77 applications filed in 1988, North was the sole
recipient, Griffith said.
   ``He is the only one that I have ever felt satisfied and
demonstrated a need to carry a concealed weapon,'' said Griffith.
The county's chief judge makes the final decision on concealed
weapon permits, based on need.
   Papers filed by North's attorney, Brendan Sullivan, focused on
two threats to the life of the former White House aide. ``According
to experts, dangers come from two basic sources _ the terrorist
element, which wants to fulfill its promise to even the score, and
the nut element, which surfaces in situations like this,'' the
papers said.
   Fairfax County law allows residents to carry weapons in view,
but those who wish to carry a concealed weapon must go through a
complicated approval process, said Griffith.
   The permit is only in effect when North is in Fairfax County,
where he lives.
   ``It's only good in the jurisdiction it's issued in,'' said a
District of Columbia police spokesman. ``You get a gun permit in
Virginia, it's only good in Virginia.''
</TEXT>
