<FIRST>u a PM-Eliana-AIDS 2ndLd-Writethru a0556 04-27 0784</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eliana-AIDS, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0556,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>Girl With AIDS Enters Public School After 2{-Year Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Principal Sandra...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with classroom reaction and more calls of concern; picks up 8th graf, ``Attorney
Steve...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mentally disabled, AIDS-stricken 7-year-old
stepped into a classroom for the first time in her life today, with
bows in her hair, a knapsack on her back and the cheers of
supporters surrounding her.
   Rosa Martinez, who fought a 2{-year court battle against school
officials who feared a health risk, called today the most important
day in her daughter Eliana's life.
   A federal district judge Wednesday cleared the way for Eliana to
attend class without being confined to a glass isolation booth, as
required in an earlier ruling.
   Supporters cheered as Mrs. Martinez and Eliana walked into the
one-story, red-brick Manhattan Exceptional Center, where 201
students are enrolled. There were no protests.
   ``She'll finally, for the first time in her life, be able to be
with children and spend all the time she can with them,'' Ms.
Martinez said as they went inside.
   Eliana wore a pink dress and pink bows in her hair and carried a
toy that plays the Disney song ``It's a Small World.''
   Ms. Martinez told reporters later that when Eliana entered the
classroom, ``the children came around her and one of them hugged
her.''
   ``They just surrounded her,'' she said. ``They didn't need any
introductions.''
   Principal Sandra Williams said she sent notes to parents
Wednesday to prepare them for Eliana's arrival and received seven
calls of concern, with one mother saying she was not ready to
accept the risk.
   Attorney Steve Hanlon, who pressed a suit through a federal
appeals court to keep the little girl from being put in a
glass-walled booth in the class for mentally disabled, physically
impaired children, drove mother and daughter to school. Eliana
became the 12th student in the class.
   ``It's a wonderful day for her,'' he said. ``She'll do
wonderfully here. She's going to take off like a rocket.''
   But he said he expected her first day to be difficult because
``she doesn't have any exprience with other kids.''
   Linda Castellano, a family friend and head of an AIDS support
group called ``Linda and Frenz,'' was among seven supporters on
hand to watch Eliana enter public school for the first time.
   ``I know she'll benefit from playing with other kids,'' she
said. ``She's always around adults and always having to look up.
Now she'll have eye contact with children.''
   The child, who had been taught at home since June 1987, was once
told she could attend class on the condition she remained inside a
glass booth. However, the issue of a partition became moot when
U.S. District Judge Elizabeth A. Kovachevich decided Eliana posed
no significant threat to her classmates.
   Hanlon predicted Wednesday that the ruling will have
far-reaching effects.
   ``I'm just a trial lawyer,'' Hanlon said, ``but people who
really do a lot of this work tell me this is a landmark case _ that
it will have a major impact around the country.''
   In an earlier ruling, Kovachevich tried to allay the school
system's fears by ordering the isolation booth for the incontinent
child until the girl became toilet trained and learned to stop
sucking her fingers.
   But Mrs. Martinez said she would not send her daughter to school
to sit in a ``glass cage'' and appealed.
   ``I'm so happy. I don't have bitterness for anything,'' Mrs.
Martinez said after the ruling. ``My daughter is not a monkey. I've
always said that.
   ``All she understands is she will be going in to play with some
little people. She doesn't know what school is; she hasn't been to
it.''
   School board attorney Crosby Few said he was glad the judge had
ruled and would recommend that it be followed.
   In December, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals sent the
case back to Kovachevich, saying the child must be placed in a
regular classroom setting unless evidence proved Eliana posed a
significant risk to other children through bodily secretions.
   The judge said she learned through recent sworn statements that
Eliana is ``capable of being instructed not to suck or mouth her
fingers and that she is well on her way to being fully toilet
trained.''
   Hanlon and Mrs. Martinez, a nurse who adopted Eliana as an
infant in her native Puerto Rico, argued that in order to develop
fully Eliana needed to be with other children for interaction,
stimulation and socialization.
   Eliana was stricken with acquired immune deficiency syndrome
from tranfusions of tainted blood shortly after her premature birth.
</TEXT>
