<FIRST>r w PM-US-ArabLeague 1stLd-Writethru a0559 04-27 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Arab League, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0559,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Envoys Call On Baker to Discuss Lebanon And West Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS cycle to PM sted AM; inserts new 5th graf, Arab League,
with foreign ministers approving plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab League delegation was meeting today
with Secretary of State James A. Baker III to discuss a cease-fire
plan for Lebanon and a U.S.-supported Israeli proposal for
elections on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   The delegation also planned to ask Baker to reopen the Palestine
Liberation Organization's office here. The Reagan administration
closed in on the ground the PLO is engaged in terrrorism, but the
administration later opened talks with the group.
   The Arab League delegation is headed by Clovis Maksoud, the
league's representative in the United States, and includes
Ambassadors Saud al-Sabah of Kuwait and Mohsin A. Alaini of North
Yemen.
   The league has proposed stationing 312 officers from Arab armies
in Lebanon to monitor a cease-fire under United Nations
supervision. The country is torn by warfare between Christian and
Moslem factions, with 40,000 Syrian
   Arab League foreign ministers approved the cease-fire proposal
at a meeting in Tunis, Tunisia, today. The Council of Ministers
from the 22 member countries, after nearly seven hours of
discussions, said the cease-fire should begin Friday at noon.
   Maksoud said that in the afternoon meeting, the delegation also
would discuss with Baker the proposal by Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir to hold elections among Palestinian Arabs on the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and in Gaza.
   The elected leaders would negotiate an interim system of local
self-rule to be followed by negotiations on an overall settlement
for the territories Jordan and Egypt surrendered in the 1967
Mideast war.
   The Arab League has rejected the plan, saying it is a device for
ratification of Shamir's ``annexation'' of the West Bank and Gaza,
where more than 1.4 million Palestinian Arabs live. But Baker has
called on all sides to consider the arrangement as a hopeful step
toward a permanent agreement.
   The league is planning tentatively to hold a summit meeting next
month and would send a delegation afterward to meet with Baker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
