<FIRST>r a PM-AbbieHoffman     04-27 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abbie Hoffman,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>District Attorney Says Drugs Found In Hoffman's Refrigerator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOYLESTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small quantities of illegal drugs were
found in the home of Abbie Hoffman, the Yippie movement co-founder
who committed suicide earlier this month, authorities said today.
   The drugs were found in a box in Hoffman's refrigerator, Bucks
County District Attorney Alan M. Rubenstein said.
   The box contained 9.38 grams of marijuana, 0.31 grams of
hashish, a cocaine residue and trace amounts of LSD, amphetamines
and psilocybin, Rubenstein said. Toxicology tests completed last
week confirmed the drugs and the amounts, he said.
   Hoffman, 52, was found dead April 12 in his home near New Hope.
Coroner Thomas J. Rosko ruled April 18 Hoffman died of a ``massive
overdose'' of the sedative phenobarbital and large quantities of
alcohol.
   Rubenstein said the quantities of the illegal drugs found in
Hoffman's refrigerator indicated they were for his personal use.
   ``None of these items were found in his bloodstream,''
Rubenstein said.
</TEXT>
