<FIRST>u i PM-Vietnam-USRemains     04-27 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-US Remains,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Returns 21 Sets Of U.S. Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam today returned 21 sets of
remains that tentatively have been identified as Americans killed
in the Vietnam War, the Vietnam News Agency said.
   A brief dispatch from the official agency, monitored in Bangkok,
said the remains were turned over to a representative of the
Hawaii-based U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution Center, the military
unit set up to resolved the issue of more than 2,300 Americans
missing in action, or MIA, from the Indochina war.
   According to U.S. spokesmen, the military unit was to have
picked up the remains in a ceremony at Hanoi airport and then fly
them to army laboratories in Honolulu for analysis and
identification.
   The Vietnamese report did not provide details but said the
Americans ``appreciated the humanitarian policy, good will and
cooperation'' of Vietnam.
   A total of 1,730 Americans are still listed as missing in action
in Vietnam while 634 are missing in Cambodia, Laos and China.
   The Indochina war ended in 1975 with communist victories over
U.S.-backed governments in Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos.
   A 20-member U.S. military flew to Hanoi from Bangkok earlier
today aboard a U.S. Air Force C-131 transport to pick up the
remains. The team, headed by Lt. Col. Bill Jordan, was to arrive in
Honolulu Friday after stopping in Guam.
   Including today's repatriation, Vietnam has returned 184 remains
since mid-1987 when it agreed to accelerate cooperation on the
issue in exchange for Washington's help in encouraging private
humanitarian aid to Vietnam.
   The U.S. military says that of those remains returned since
mid-1987, 45 have been positively identified as those of U.S.
servicemen killed in action.
   A team of 10 U.S. military specialists has been in Vietnam since
April 12, cooperating with Vietnamese counterparts in the fifth
joint field investigation on MIAs. They are interviewing villagers
who witnessed plane crashes and seeking other evidence of the
missing men. The investigators are to work until April 30 in the
longest such project thus far.
</TEXT>
