<FIRST>u i PM-Bangladesh-Tornadoes 3rdLd-Writethru a0583 04-27 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Tornadoes, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0583,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tornado Kills 500, Rains Come After 2-Month Drought</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD details of damage, 5,000 reported injured.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAVEL RAHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associate Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANIKGANJ, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tornado killed at least 500
people, injured thousands and devastated more than 20 villages in
central Bangladesh, the government said today.
   The tornado Wednesday night blew away people, houses and animals
as it whirled at 100 mph through the Manikganj area, 25 miles
northwest of Dhaka.
   Survivors said the funnel cloud raged for 10 minutes and
flattened ``everything, including buildings.''
   ``I saw black clouds gathering in the sky. In moments we found
we were flying along with the house,'' said Sayeda Begum, a
30-year-old homemaker in Saturia village near Manikganj.
   Another tornado hit the Narsingdi district, 25 miles east of the
capital, killing five people and injuring 500, the English-language
newspaper New Nation said.
   The tornadoes brought with them rain and hail and followed a
two-month drought that has threatened to destroy more than half the
rice crop in this impoverished nation. The tornadoes hit hours
after President Hussain Muhammad Ershad ordered nationwide prayers
for rain.
   In Dhaka alone, more than 75,000 people joined Ershad in a
prayer service.
   A senior government official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said 5,000 people were injured in Manikganj. He said 500
bodies had been recovered.
   Troops searched through rubble today for more victims.
   In Saturia, nothing was standing as far as the eye could see.
The village of 10,000 resembled a bombed area, with houses uprooted
and electric poles twisted.
   Mrs. Begum said she, her husband and four of their children were
lifted through the air and all were injured. A fifth child, a
5-year-old boy, was found about two miles away and received severe
bruises, she said.
   At Nandeshwari, a neighboring village of at least 120 houses,
there were no standing structures or people in sight.
   Tofael Ahmed, a teacher, wept bitterly, holding a torn shirt
that had been worn by his son. Both his son and daughter were
missing.
   ``What shall I do with this shirt. Why should Allah curse me
like this,'' he cried. He said he had brought the shirt for his son
to wear during the Moslems' religious festival of Eid next week.
   Authorities said more than 500 people were admitted to hospitals
and many were in critical condition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
