<HEAD>Rebels Loot Shops, U.N. Equipment, Kill Woman in Northern Uganda</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels abducted 15 people, killed a
woman, looted shops and stole communications equipment belonging to
the United Nations in northern Uganda, sources said Thursday.
   More than 200 rebels armed with guns, spears, machetes, arrows
and sticks waged the attack before dawn Monday in Moyo district,
about 280 miles northwest of Kampala, said Moses Ali, a Moyo
parliamentarian.
   A reporter for a weekly Kampala newspaper said the rebels,
believed to be members of the Holy Spirit Movement, abducted three
women and 12 government laborers who had been drilling water wells
for about 40,000 Sudanese refugees camped in the area near Uganda's
border with Sudan.
   Ali, who also serves as minister for youth, culture and sports,
said the rebels also looted shops and stole communications
equipment belonging to the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
   It was the first reported attack in the region since President
Yoweri Museveni came to power three years ago.
