<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-AssaultWeapons 1stLd-Writethru a0544 04-27 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Assault Weapons, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0544,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Releases 1,200 Imported Assault Guns Seized By Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf, `Justice Department...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with Justice reviewing ruling and no comment from Customs.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ruled that the Customs
Service must release about 1,200 semiautomatic rifles impounded at
an airport as part of the Bush administration's ban on the
importation of assault weapons.
   The decision was issued Wednesday by U.S. District Judge William
Acker Jr., who criticized the temporary ban, initiated by federal
drug policy coordinator William Bennett.
   The ban was ``obviously the product of a `hurry-up' skull
session, if not a stampede reaction set off by Bennett,'' the judge
said.
   Acker did not overturn the ban for other rifle models imported
to other cities. But he ordered federal officials to deliver to Gun
South Inc. of Trussville about 1,200 Steyr AUG-SA rifles impounded
by customs agents at the Birmingham Municipal Airport and another
3,000 to be sent from Austria.
   The company argued that the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms approved import permits for the rifles before the Bush
administration announced its ban in late March.
   The Justice Department was reviewing the decision and had not
decided whether to appeal the judge's ruling, said spokeswoman Amy
Brown.
   There was no immediate comment from the Customs Service.
   ATF Director Stephen Higgins said in court documents that
releasing the weapons would undermine the government's policy
review of the effects of the temporary ban.
   Acker said the administration issued the ban without consulting
American gun dealers or foreign manufacturers of semiautomatic
rifles, and without re-examining ATF's past approval of the Steyr
AUG-SA.
   The ban followed a schoolyard shooting in California involving
an assault rifle.
   Gun South owner and president Don Wood, who sued four weeks ago,
testified his company would face bankruptcy if it could not receive
and sell the rifles it has ordered and committed to pay for.
   The company also claimed the Steyr AUG-SA rifle is used for
hunting, the criterion on which ATF had approved previous shipments
of the rifles.
   The Justice Department argued that the public interest in
halting importation of semiautomatic and automatic rifles pending a
review outweighed any potential harm the temporary ban might cause
Gun South.
   ``This is a small case but a significant example of why our
justice system enjoys the envy of the world. Once again, a federal
judge has enjoined the government from violating the right of way
at a constitutional intersection,'' said James C. Barton, an
attorney for Gun South.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
