<FIRST>u a PM-Spearfishing 1stLd-Writethru a0564 04-27 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spearfishing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0564,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 40 Arrested In Protests Of Indian Treaty Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1st graf and 11th graf, `At Rainbow' to CORRECT number
of arrests to reflect total now being reported by Department of Natural
Resources.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GERMAIN, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-three people have been arrested
in the latest wave of demonstrations against Chippewa Indian
spearfishing in off-reservation public lakes.
   The arrests were made Wednesday when large crowds gathered at
boat landings in northern Wisconsin where the annual Chippewa
spearing season began last weekend prior to the fishing season for
non-Indians.
   Federal courts since 1983 have upheld 19th century treaties in
which the Chippewa deeded northern Wisconsin to the United States
and were guaranteed the right to hunt, fish, trap and harvest wild
grain on public land.
   Critics say the Indians' spears leave too few trophy-size fish
for the rod-and-reel season that begins next month. More than 400
people rallied Wednesday at the state Capitol in Madison,
complaining that spearing discourages sport fishing upstate and
reduces the region's summer tourism business.
   Tribal members are expected to spear about 30,000 fish this
spring, compared with an annual hook-and-line walleye catch of
about 800,000 fish annually in northern Wisconsin.
   The Chippewa have announced plans to spear at 254 lakes.
   Five of the tribe's six Wisconsin bands fished Wednesday.
   Wardens and police have been kept busy this season shielding
spearers from hecklers, said George Meyer, DNR administrator of
enforcement for the Department of Natural Resources.
   ``It's starting out every night with a crowd someplace,'' Meyer
said.
   The Chippewa fish at night with battery-powered lights to
illuminate walleyed pike, muskellunge and other fish in shallow
water.
   At Rainbow Flowage, a Wisconsin River reservoir, 35 people were
arrested Wednesday night for disorderly conduct or obstructing
police after walking into a restricted area at a public boat
landing used by Chippewa, said David Kunelius, a DNR spokesman.
   About 150 miles to the west, six people were taken into custody
at Balsam Lake in Polk County for various offenses from scattering
nails on roads to disorderly conduct, Kunelius said.
   One man was arrested for disorderly conduct at Crescent Lake,
where a crowd peaked at about 200 people. Another was arrested for
tire slashing at Seven-Mile Lake, where there were no spearers,
Kunelius said.
</TEXT>
