<FIRST>u i PM-ArabLeague-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0580 04-27 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arab League-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0580,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab League Calls For Cease-Fire In Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf pvs, ``Foreign Minister...'' to CORRECT spelling
of name to Al-Sharaa, sted Al-Charaa. Pickup 6th pvs, ``About 40,000...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab League foreign ministers called today
for a cease-fire in Lebanon and said they will send observers to
monitor it.
   The ministers also said blockades of Lebanon's ports should be
lifted. The blockades touched off six weeks of intensive fighting
between Christian and Moslem forces that have left more than 270
people dead.
   The Council of Ministers from the 22 member countries, after
nearly seven hours of discussions, said the cease-fire should begin
Friday at noon.
   Their final statement did not say how many observers will be
sent or when, saying only that the plan should be carried out
``without delay.''
   Foreign Minister Farouk Al-Sharaa of Syria told reporters at the
close of the session that his country is ready to give any aid a
special six-member Arab League committee will need to help end the
fighting.
   About 40,000 Syrian troops are based in Lebanon under an 1976
Arab League peacekeeping mandate. Syria maintains it is not part of
the conflict.
   However, the Syrian army, in alliance with Druse warlord Walid
Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party militia of about 7,000 men,
has been fighting the 20,000 Christian troops of Gen. Michel Aoun
since March 8.
   Iraq supports Aoun in the fighting.
   The Council of Ministers met from midnight to 3:30 a.m. today,
then suspended the session. The council met again for more than
three hours beginning at 1 p.m. before issuing the final communique.
   The special committee charged in January with finding a solution
to the conflict, composed of foreign ministers from six of the 22
Arab League member nations, has recommended stationing 312 Arab
observers in Beirut, sources said.
   An Arab League delegation also met today in Washington with
Secretary of State James A. Baker III to discuss the cease-fire
plan. Aoun, whose blockade of Moslem controlled ports touched off
the latest round of fighting in Lebanon, has repeatedly called on
the United States to help end the nation's civil war.
</TEXT>
