<FIRST>r a AM-QualityAssurance     04-27 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quality Assurance,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Plans `Quality Assurance' Labels on Produce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pressured by consumer and grocer concerns
over food safety, state agriculture officials are about to offer a
``quality assurance'' seal for produce grown by farmers who agree
to meet all pesticide regulations.
   The plan developed quickly after consumer scares in March over
the use of the chemical Alar on apples and the discovery of cyanide
in two Chilean grapes.
   Despite the short lead time, the California Department of Food
and Agriculture is expected to inaugurate the new system early next
month unless a hitch develops.
   The language of the ``quality assurance'' seals has been under
review by the state Attorney General and governor's staffs this
week to see if it would present any legal liabilities for the state.
   Participating growers would sign a contract with the state in
which they would agree to comply with all laws and regulations and
manufacturer's label instructions governing any pesticides they use.
   The state will test about 2,500 samples of crops from those
signing up for the voluntary program. That sampling, financed by an
additional one cent per box levy paid by participants, will be in
addition to the 8,000-9,000 pesticide tests the department already
conducts on fruits and vegetables each year, by far the most of any
state in the nation.
   Growers in the program whose crops are below tolerance limits
for pesticide residue will be able to label their produce with a
``quality assurance'' sticker certified by the state.
   ``This will give them a seal to use that it is
California-produced in accordance with California laws and
regulations,'' said Jim Wells, who oversees the agriculture
department's pesticide regulatory program. ``Retailers and growers
alike feel that kind of thing will help put the public's mind at
ease.''
   However, Harry Snyder of Consumers Union said growers should
quit using pesticides and predicted that the program will fail
because buyers who consider pesticides dangerous won't be appeased
by a seal on produce.
   ``People have the perception this stuff is dangerous,'' Snyder
said. ``Well, it's an accurate perception.''
   After the Alar and cyanide incidents, the California Grocers
Association persuaded state agricultural officials to start this
program, said President Don Beaver.
   ``We have no control as retailers what is being used by
growers,'' Beaver said. ``All we want to know is, if we are buying
it and we are paying for it, that it's safe for consumers.''
   Officials of grower organizations expressed cautious enthusiasm,
although some felt the system should be mandatory instead of
voluntary or should be delayed a year to allow more time to prepare
for the change.
   ``The indication we've gotten from retailers and also from the
California Grocers Association is that they intend to buy only from
those who have the seal, so suddenly we have some questions,'' said
Richard Matoian of the California Grape and Tree Fruit League.
``Once one person puts a stamp on a box, everybody's going to have
to do it to keep their markets.''
   Iceberg lettuce probably will be the first crop to use the new
seals because growers report they are ready to sign up now.
   ``The position our industry has taken is they do support the
seal, and they're ready to start implementing it as soon as the
state wants to do it,'' said Wade Whitfield, president of the
California Iceberg Lettuce Commission.
   Beaver feels food is safe now, but because the public perceives
that some isn't, such a program is necessary to help restore
consumers' confidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
