<FIRST>r i AM-Lenin     04-27 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lenin,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suggetion to Remove Lenin's Body From Mausoleum Creates Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stage director has caused a furor reaching all
the way to the Communist Party Central Committee by suggesting on
live TV that Vladimir I. Lenin's body be removed from the mausoleum
on Red Square and buried.
   Lenin's mausoleum at the Kremlin Wall is visited by millions of
Soviets every year, reflecting the reverence in which the Soviet
founder still is held.
   Two candidate members of the party's policy-making Central
Committee, speaking at a meeting Tuesday, criticized the suggestion
by Mark Zakharov, director of Moscow's Leninsky Komsomol Theater.
   Zakharov said on the weekly discussion program ``Vzglad'' that
Lenin's body should be removed from the mausoleum where it has been
kept since his death in 1924 and buried.
   The mausoleum, he and other speakers said, should be turned into
a monument to the Soviet founder without his body.
   ``Vzglad'' is one of the most outspoken and popular shows on
Soviet TV, and the April 21 live show was broadcast only hours
after official TV carried a Kremlin ceremony marking Lenin's 119th
birthday.
   ``To repeat these kinds of questions is, it seems to me, simply
immoral,'' said Ratmir Bobovikov, regional party leader in Vladimir.
   ``Literally the next morning people began calling the party
committee and in disbelieve asking, `How are we supposed to
understand this? Whose point of view is this?' '' he said.
   Another Central Committee member criticized the show for
broadcasting the comments.
   ``Why does our television _ state, party television _ permit
such statements?'' said Georgy Zhukov, a candidate Central
Committee member who retired at Tuesday's meeting.
   Alexander Aksenov, director of the state radio and television
committee, said ``Vzglad'' was ``a live broadcast and no one
expected anything like it.''
   He indicated that editors face disciplinary action for the
broadcast.
   Although ``Vzglad'' is one of the most popular shows on Soviet
TV, its editors have been chastised more than once for the
viewpoints expressed on the show, he said.
   Even under the greater openness of President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policies, Lenin is rarely criticized.
   On major state holidays, May Day and Revolution Day, the Soviet
leadership stands atop the mausoleum to review parades.
   Lenin's widow, Nadezhda Krupskaya, bitterly opposed interment of
Lenin in an above-ground mausoleum where his body could be viewed,
but she was overruled by the party leaders, including Josef Stalin.
   When Stalin died in 1953, his body was placed in the mausoleum,
but it was removed in 1961 after Premier Nikita S. Khrushchev began
a liberalization campaign and a re-evaluation of Stalin's ``cult of
personality.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
