<FIRST>r a AM-Lujan-LouisianaErosion     04-27 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lujan-Louisiana Erosion,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lujan Says He Underestimated Problem of Louisiana's Vanishing Coastline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McKNIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan said Thursday
he underestimated the problem of protecting Louisiana's
disappearing coastal marshes, which are vanishing at the rate of
about an acre every 15 minutes.
   Louisiana loses 30 to 50 square miles of its coastal marshes
each year. The wetlands support a billion-dollar seafood industry
and serve as the winter home for about 5 million migratory birds.
   Lujan was here for a meeting at the Petroleum Club of New
Orleans; he also visited an offshore drilling rig.
   ``At first, I thought that all we needed to do was put riprp and down
the coast,'' Lujan said. ``And
then someone explained to me that was not possible.''
   For one thing, Louisiana's 400 miles of coastline translates to
almost 7,000 miles of shoreline when the bays, inlets and
peninsulas are included. Solid objects also tend to sink in the
marshy soil of the shoreline.
   Louisiana, with 40 percent of the nation's coastal wetlands,
suffers 80 percent of the annual loss. Most of the loss is due to
industrialization along the Mississippi River, which robs the
marshes of the fresh water and silt that used to renew them.
   Lujan said the ``no net loss'' policy proclaimed by President
Bush probably can't be interpreted to mean that an acre of
Louisiana marsh must be reclaimed for every acre lost.
</TEXT>
