<DOCNO> AP890427-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-US     04-27 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-US,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Returns 21 Sets of Remains to U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam on Thursday returned 21 sets of
remains believed to be those of Americans killed in the Vietnam
War, and U.S. sources said they expected talks soon on further
repatriations of the dead.
   Vietnam's Communist Party leader Nguyen Van Linh said the two
countries were ``cooperating fruitfully'' to solve humanitarian
issues arising from the long, bloody conflict.
   The resolution of the missing in action issue and Vietnam's
military occupation of Cambodia have been the prime obstacles to
normalization of ties between Vietnam and the United States.
   A dispatch from the official Vietnam News Agency, monitored in
Bangkok, said the remains were turned over to a representative of
the Hawaii-based U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution Center, the
military unit tasked with resolving the fates of more than 2,300
MIAs from the Indochina conflict.
   According to a U.S. spokesmen, a team from the center was to
have picked up the remains in a ceremony at Hanoi airport, then
take them to army laboratories in Honolulu for analysis.
   The Vietnamese report did not provide details but said the
Americans ``highly appreciated the humanitarian policy, goodwill
and cooperation'' of Vietnam.
   U.S. official sources, who asked not to be identified, said
talks on more repatrations were likely to take place in the near
future.
   There are 1,730 Americans still listed as missing in action in
Vietnam, while 634 others are missing in Cambodia, Laos and China.
The war ended in 1975 with communist victories over U.S.-backed
governments in Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos.
   A 20-member U.S. military flew to Hanoi from Bangkok on Thursday
aboard a U.S. Air Force C-131 transport to pick up the remains. The
team, headed by Lt. Col. Bill Jordan, was due to arrive in Honolulu
on Friday after an overnight stop in Guam.
   Counting Thursday's repatriation, Vietnam has returned 184 sets
of remains since 1987, when it was agreed to accelerate cooperation
in exchange for Washington's help in encouraging private
humanitarian aid to Vietnam.
   The U.S. military says that of those remains returned since
mid-1987, 45 have been positively identified as those of U.S.
servicemen killed in the conflict.
   A team of 10 U.S. military specialists has been in Vietnam since
April 12, working with Vietnamese in the fifth joint investigation
on MIAs. They are interviewing villagers who saw plane crashes and
seeking other evidence of the missing men.
   The investigators will work until April 30 in the longest such
project thus far.
   American experts believe that while other remains will probably
be found, a total resolution of all on the MIA roster is impossible
given the corrosive tropical climate, difficult terrain and the
fact that many died at sea.
   The lack of diplomatic relations between the onetime enemies has
hampered progress on the MIA and other humanitarian issues.
   But Vietnam announced April 5 that it will withdraw all of its
troops from Cambodia by Sept. 30, and progress on the MIA
resolution has been substantial.
   ``At present, the Vietnam-U.S. relationship is not good but it
is better than that during the U.S. aggression against Vietnam,''
Linh said in a recent interview.
   ``The two countries are cooperating fruitfully in the settlement
of humanitarian issues of both sides,'' he said. ``We are prepared
to look forward.''
   Linh, who is seeking to expand ties with the non-communist
world, said normal relations with the United States would ``benefit
both sides as well as peace and stability in the region.''
</TEXT>
