<FIRST>r w AM-InfantMortality 1stLd-Writethru a0613 04-27 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Infant Mortality, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0613,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third World Methods Urged for Cutting US Baby Deaths</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf pvs, Ms. Lacey, to CORRECT name to Gude</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health experts told Congress Thursday that
Third World methods could help reduce infant mortality rates in the
United States.
   ``Approximately 40,000 infants die each year'' in the United
States, said Lacey A. Gude, a Washington businesswoman who serves
as secretary of the National Association of the Partners of the
Americas, a group that aimes to foster cooperation among the
nations in the Western Hemisphere.
   She said health workers in Latin America are used to making do
with little money and to dealing with poor people.
   She cited a card that Brazilian communities give new mothers to
keep track of their children's weight and vaccinations. Babies who
die soon after birth are often underweight.
   ``A simple device like this has made a big impact on educational
programs in other countries and we believe it can help us reduce
our own infant mortality rates here in the states,'' she said.
   Ms. Gude and others testified to the House committee on hunger.
   Dr. Norbert Hirschhorn testified in favor of the cure now
widespread in poor countries for diarrhea in babies: a simple
mixture of water, sugar or glucose and salt that can be drunk.
   Such an oral rehydration treatment using ``rice powder in place
of glucose is palatable and helps slow diarrhea,'' he said.
   He said the standard U.S. treatment for dehydration, the loss of
body fluids, is to give replacement fluids intravenously. But this
treatment is expensive and not always available outside hospitals.
   Hirschhorn is vice president of John Snow, Inc. a consulting
firm.
   Rep. Mike Espy, D-Miss., chairman of the committee's domestic
task force, said diarrhea annually kills about 500 American
children under age five. Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, chairman of
the committee, estimated that oral rehydration saves 750,000 to a
million lives every year in the Third World.
   Dr. Stanley Foster said the United States could learn from other
countries about immunizing pre-school children against measles and
whooping cough.
   ``Coverage for measles'' for children under age two in some
large U.S. metropolitan areas ``has been documented to be as low as
49 percent,'' he testified.
   ``This is lower than in many nations of the developing world.
...''
   Dr. Foster directs the field services division of the U.S.
government's International Health Program Office.
   Dr. Sandra Huffman, president of the Center to Prevent Childhood
Malnutrition, said that breast feeding is less common in the United
States than in Canada, Sweden, the Netherlands or Australia.
   ``The United States has far to go if we are to catch up with
breast-feeding rates in those developed countries, all of which
have lower infant mortality rates than the United Statses,'' she
testified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
