<FIRST>u p AM-AsWyomingGoes Bjt   04-27 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-As Wyoming Goes, Bjt,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Wins Wyoming House Seat, Making One of Three in Bush Era</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans breathed easier Thursday after
Craig Thomas' solid victory in a hotly contested congressional race
in Wyoming, but Democrats still claimed ``a lot of momentum'' from
the three special elections during George Bush's first 100 days as
president.
   ``We feel good about two out of three,'' said Democratic Party
chairman Ron Brown.
   After a 40-day campaign marked by heavy involvement by both
national parties, Thomas defeated Democrat John Vinich on Wednesday
for the House seat given up by Republican Dick Cheney when he was
appointed secretary of defense.
   Unofficial returns gave Thomas 74,258 votes, or 52 percent, to
Vinich's 60,821 votes, or 43 percent.
   There were few claims that the contest had any broad national
importance, with most analysts concluding merely that as Wyoming
goes, so goes Wyoming.
   ``It's a strain to try to come up with anything of national
significance,'' said Tom Mann, director of governmental studies at
the Brookings Institution.
   ``Unlike the Democrats, who like to beat their breasts and claim
national implications in every special election, we will simply say
that in this one the best man won,'' said Rep. Guy Vander Jagt of
Michigan, chairman of the House GOP campaign committee.
   Brown noted that the Democrats won the first two special House
elections this year and he said a victory in Wyoming would have
been ``like winning the Pennsylvania lottery.''
   ``It's the first thing after a presidential election where the
Republicans win and are feeling pretty full of themselves and we
come in and the first three tests do real well,'' said Brown.
   The possibility that the Democrats might make it three in a row
had Republicans feeling on edge early in the Wyoming campaign,
despite the fact Republicans outnumber Democrats three-to-two among
the state's registered voters.
   ``It's like getting a big ball and chain cut,'' said GOP
campaign committee spokesman John Buckley of the returns from
Wyoming.
   ``I think we have a lot of momentum coming out of this series of
three special elections,'' said Howard Schloss, spokesman for the
Democratic House campaign committee.
   The president did not campaign in Wyoming. Any possibility that
he might was quashed when out-of-state involvement became in issue
on both sides.
   After Bush's landslide victory over Democrat Michael Dukakis in
November _ the fifth GOP victory in the last six presidential
elections _ Republicans set their sights on diminishing if not
ending Democratic dominance of Congress.
   The battle was joined early with a special election last month
in Indiana to fill the House seat once held by Vice President Dan
Quayle. Democrat Jill Long was the upset victor after a campaign in
which she tagged her GOP opponent as soft on taxes, a theme often
used against Democrats by GOP candidates.
   In a second special election one week later in Alabama, the
Democrats held a seat by a landslide margin, dashing Republican
hopes for a show of strength in the Deep South.
   Ed Rollins, who had signed on with the GOP campaign committee at
a fee of $250,000 a year, proclaimed the stakes were high in
Wyoming and said the campaign was ``something I've had my hands on
since day one.''
   Democrat Vinich immediately started running ads talking about
``outside Washington consultants'' taking control of the Thomas
campaign.
   Thomas countered with ads saying that 80 percent of Vinich's
campaign money came from out-of-state labor unions.
   The Democrat started the Wyoming campaign with a big edge over
Thomas in name recognition. Five months earlier, Vinich had come
within 1,322 votes of upsetting Sen. Malcolm Wallop.
   Vander Jagt chided the Democrats for running a Willie
Horton-style campaign that accused Thomas of being soft on
criminals.
   ``It was not a pleasant campaign,'' he said.
   Brown said he planned to study polling results to determine the
impact of the negative ads run in Wyoming.
   ``It's too early to tell,'' he said.
   In the presidential campaign, Bush succeeded in tagging Dukakis
as soft on crime by citing a Massachusetts prison furlough program
and particularly the case of Horton, a convict who left while on
furlough and raped a woman in Maryland.
   In Wyoming, Vinich ran ads accusing Thomas of being soft on
criminals by voting for legislation that allowed certain felons to
serve sentences in county jails rather than the state prison. The
ads were criticized by many Democrats who pointed out that the
legislation passed both chambers of the Wyoming Legislature with
only three dissenting votes and then was signed by a Democratic
governor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
