<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WoodyGuthrie     04-27 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Woody Guthrie,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Folk Singer Still Sore Topic In His Hometown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKEMAH, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some townspeople won't claim folk singer
Woody Guthrie as a native son, while others say the town hasn't
done enough to capitalize on the Dust Bowl balladeer and lure
tourists whizzing past on Interstate 40.
   The decades-old argument is raised anew this week because
Guthrie's son, Arlo, is giving a benefit concert Saturday at
Okemah's venerable Crystal Theatre.
   It will be Arlo Guthrie's first performance in his father's
hometown.
   ``I don't feel an obligation to push my dad on anyone,'' the
younger Guthrie said in a recent interview. ``His work, his life
can stand on its own. Time and history have spoken for him. Now, I
can relax a bit and just have fun with his music and just be my
dad's kid.''
   Theater owner Mark Smyth said he has sold out the 698-seat
theater at $10 a ticket, but he said many of those attending will
be from out of town.
   ``I wouldn't go across the street to hear it,'' said Dorothy
Webb, an Okemah resident since 1931. ``I'm not for it at all, and
I'm against it.''
   Detractors call Woody Guthrie, whose songs included ``This Land
is Your Land,'' a Communist and a ``militant atheist.'' Supporters
say he was a patriot and a defender of the downtrodden.
   ``If you'd read what Woody wrote, you'd know how he felt,'' said
Guthrie's sister, Mary Jo Edgmon of Seminole.
   Last week, local funeral home director Bart Webb, Mrs. Webb's
son, placed a poster outside the downtown American Legion hall
proclaiming ``Woody Was No Hero.'' A local newspaper reporter who
tore it down faces municipal charges.
   For years, a town water tower has proclaimed to traffic on I-40
that Okemah is Guthrie's home. But when the ramshackle house
Guthrie lived in until he left Okemah at age 17 began falling down,
locals let it go. Its pieces are stored for possible future
restoration.
   Guthrie was born 76 years ago in this central Oklahoma town of
3,300. He died in 1967 at age 55 of Huntington's chorea, a
hereditary degenerative disorder.
   There are no monuments to him in Oklahoma. His ashes were
scattered over the Atlantic.
   Guthrie denied he was a Communist, and the House Un-American
Activities Committee that focused on entertainers in the 1950s
didn't call him to testify.
   Guy Logsdon, a retired University of Tulsa professor who has
lectured about Guthrie and performed his music for years, noted
that Guthrie served in the Merchant Marine during World War II.
   ``Woody was outspoken. He was a radical in a lot of ways and
controversial,'' Logsdon said. ``Most people never considered Woody
a threat to the security of this nation.
   ``Woody was very patriotic. All you have to do is look at his
songs.''
   Guthrie wrote more than 1,000 songs, including classics such as
``So Long, It's Been Good to Know You.'' Many have become folk
standards.
   He led a vagabond existence after leaving Okemah, writing and
performing about what he saw in migrant worker camps from Oklahoma
to California. His songs railed against the abuses of the poor.
   Smyth, an Okemah native, guessed that the town's residents are
``80 percent pro-Woody.''
   ``But the little core group that are against Woody are pretty
vocal,'' he said.
   ``Two or three people, they speak out against Woody,'' said
Logsdon. ``Then there has been the right-wing element, it has
always circulated things quietly against Woody.
   ``There will always be those who don't like Woody, and don't
know why. Woody liked Okemah. He was proud of Oklahoma and Okemah.
He loved both places. He didn't always paint a pretty picture,
because he wrote what he experienced.''
   Logsdon said Guthrie would not have been surprised by the debate.
   ``He would enjoy the controversy and would laugh,'' he said.
``He had the ability to laugh at himself and laugh at life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890427-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1431EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle 2ndLd-Writethru a0542 04-27 0823</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0542,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Countdown On Track For Friday Shuttle Launch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: 2nd and 3rd graf new from pre-flight briefing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trouble-free countdown gave NASA
workers some breathing room today as preparations proceeded toward
Friday's midafternoon launch of Atlantis and five astronauts. The
mission will propel a probe to Venus on the first space shuttle
planetary mission.
   ``We're ready to go fly,'' said Richard Truly, the former
astronaut who has been nominated as NASA administrator. The
Magellan spacecraft, ready for its 15-month flight to Venus, ``is
in good shape,'' said Lennard Fisk, NASA's chief scientist. After
an 11-year hiatus in deep space exploration, he said, ``No one is
going to question our leadership in planetary (flight) again.''
   Officials called it their smoothest countdown in 29 shuttle
missions.
   ``We just don't have anything out there that we're worried
about; it's been a real smooth count and we expect it to continue
that way,'' NASA test director Ronald Phelps told reporters.
   Phelps spoke as the countdown was halted for 15-hours, 34
minutes. The hold was planned to allow for any catchup work in case
of problems, but Phelps said there were none.
   As the NASA crew prepared for its four-day flight, three Soviet
cosmonauts returned to Earth today, leaving the Mir space station
unmanned for the first time in more than two years. Three of the
cosmonauts had been in orbit for five months, the third for eight
months.
   When the Atlantis count resumes shortly before midnight, the
launch team will make preparation to begin loading more than
500,000 gallons of propellant into Atlantis' fuel tanks.
   The only concern, and it was slight, was the possibility of
crosswinds of more than 17 mph that could be dangerous if the
shuttle had to make an emergency landing on a runway near the
launch pad.
   Shuttle managers assessed all facets of the flight during a
day-long meeting Wednesday and reported, ``all preparations are
progressing satisfactorily. There are no technical or programmatic
issues. ... Weather is expected to be good.''
   Liftoff of the 29th shuttle mission and the fourth since the
Challenger explosion three years ago is set for 2:24 p.m. Friday.
The launch team will have only a 23-minute period in which to get
the shuttle off the ground because of the need to deploy the
Magellan probe from a precise point in space and the requirement
that liftoff occur before darkness falls on emergency landing sites
in Spain and Morocco.
   The astronauts were to review flight plans and make efficiency
runs in jet aircraft today.
   They are commander David Walker, pilot Ron Grabe and mission
specialists Mary Cleave, Mark Lee and Norm Thagard.
   Late Friday, about six hours after liftoff, Lee and Cleave will
release Magellan from the cargo bay and an hour later a rocket will
hurl the 7,600-pound payload on a 450-day voyage to Venus.
   Magellan is to orbit the cloud-veiled planet and map up to 90
percent of the surface with a high resolution radar system.
   Its images should reveal details as small as 100 yards across,
about the size of a football field. This is 10 times sharper than
any previous pictures of the planet.
   ``All our previous data from Venus has been low resolution and
about all that data has done is tell us basically there are
continent-size mountain masses on Venus and that there are
extensive rolling plains,'' Magellan project scientist Joseph Boyce
said Friday.
   ``We don't know whether Venus ever had oceans, we don't know how
Venus rids itself of its internal heat, and we don't know if Venus
is still volcanically active,'' he said. ``Magellan's goal is to
answer these questions and improve on our knowledge of the
geophysical and geological properties of Venus and the nature of
processes that shape its surface.''
   Boyce said the images could help scientists understand how Earth
and its sister planet Venus evolved so differently, even though
they basically were identical when formed at the beginning of the
solar system.
   The surface temperature on Venus is 900 degrees Fahrenheit and
its atmospheric pressure is 90 times that of Earth's. The
atmosphere is composed primarily of carbon dioxide and a thick
cloud of sulfuric acid drops.
   John H. Gerpheide, Magellan project manager, said the $550
million Magellan mission will mark ``the beginning of a big year
for the planetary program.''
   ``In August the Voyager spacecraft will fly by Neptune and in
October we'll launch Galileo to Jupiter,'' he told reporters
Wednesday.
   ``So after an 11-year gap in the planetary program, we're
anxious to get started,'' he said. ``We have our team in place .. .
and the butterflies are soon to arrive.''
   The last planetary mission launched by the United States was the
1978 Pioneer-Venus probe. Voyager 2, launched in 1977, will take
the first closeup look at distant Neptune in August after earlier
exploring Jupiter, Saturn and Uranus.
</TEXT>
