<FIRST>u a PM-PlaneDoorHearing 2ndLd-Writethru a0450 04-27 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Door Hearing, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0450,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Says Airline Fell Short in Inspecting Door</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 15 grafs to UPDATE with United saying that inspection
was not skipped by was less than FAA required, testimony today by Boeing
engineer. Picks up 12th graf, `United inspected...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A clerical error caused United Airlines to fail
to follow federal requirements in inspecting the cargo door that
blew off the jumbo jetliner two months later, killing nine people,
the company said today.
   Robert Doll, United vice president for technical services, told
federal investigators Wednesday the airline was unaware it had to
inspect the locking mechanism after the cargo door was repaired
Dec. 23 in Chicago.
   Doll clarified his statement today, saying a partial inspection
was made. Although it was not as thorough as the Federal Aviation
Administration required, company repairmen were satisfied the door
was operating properly, he said.
   Company officials stressed that the Boeing 747 door had been
inspected in November 1988, three months before the accident, and
no problems were found.
   A Boeing Co. engineer testified today that the plane
manufacturer had no idea why on Feb. 24, the door and part of the
fuselage tore off as United Flight 811 was climbing to 23,000 feet
85 miles southwest of Honolulu.
   Boeing engineering manager James Fitzgerald also told the
National Transportation Safety Board the company had made no
projections about the effects of a cargo-door loss.
   ``The doors are not designed to come off the airplane,''
Fitzgerald said. ``We had no way of knowing exactly what would
happen if a door came open in flight.''
   Fitzgerald refused to speculate on how the accident happened.
   He came under extensive questioning from Capt. Douglas Robinson
of the Air Line Pilots Association, who criticized Boeing's
contention that the door is safe in the wake of the United accident
and a 1987 incident when a door partly opened in mid-flight on a
Pan Am flight.
   ``We cannot explain the Pan American incident and we have the
United accident where the door failed, but we steadfastly are
saying the door is safe,'' Robinson said.
   He also noted that the two known failures of 747 cargo doors
both involved forward cargo doors, and advised the company to study
why.
   Fitzgerald also said Boeing is looking at ways to improve the
warning system to ensure the cargo doors are closed before takeoff,
but has not determined what to do or even if changes in the present
systms are necessary.
   Doll's testimony Wednesday came during a day when United
officials were grilled about the operation and maintenance of the
800-pound cargo doors. Speculation has focused on a possible
malfunction in the locking mechanism of the cargo door, which
remains on the bottom of the Pacific.
   The plane was bound for Sydney, Australia, with 337 passengers
and a crew of 18.
   After the Pan Am incident, the FAA proposed new rules requiring
that lock mechanisms of all 747s be visually inspected for signs of
wear by July 31, 1988, said United spokesman Robert Doughty.
   United inspected all 31 of its 747s and found no problems,
Doughty said.
   The FAA also required that aluminum parts of locking mechanisms
be reinforced with steel, which United also began to perform.
   But a clerical error caused the company to miss a third
requirement regarding cargo doors that had been opened and closed
manually because of a problem with the electrical system.
   That requirement was that once those doors were repaired, they
had to be reinspected for damage, Doughty said.
   A clerk who retyped the message from Boeing Co., the aircraft
manufacturer, into United's internal communication system
apparently dropped six key words, Doll told the board.
   The note, with the words that were dropped in parentheses, read:
``The special procedures ... for manual door operation must be
continued and performed prior to takeoff following each operation
of the door until electrical restoration (and operations are
resumed and reinspection) of the lock sectors has been accomplished
... ''
   ``It was a clerical error,'' Doughty said.
   The cargo door of the 747 developed electrical problems during
flights over the Pacific in December 1988, and the door was
operated manually for more than a week before repairs were made in
Chicago, company officials said.
   Doll told investigators he would like to see the door raised
from 17,000 feet of water, but the safety board has made no
decision on that yet.
   Doll also said he is unconvinced the locking machanism was the
culprit because United has had no similar problems.
   He told investigators the 747 did not have a history of unusual
cargo door problems, and that United recorded 112 problems with
forward and aft cargo doors in all of its 747s from March 1986 to
February 1989. Eight of those were on the ill-fated plane, he said.
</TEXT>
