<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     04-27 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Clash With Police, Dissidents Vow Demonstrations Despite
Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 20,000 striking workers and
students clashed with riot police in Seoul and seven other cities
Thursday, and dissidents planned weekend demonstrations in defiance
of a government ban.
   About 10,000 striking workers from 12 plants fought police with
rocks and firebombs in the southeastern industrial city of
Changwon, demanding the release of jailed strike leaders.
   In the nearby port of Masan, about 3,000 workers also clashed
with police, demanding pay increases and the release of strike
leaders. Protesters set fire to a governing office and threw rocks
at several police posts.
   About 1,000 students in the southern city of Kwangju clashed
with police after a campus rally at which they burned effigies of
President Bush and President Roh Tae-woo.
   Police officials said two riot troopers had been seriously
injured in Changwon, but they had no further details. It was not
known immediately if there were any workers injured or arrested.
   In Seoul, an estimated 4,500 students hulring rocks and
firebombs battled police at three universities in support of
striking workers and scheduled border talks between students of
South and North Korea.
   About 10,000 students at the state-run Seoul National University
boycotted classes and held an anti-government campus rally,
denouncing alleged government suppression of labor movement.
   ``Down with Roh Tae-woo,'' students shouted, shooting clenched
fists into the sky.
   After the student rally, about 3,000 tried to march into the
streets, hurling rocks and firebombs. Police fired tear gas to
drive them back.
   No injuries or arrests were reported.
   Campus clashes were also reported in Anyang, Chunchon, Chongju
and Taejon.
   Student leaders said they will march to the border village of
Panmunjom Friday for talks with North Korean students on uniting
the Korean peninsula and taking part in an international youth
festival in Pyongyang in July.
   Authorities outlawed the march and said police would block it.
Last year, several marches for unification were blocked by police.
   The United National Democratic Movement, the main dissident
alliance, said they would hold a labor rally Sunday in Seoul
despite a government ban and said police would be responsible for
any violence.
   About 30 labor leaders were arrested in police raids in Seoul
Thursday as the government moved against radical labor groups,
police said. Those arrested face charges of staging illegal
strikes, they said.
   The radical students have been staging almost daily violent
protests in recent weeks to demand the overthrow of the Roh
government. The radicals and allied dissident groups lack
widespread popular support and are not seen as a threat to the Roh
government.
   But government leaders are concerned about growing labor unrest
and a wave of increasingly violent strikes for better pay and
improved working conditions. Student and dissident groups are
attempting to unite with workers to build an anti-government
alliance.
   Dissident leaders claim Roh is a front for military rule and
demand the former general step down. Roh won a December 1987
election after rival opposition candidates split the opposition
vote.
</TEXT>
