<FIRST>u a PM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0481 04-27 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0481,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Drops Anchor, Beach Cleanup Effort Gets Big Boost</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with state questioning Exxon cleanup
figures, revises spill estimate, picking up 5th graf pvs, `The landing...'.
DELETES 9th graf pvs, `Exxon has...', not outdated. ADDS 2 grafs on end
with wildlife report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has arrived to help in an assault
on gummed-up beaches and bays, more than doubling cleanup efforts
five weeks after the nation's worst oil spill fouled Prince William
Sound.
   After loading workers and supplies in Valdez, the USS Juneau was
anchored today near Smith Island as part of Exxon's state-guided
effort to clean rocky beaches where seals and sea lions have their
pups.
   ``The Juneau allows us to accelerate the pace of the cleanup.
That's key,'' said Exxon spokesman Joe Tucker.
   The top state environmental official today disputed Exxon's
estimate of how the cleanup is going, saying more study was needed
before concluding that just 10 percent of the oil remained
unaccounted-for. Exxon had stated that 17 percent of the spilled
oil had been recovered and 73 percent has dissipated.
   ``It's important for our credibility we want to make sure we
take all the steps necessary to make an assessment, even if Exxon
is willing to go out on a limb and provide you with figures that
may be both gross and inaccurate,'' Alaska's environmental
commissioner Dennis Kelso said.
   The state also revised its estimate of the total amount of oil
spilled downward, to 10.9 million gallons from 11.2 million
gallons. Exxon's estimate of the oil spill remains 10.1 million
gallons.
   The arrival of the Juneau could spell good news for marine
mammals in the sound, where the most heavily oiled beaches are.
   ``The ship carries nine landing craft,'' Tucker said of the
Juneau. ``Each will be equipped by Exxon with pumps and heaters,
enabling the company to transport crews to work areas more quickly.
The crew will just stay out there.''
   The landing transport is carrying 400 workers who were to get
off each morning and return to sleep at night. About 250 workers
who had been cleaning Eleanor Island today moved to Green Island.
Most of them sleep on barges nearby.
   After three days of 15-to-20-foot seas and gale-force winds
whipping snow in some areas, skimmers returned to work Wednesday in
the sound and the Gulf of Alaska. Today's forecast called for light
rain and wind, and seas of three feet.
   Confirmed reports have placed the oil at Cape Douglas on the
Alaska Peninsula, 275 miles west of where the Exxon Valdez ran
aground on Bligh Reef on March 24 in a picturesque area rich in
marine life.
   Neither Exxon, which conducts daily overflights of the area, nor
the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration could confirm a
report by a National Park Service officer that oil was spotted 100
miles south of Cape Douglas at Kashvik Bay on the Alaska Peninsula.
   The spreading oil sheen has crept into energy politics as well
as the coves that make up Kenai Fjords National Park 100 miles
south of Anchorage.
   A letter to the House Interior Committee released Wednesday by
Gov. Steve Cowper urged Congress to buy back oil exploration leases
sold for Bristol Bay, an area Cowper said produces $1 billion a
year in seafood.
   ``Alaskans already have had to face the closure of this year's
multimillion-dollar Prince William Sound herring fishery and black
cod fishery, and the attendant loss of jobs and community
stability,'' Cowper wrote.
   ``The spector of such an event in Bristol Bay is unthinkable,''
Cowper said. ``It is time to cancel the sale and refund the bid
money.''
   But President Bush, speaking in Austin to a joint session of the
Texas Legislature, warned that the nation must not retreat from oil
exploration because of the spill.
   ``We are using federal resources intelligently in the cleanup
effort,'' he said. ``We are working with industry to develop an
improved plan in the event of a future spill.
   ``But shutting down our domestic energy production is no answer,
and would merely increase our dependence on foreign oil,'' Bush
said. To avoid that, ``we must return to high levels of exploratory
drilling.''
   While some wildlife has moved out of oiled areas, bald eagles
and other scavengers have been drawn to it, said Walt Steiglitz,
regional director for the U.S. Fish &amp; Wildlife Service.
   Steiglitz said in a news release that eagles and gulls that have
moved in to feed on the carrion will become ``secondary victims of
the oil by contamination through the food chain.'' Four eagles have
been reported dead.
</TEXT>
