<FIRST>r a AM-LargestDeathRow     04-27 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Largest Death Row,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas' 300 Inmate Death Row Now Nation's Largest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a barred door slammed shut behind
convicted killer Martin Vega on the steamy row of identical cells
known simply as J-23, Texas's death row became the largest in the
nation.
   Vega, whose white prison suit bears an orange tag with his name
and the number ``DR 932,'' is the 300th person on death row in
Texas, according to Department of Corrections statistics this week.
   Florida, which in recent years has held the largest number of
convicted killers awaiting execution, this week has 299 death row
inmates, according to Paula Tully of the Florida Department of
Corrections.
   ``It's a pretty good indication that the people of Texas support
the death penalty if they keep sending people there,'' said Ron
Dusek, a spokesman for Texas Attorney General Jim Mattox.
   Texas also leads the nation in the number of people put to death
since the U.S. Supreme Court in 1976 allowed capital punishment to
resume. Thirty men have been given lethal injection at the Walls
Unit in Huntsville, starting with Charlie Brooks in December 1982.
   By that time, Texas had 130 others awaiting the same fate as
Brooks.
   During the early 1980s, death row grew by about two per month.
As the pace of executions quickened, so did the number of people
awaiting death. In 1986, 43 new inmates joined the ranks while 10
were executed. An additional 36 came the next year, and the
three-per-month average continues now.
   But while death row in Texas has grown _ it now incorporates
five prison wings _ the number of executions has fallen. Only three
were put to death last year and just one so far in 1989 as inmates'
attorneys have won Supreme Court review of cases.
   ``The way it's growing, they can dedicate half the farm to death
row in the next five years, unless they do away with the death
penalty,'' says Jim Beathard, awaiting execution for a killing
spree in which three members of a family died in 1984.
   Jim Vanderbilt, who has been on the row since 1976 and is among
the most senior of all inmates, fears a legal breakthrough will
trigger many executions.
   ``The water is building up behind the dam,'' Vanderbilt says.
``And if they let the dam overflow or if they remove the dam, then
there's going to be a flood.''
   For Vega, 42, a self-described jack-of-all-trades who was
convcted in February of the 1985 slaying of his wife's former
husband, in what authorities said was an attempt to collect the
man's insurance, the move to death row was his fourth trip to the
Texas prison system. Included among his terms was a two-year stint
for robbery which kept him behind bars for just one week before he
was released.
   Death row, he says, is different.
   ``It's a title we have and under that title we're supposed to be
dangerous,'' he said in an interview this week. ``But Lord knows a
lot of people here are not dangerous. I'm not saying all _ but
some.''
   Vega, from Luling, says he misses ``freedom, my family, women,
money, breathing the fresh air and just being able to raise my
hands and say `I'm free!'''
   But the Texas prison system, mandated by federal court orders
this decade to improve prison conditions and inmate rights, is a
much better place now, Vega says.
   One prison beating in the old days left him with a severed
tendon that has left the little finger of his left hand immobile.
   ``Most officials I have encountered have been nice so far,'' he
says. ``If you have a question, they will answer. Since the time
I've been back here, TDC has not bothered me at all. It's good.''
</TEXT>
