<FIRST>u i AM-Israel Bjt   04-27 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, Bjt,0828</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clashes Kill 3, Injure Scores; Army Says Figures Inflated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>USARIN, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and
killed three Palestinians and wounded 74 others in widespread
clashes Thursday in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, Arab
reports and hospital officials said.
   The army reported only eight woundings and accused Palestinians
of inflating the figure to gain sympathy.
   The gunshot wounds reported by Palestinian hospitals brought to
more than 225 the number reported injured in clashes with soldiers
this week. The army has confirmed only 22.
   In the West Bank, more than 100 teen-agers from Jewish
settlements hiked near the Palestinian village of Beita, where an
Israeli girl was killed a year ago, to symbolize their demand that
the occupied lands be part of Israel.
   ``It's our country. We must walk here,'' said 16-year-old Biti
Shaovitz from the settlement of Karnei Shomrom.
   Soldiers and armed settler leaders guarded the hikers. Under an
agreement with the army, they did not enter Beita, where
15-year-old Terza Porat was accidentally killed by a Jewish
bodyguard a year ago when a group of hikers got involved in a
confrontation with stone-throwing Arabs.
   Before Thursday's hike, soldiers raided the village to search
for Palestinian activists. Two youths were wounded by army gunfire,
a military spokesman said. Arab reports said five were wounded.
   The army's deputy spokesman, Col. Renaan Gissin, said, ``The
reason you see a greater number of wounded is because of a
deliberate attempt by Palestinians to overload the list.''
   ``There is no dramatic increase in the number of wounded,'' he
said.
   The wounded figures from hospitals include people who are
treated for gunshot wounds, then released. The army says it does
not include these since it cannot verify if they were shot by
soldiers or fellow Palestinians.
   ``This makes it easy for the Palestinians to inflate the
figures,'' said Gissin.
   He added the army also cannot confirm gunshot victims who go to
private hospitals or clinics, only those treated in government
hospitals.
   Of the 74 reported treated in five Arab hospitals on Thursday,
the army confirmed 11 Palestinians wounded, eight from the West
Bank and three from Gaza.
   An official at the U.N. Relief and Works Agency, which is
responsible for Palestinians refugees, said he had reports of 30
gunshot wounds by midafternoon in Gaza and was still receiving
reports. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Of the 154 reported wounded earlier in the week, the army
confirmed 14.
   The army reported that soldiers Thursday ran into a violent
protest in the Askar refugee camp near the West Bank town of Nablus
and opened fire, killing one Palestinian.
   The victim, Imad Muhammad Harbieh, 20, was shot in the chest,
hospital officials said.
   In the Gaza Strip, Ali Said Gharableh, 30, died of a gunshot
wound to the chest in a clash with soldiers after Moslem prayers at
a mosque in Gaza City, hospital officials said.
   Also in Gaza, 15-year-old Ashraf Samir Ead was shot in the chest
in a protest in the town of Rafah and died en route to the
hospital, Arab reporters said.
   The army was checking the reports of the deaths in Gaza.
   Thursday's deaths raised to 454 the number of Arabs reported
killed in the revolt, which began in December 1988. Eighteen
Israelis have died.
   On Thursday, the PLO-backed leadership of the uprising issued a
leaflet rejecting plans by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to hold
elections in the occupied lands. The leaflet said the plan was
attempt to divide the Palestinians and circumvent the PLO.
   An aide to Shamir said Israel will not offer an alternative to
Shamir's election proposal, despite the rejection of the plan.
   On Wednesday, 83 prominent residents in the occupied lands
rejected the idea, calling the elections a ploy to end the uprising
without giving the Palestinians what they want: an independent
state.
   ``This is the best program we can suggest to them,'' said Shamir
spokesman Yossi Ahimeir.
   Shamir's plan calls for elections of local Palestinians to
negotiate an interim peace with Israel, to be followed by talks on
the final status of the occupied lands.
   Shamir, who has repeatedly rejected the Palestinians' demands
for their own state and talks with the PLO, said on Israel army
radio: ``We have heard an announcement from some of our neighbors
that they reject our proposals. I hope this is not their last
word.''
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin told Israel Radio if Palestinians
turn down the peace proposal, Israel must adopt a policy ``of a
more intense action of putting down first of all the violence.''
   This, he said, ``will bring about, between half a year to a
year, acceptance of the political way by elements in the Arab world
and, first and foremost, in the territories.''
</TEXT>
