<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Passover     04-27 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Passover,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shanghai Jews Return To Their Roots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passover, the Jewish holiday of exodus, was a
festival of return this year for a group of Jews who lived in
Shanghai more than four decades ago.
   ``It was symbolic of the return of a Jewish presence to China''
said Yosef Tekoah, Israel's former ambassador to the United
Nations, said of the Passover seder celebrated this year in China's
largest city.
   Tekoah, as honorary chairman of the International Assembly of
Jews in China, last week led 25 Shanghai Jews or their descendants
back to the city that offered thousands of Jews refuge from
persecution in the first half of this century.
   The tour, which included 50 others from the United States,
Israel and other countries, also provided new impetus to growing
contacts between China and Israel, which have no diplomatic
relations.
   For most on the trip, nostalgia took precedence over politics.
Tekoah, chancellor of Ben Gurion University of the Negev, recited
the Kaddish, or prayer for the dead, at the synagogue, now a law
college auditorium, where he prayed with his parents as a boy.
   Sasson Jacoby, foreign editor of the Jerusalem Post, returned to
the house where he spent his childhood. He also found his old
synagogue, now a Shanghai government education bureau office.
   ``Nothing has changed. They haven't even repainted the
interior,'' he said. The Red Guard, the young leftists who
destroyed houses of worship throughout China during the 1966-76
Cultural Revolution, apparently failed to discover the Hebrew
inscriptions now hidden behind a movie screen.
   The group also found several former Jewish cultural centers. At
one, they ran into a Chinese wedding in what is now a public hall.
   ``Most of it remains as we remember it,'' Tekoah said, adding
that while the homes in the old foreign quarters are run down,
today's Shanghai is vibrant with activity. Gone are the downtrodden
masses of beggars, rickshaw drivers and the desperately poor.
   The Shanghai Jewish community dates back at least to the 19th
century when Jacoby's ancestors arrived from Baghdad.
   The Iraqi Jewish community, numbering about 1,000, included
families such as the Sassoons and Kadoories who were to become rich
in the China trade. The Sassoon family in 1921 helped build their
synagogue, and Jacoby's father was once the temple's rabbi.
   The next wave, including Tekoah's family, were refugees from the
Bolshevik Revolution. Many of the 8,000 Russian Jews first stopped
in Harbin and other northeastern China cities.
   The third and largest group was German and other central
European Jews escaping Nazi persecution before and during World War
II. From 20,000 to 25,000 eventually made their way to Shanghai,
Tekoah said.
   ``China occupies a very special place,'' Tekoah said. ``It is
the only country in the entire world that didn't know what
anti-Semitism is. The Chinese people by their nature are very
tolerant, and Jewish people have benefited from that.''
   Tekoah said that in his speech at the Passover seder, he spoke
of parallels between two of the world's oldest cultures. Both value
scholarship and the family, he said, and both are very pragmatic in
their approaches to life.
   Jewish traders are believed to have settled in China even before
the beginning of the Christian era, but the first permanent Jewish
community was probably established in the 11th century in Kaifeng,
in central China.
   The Kaifeng Jews, who may have arrived by way of India,
flourished until the 19th century when they assimilated with the
Chinese and their customs and rituals gradually disappeared.
   During their Shanghai visit, the tour met with the Shanghai
Judaic Studies Association, a group of Chinese scholars formed
several months ago to study the heritage of Judaism in Kaifeng and
other Chinese cities.
   ``They want to be in touch with Jewish organizations in
Israel,'' Tekoah said. He said the forming of such a group, and the
warm reception they received in Shanghai, were indications of
increased contacts between Israel and China, long a firm supporter
of Arab causes.
   ``As Mao Tse-tung said, a 1,000-mile journey begins with a
single step.''
   The Jewish community in Shanghai dissolved in 1948 and 1949 with
the communist takeover and the creation of the Jewish state in
Israel. But now, Tekoah said, the links have been restored. ``For
each one of us this was a very moving return to our roots.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
