<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     04-27 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Kabul on Anniversary of Communist Coup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas bombarded Kabul with
rocket fire Thursday, the 11th anniversary of the communist coup,
and officials said at least six people were killed and four were
injured.
   The military fired back with long-range missiles into the
surrounding mountains where the insurgents are hiding.
   The guerrillas issued a statment from their Peshawar, Pakistan,
headquarters describing the 1978 revolution as ``the beginning of
more than a decade-long nightmare.''
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency said Iran-based guerrillas
and Afghan refugees marched in Tehran to protest the communist coup.
   Hundreds of Afghan refugees in New Delhi also marched and burned
an effigy of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, whose
government backs the Afghan leadership.
   ``Long live Afghanistan! Down with Russia! Down with
communism!'' they shouted while marching near Parliament.
   In a speech to diplomats and visiting delegations, President
Najib said the army has proved it can defend Afghanistan without
the help of Soviet troops, who completed their withdrawal from the
country Feb. 15.
   ``The enemies had set a deadline of two or three weeks after the
withdrawal for occupying Kabul,'' Najib said. ``You can see that
... the armed forces have created an unsurmountable barrier before
the aggressors.''
   As he spoke to 1,500 people at the presidential palace, rockets
and explosions could be heard outside.
   Fifteen rockets hit Kabul starting at sunrise.
   One landed in the central square, where a day earlier the
government celebrated the anniversary with a military parade. The
parade was held a day before the actual anniversary because of
fears of attacks.
   There had been speculation for weeks the guerrillas would send a
volley of rockets into the city of 2.25 million people Thursday.
   The dead included two soldiers and a member of the local
security forces. One rocket killed two women, injured two children
and a man, and destroyed three mud-and-stone houses, military
officials said.
   About half a mile away, another woman died and a child had his
legs blown off when a rocket slammed into their house, the
officials said on condition of anonymity.
   This year's observance of the Saur, or April revolution, was
subdued. Most businesses closed and there were few people or
vehicles in the streets, which were lined with the black, red and
green Afghan flag, and the red flag of the ruling People's
Democratic Party.
   The Moslem insurgency began after the coup that ousted President
Mohammed Daoud on April 27, 1978. More than 1 million people have
died in the fighting and 5 million Afghans _ about one-third of the
country's population _ fled to neighboring Pakistan and Iran.
   Soviet military forces entered Afghanistan in December 1979,
replaced one communist government with another and stayed to help
fight the insurgents, known as mujahedeen or Islamic holy warriors.
   Najib became president in May 1986. On May 15, 1988, the Red
Army began leaving Afghanistan under a U.N.-sponsored accord.
</TEXT>
