<FIRST>r w AM-NewsMedia-North     04-27 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-News Media-North,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Lawyers, ACLU, News Media on Same Side in Document Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North's lawyers and a civil liberties
group are joining 10 news organizations in seeking release of a
sealed document described to North's trial jury by his principal
lawyer.
   The news organizations, including The Associated Press, are
battling the Justice Department in the U.S. Court of Appeals in an
attempt to gain access to the stipulation, which has been given to
the jury.
   The document summarizes intelligence intercepts concerning a
CIA-assisted arms shipment from Israel to Iran in the early stages
of the Iran-Conta affair.
   The news organizations are seeking a speedy hearing on their
request, saying that North's lawyers were free to disclose ``the
entire stipulation on the public record'' during final arguments in
his criminal trial. North lawyer Brendan Sullivan described what
the document shows in open court on April 19, but the Justice
Department says full disclosure ``would threaten national
security.''
   The stipulation describes U.S. government tracking of the
November 1985 shipment of Hawk missiles to Iran.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell on Saturday rejected the
motion of the news organizations to gain access to the stipulation,
saying it ``is a classified document.'' The organizations went to
the appeals court Monday.
   The Justice Department now wants the matter sent back to
district court to give the government an opportunity to spell out
in secret to the judge why the press should be denied access.
Alternatively, the department wants 14 days to file a brief in the
appeals court.
   On Thursday, the news organizations opposed both government
requests, saying the case should remain in the appeals court and
that briefs should be filed by next Tuesday.
   The American Civil Liberties Union supports the news media's
request for an expedited hearing on the request for public
disclosure.
   ``The government has made no attempt here to show any compelling
interest for sealing an exhibit which has been shown to the jury
and partially read in open court,'' stated the motion by ACLU
lawyer Kate Martin.
   North's lawyers say nondisclosure of an exhibit at a criminal
trial is incompatible with the Sixth Amendment guarantee of a
public trial and with the Classified Information Procedures Act.
CIPA makes no provision for partial release of a trial exhibit to
jurors but not to the public, said North's lawyers.
   Court security officers deleted portions of Sullivan's courtroom
comments on the intercepts from the official court transcript, but
Gesell ruled that they must be restored.
   One deleted passage said that employing certain
intelligence-gathering methods allowed North to know ``exactly what
was going on in the Iranian initiative and exactly what was
happening with respect to the transfer of missiles to Iran.''
Another deleted passage said the intercepts were delivered to
high-ranking government officials, including CIA Director William
Casey and Deputy National Security Adviser John Poindexter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
