<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     04-27 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Missiles,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Leaders Attack U.S. Rejection Of Missile Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German leaders on Thursday
criticized Washington's rejection of superpower talks on
short-range nuclear weapons and urged NATO to show more readiness
to deal with the Soviet bloc.
   ``There is much to fear in this world. But we certainly don't
have to fear negotiations, or a Soviet Union that is ready to
talk,'' Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher told Parliament,
winning cheers and applause from opposition as well as government
party lawmakers.
   His remarks followed a major policy speech in Parliament by
Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Kohl also stepped up pressure on the United States to agree to
negotiations with the Soviets on reducing short-range nuclear
rockets and artillery.
   ``Because of the range of the short-range systems, the Federal
Republic of Germany is affected more by these weapons than the
other partners in the (NATO) alliance,'' Kohl said.
   Kohl also has called on the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
to delay a decision on modernizing aging short-range Lance nuclear
missiles until after federal elections next year. Polls indicate
most West Germans oppose NATO plans to increase the range of the
Lance missiles.
   The NATO nations are in disarray over Kohl's proposal for
superpower negotiations on short-range weapons.
   Washington has given Kohl a clear rebuff, fearing negotiations
could lead to elimination of the short-range weapons and increase
the threat to Western Europe from superior Warsaw Pact conventional
forces.
   Britain also rejects Kohl's proposal.
   But NATO allies Belgium, Norway and Denmark have indicated their
support for Kohl. Another NATO partner, Italy, on Thursday
announced it was siding with Kohl.
   The Western alliance hopes to reach a common position on the
issue before the May 29-30 NATO summit in Brussels, but there have
been no signs the stalemate can be broken before then.
   Genscher delivered a ringing address indirectly targeting the
United States and Britain.
   ``Those who want disarmament must take up negotiations,'' he
said.
   U.S. officials have said NATO should keep a cautious eye on
reform movements in the Soviet Union and other Soviet bloc nations,
because there is no certainty their results _ including promises of
unilateral disarmament measures _ will be permanent.
   But Genscher urged the West to be far more receptive of positive
Soviet bloc developments.
   ``This is a historic opportunity. We cannot let it pass us by
and wait passively. That is our responsibility,'' Genscher said.
   Kohl echoed Genscher's call for an increased Western dialogue
with the Soviet bloc.
   ``We should support the reform processes in all Warsaw Pact
countries,'' Kohl said, urging ``our European and American friends
to help carry out this policy and agree on a common course.''
   Recent polls indicate that three-quarters of the West German
population favors eliminating nuclear weapons in Europe. Most of
NATO's short-range weapons are based in West Germany.
   Kohl reassured the United States and other alliance partners
that his government does not want to eliminate those arms.
   ``In the current circumstances, land, sea and airborne
short-range nuclear weapons are still important in Europe,'' Kohl
said.
</TEXT>
