<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1746EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TankerSpill-Wildlife     04-27 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill-Wildlife,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservationists Say Wildlife Loss from Oil Spill Much Worse than
Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY B. DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Press reports from Alaska have failed to get
across the vast killing of wildlife or the enormous remaining risks
to millions of birds, animals and fish from the oil spill in Prince
William Sound, a conservation group said Thursday.
   ``We may already be seeing only one percent of the dead,'' said
Albert M. Manville, senior staff wildlife biologist for Defenders
of Wildlife.
   Manville, who spent April 12-17 observing cleanup efforts and
damage from the March 24 spill, said reports of 200 to 300 miles of
beach contaminated by the 11-million gallon spill were ``wildly
inaccurate.''
   Actual beach contamination, he said, ``is probably closer to
1,000 to 2,000 miles'' of coastline and islands southwest of the
sound.
   Aerial spotting may report many beaches clean when an
on-the-ground inspection would show they are not, Manville said. He
said he was unable to say how much uncontaminated coastline remains
at risk.
   ``The war on stopping the oil spill is lost, in my opinion, but
a few skirmishes can still be won,'' he said. ``The unfortunate
fact of the matter is that ongoing wildlife rehabilitation is
probably more for the public's benefit than for the wildlife's.''
   His organization was joined by several other environmental
groups in writing the tanker owner, Exxon Corp., the Coast Guard
and other cleanup authorities asking greater attention to wildlife.
   The letter from Defenders, Greenpeace, the Sierra Club Legal
Defense Fund, the National Audubon Society and Trustees for Alaska
called for immediate installation of protective booms and
stationing of skimming equipment at Port Nellie Juan and Port Wells
in western Prince William Sound and Port Chalmers and Stockdale
Harbor on the northwest coast of Montague Island, and development
of a plan developed to protect Orca Inlet if necessary.
   Millions of waterfowl migrate through the sound area every year,
and 300,000 to 500,000 birds make the sound their home for at least
part of the year, Manville said.
   Birds on their northward migration probably would not land on
oil or oil-soaked areas in good weather, but if the weather is bad
they might ``and we could have the catastrophic loss of millions of
birds,'' Manville said.
   Oil has been spotted 325 miles from the spot where the tanker
Exxon Valdez ran aground, Manville said. This was a somewhat
greater distance than the 275 miles mentioned in the latest
confirmed reports from Alaska.
   Accurate counts of dead wildlife have been difficult, Manville
said, because of scavenging by eagles and gulls _ which may die
after eating oil-soaked carcasses. Deaths include up to 300 Sitka
black-tailed deer; at least one bear, and muskrat and porcupine.
   Probably three-quarters of the 5,500 sea otters living in the
western half of the sound, the half hit by the spreading oil, have
been killed or harmed by the oil, he said. The Fish and Wildlife
Service estimated on April 14 that nearly all the otters in the oil
``impact area'' had been killed.
   As of Wednesday, 391 dead otters had been counted either in the
wild or after unsuccessful rescue attempts.
   Defenders recommended the transfer of additional
``super-sucker'' oil scooping ships from the oil-exploration areas
off Alaska's North Slope; a visit to the sound by President Bush;
trials of a new detergent, BioVersal, offered by a West German
company for beach cleaning; payments by Exxon of $1 billion a year
for five years for restoration; conversion of key areas of the
Arctic National Wildlife Refuge on the North slope to a wilderness
area to prevent drilling there and refunding the money for some $95
million worth of drilling leases not yet awarded in Bristol Bay,
another major fishing ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890427-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     04-27 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Slain; Rebels Raid Jungle Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen shot and killed a leftist congressman
as he took his children to school Thursday and authorities said he
was the highest elected official killed in Peru's nine-year
insurgency.
   No group claimed responsibility for the attack.
   In the Amazon jungle, guerrillas raided a river town and
occupied it for four hours, killing a woman and wounding five
people, the newspaper El Comercio said.
   Eriberto Arroyo, a congressional deputy from the United Left
party, was killed in Chaclacayo, a Lima surburb, the Interior
Ministry said but refused to give further details. The United Left,
a coalition of communist parties, has the second-largest
representation in Congress.
   Radio Programas, Peru's leading news station, quoted police as
blaming the lefist Shining Path guerrilla group, which has admitted
to 15,000 killings in its nine-year war against the government. But
the Path, which seeks to impose communist rule, has made only
infrequent attacks against legal leftist groups.
   United Left Sen. Edmundo Murrugarra told reporters the
anti-guerrilla death squad, the Rodrigo Franco Command, killed
Arroyo. Murrugarra said a gunman, seated with three others in a
car, opened fire on Arroyo and his wife as they were leaving their
three children at a school.
   None of Arroyo's family members was injured, Radio Programas
said.
   The Franco Command surfaced a year ago vowing to kill people it
considers leftist guerrillas or their supporters. The government
led by center-left Alan Garcia of the Aprista party has denied any
connection to the rightist group.
   In the Amazon, at least 150 members of the Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement aboard motor boats on Tuesday stormed
Contamana, on the Ucayali River, 390 miles northeast of Lima,
according to the respected daily El Comercio.
   The Interior Ministry refused to confirm reports of the attack.
   Ten defenders in the town's police post traded shots with the
attackers for an hour before running out of ammunition and fleeing
into the surrounding dense jungles, El Comercio said.
   The Movement is an anti-U.S. guerrilla group, which emerged one
year before Peru's 1985 presidential elections. Actions by the
organization so far have been confined to attacks that generate
publicity but little bloodshed.

</TEXT>
