<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emmy-winning actress Tyne Daly says
her former ``Cagney and Lacey'' role as ``a cop, a friend, and
somebody's mother,'' should help her play the mother of burlesque
star Gypsy Rose Lee.
   Ms. Daly, following the lead of stage luminaries Ethel Merman
and Angela Lansbury, is tackling the role of Mama Rose in the 30th
anniversary revival of ``Gypsy'' that premieres here May 2 prior to
a November opening on Broadway.
   The actress said it was difficult to tell how her interpretation
of the driven, pushy stage mother would differ from those of the
late Ms. Merman, who starred in the 1959 production, and Ms.
Lansbury, who headlined a revival in 1974.
   ``I like her (Rose) because she is gallant and she has pizazz.
... She's a glorious monster and a lot of fun,'' said Ms. Daly.
   ``My obligation is to play Rose. I have to play Rose, not
Tyne,'' said Ms. Daly, adding, ``I have every intention of being
the Rose of the '80s or '90s.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting experience didn't ease the butterflies
Meryl Streep felt when she went to Washington to complain about
chemical additives in food and drink.
   ``I'm uncomfortable in a public platform,'' she said. ``But the
issue of pesticides in children's lives ... was alarming enough
that I felt that I wanted my friends to know about it and I felt
that other people would be interested in it.''
   Miss Streep, who has waged a campaign against Alar, a chemical
additive which enhances the shelf life of apples, added, ``It's
taken more work, more time and more from my family than any movie
or any other project that I have ever done.''
   On Wednesday, Miss Streep, winner of two Academy Awards and
seven Oscar nominations, was among eight women named by the
National Mother's Day Committee as Outstanding Mothers of 1989. She
and her husband, sculptor Don Gummer, have three children and live
in Connecticut.
   The others who received awards were Faith Daniels, a CBS-TV news
anchor; Sharon Rockefeller, wife of Sen. John D. Rockefeller IV of
West Virginia; talk show host Sally Jessy Raphael; Donna de Varona,
a former Olympic swimmer and ABC sports commentator; Dr. Mathilde
Krim, co-founder of the American Federation for AIDS Research;
Helen Galland, a fashion industry leader and marketing consultant;
and writer Anna Quindlen.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Denver was in Denver this week _ not to sing
country songs but to inspire and seek help for Mother Earth.
   He offered his first presentation Wednesday of ``Higher
Ground,'' a multimedia symposium that uses music and a slide show
to urge people to pitch in for the environment.
   ``I'm not here as John Denver the celebrity. I'm not here as
John Denver the singer. I'm not here as John Denver, the aspiring
cosmonaut,'' Denver told the crowd. ``I'm here as an expression of
my whole, true, complete self.''
   Denver said individuals can improve the environment by taking a
stand, and that politicians and governments will follow, not lead,
committed people who have moved to ``higher ground.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dutch Queen Beatrix and her
husband, Prince Claus, will visit China next month on a weeklong
trip focusing on economic issues, a royal house spokesman said
Thursday.
   In Beijing, the queen is to attend the opening meetings of talks
between the Netherlands' trade mission and their Chinese
counterparts, while in Gingdao, a city in a so-called new economic
zone, the royals will get a first-hand experience of China's
ongoing economic reforms.
   In Shanghai, the last stop of the trip, the royal couple is to
attend an economic seminar, as well as visit a joint venture of
Heineken, the Dutch brewery concern, and a Chinese beer
manufacturer.
   The couple previously visited China in 1978, two years before
Beatrix's coronation.
</TEXT>
