<FIRST>r w AM-GOP-JuvenileCrime     04-27 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GOP-Juvenile Crime,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen: `Middle-Class' Justice No Deterrent to Violent Teens</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Woman Assaulted Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The juvenile justice system was created to
deal with ``the children of folks like us'' and should be toughened
to punish ``the kinds of kids who did what happened in Central
Park,'' a New Hampshire congressman declared Thursday.
   ``What we're saying is, If you're going to do big-boy crime,
you're going to do big-boy time,'' said Rep. Chuck Douglas, R-N.H.,
a former state Supreme Court justice.
   Douglas spoke at a news conference called by four congressional
freshmen, members of the Republican Research Committee Task Force
on Crime, to say the beating and rape of a woman in New York's
Central Park on April 19 highlights a need for changing the
juvenile justice system.
   ``I can tell you that we have a juvenile justice system that is
modeled basically for the middle class,'' Douglas said. ``The
children of folks like us, the children of the middle class who may
get into trouble with shoplifting at a young age; they may throw a
rock through a window, that's where the juvenile justice system
works. ... But the system does not work, and it's no deterrent, and
it's no protection and shouldn't be for the kinds of kids who did
what happened in Central Park.''
   Asked to explain his ``folks like us'' comment, Douglas said,
``The kinds of people who are in this room ... people who are not
involved in the drug scene, people who are not making their living
selling crack. That's what I meant by the kinds of folks who are in
this room.''
   Eight people, ages 14 to 17, are in custody.
   Only one has a police record, and in general teachers called
them good students. One principal said of two of them: ``They come
from homes of parents who care, parents who are as shocked as we
are.'' Four lived in a building with a doorman.
   The congressmen said that in many states youngsters who commit
violent crimes such as rape, armed robbery, murder or attempted
murder get little more than a slap on the wrist.
   The task force is hoping by the end of the year to create
standardized state legislation ``that would cause the most violent
of juvenile offenders to receive the full punishment for their
actions if they're convicted,'' said Rep. Steven Schiff, R-N.M., a
former district attorney. The task force would strongly urge states
to pass its model legislation, he said.
   Douglas said he hoped Congress would pass his own bill to
withhold federal money for juvenile justice from states that fail
to adopt such model legislation.
   The other two members of the group at the news conference were
Reps. Dennis Smith of Oregon and Melton D. Hancock of Missouri.
</TEXT>
