<FIRST>r a AM-Eliana-AIDS     04-27 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eliana-AIDS,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>7-Year-Old AIDS Child Attends Class, Victory for Mom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED GOODALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mentally disabled, AIDS-infected 7-year-old
who won a long legal battle for admission to public school attended
class for the first time Thursday amid cheers from supporters and
hugs from classmates.
   Eliana Martinez, wearing a pink dress and matching bows in her
hair, received a warm welcome at the Manhattan Exceptional Center
where supporters cheered outside the single-story, red-brick
building.
   Administrators pushed for a smooth transition inside, and fellow
students wasted no time getting acquainted with their new classmate.
   ``She rushed in, the children came around her and one of them
hugged her,'' said Rosa Martinez, who fought officials' fears that
her incontinent daughter posed a health risk to others through
bodily secretions. ``They just surrounded her,'' she added. ``They
didn't need any introduction.''
   A federal judge ruled Wednesday that the child could attend
school without being confined to a glass isolation booth, paving
the way for what Mrs. Martinez called the most important day of
Eliana's life.
   Principal Sandra Williams said she sent notes to parents
Wednesday to prepare them for the girl's arrival and received seven
calls of concern, with one mother saying she was not ready to
accept the risk.
   A meeting aimed at reducing anxiety among parents is scheduled
for next week, said Walter Sickles, deputy superintendent of
Hillsborough County schools.
   Eliana carried a knapsack and a toy that plays the Disney song
``It's A Small World'' as she entered school to become the 12th
student in her class.
   ``It's a wonderful day for her,'' attorney Steve Hanlon said.
``She'll do wonderfully here. She's going to take off like a
rocket.''
   Mrs. Martinez said she was glad the 2{-year legal battle was
finally behind her. ``I'm too happy to be bitter about anything,''
she said.
   Linda Castellano, a family friend and head of an AIDS support
group called Linda and Frenz, was among seven supporters outside
the school where 201 pupils are enrolled.
   ``I know she'll benefit from playing with other kids,'' she
said. ``She's always around adults and always having to look up.
Now she'll have eye contact with children.''
   U.S. District Judge Elizabeth A. Kovachevich, who originally
ordered the glass booth for Eliana, ruled Wednesday that the girl
posed no significant health risk to her classmates.
   Her initial decision would have confined the child to the booth
until she became toilet trained and learned to stop sucking her
fingers. Mrs. Martinez said she would not put her child in a
``glass cage.''
   The latest decision came four months after the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals sent the case back to Ms. Kovachevich, saying
Eliana, who had been taught at home since June 1987, must be placed
in a regular classroom unless there was evidence she posed a threat
to other children through bodily secretions.
   School officials generally said they were relieved that the
lengthy battle is finished. One, however, indicated he was still
concerned about safety and said if he had a child in Eliana's class
he probably would not let the child stay at the school.
   ``Based on the knowledge I do have right now, I could not allow
my child to be in the class,'' school board Chairman Sam Rampello
said. `` ... A judge's decision doesn't take away the trepidation.''
   Mrs. Martinez adopted Eliana as an infant in her native Puerto
Rico. The girl became infected with AIDS from tranfusions of
tainted blood shortly after her premature birth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
