<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Italy-SeatBelts     04-27 0124</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Italy-Seat Belts,0127</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seat Belt Law Goes Into Effect in Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italians had to buckle-up Thursday as the
nation's first seat belt law went into effect, and a traffic
policeman in the eastern coastal city of Ancona wasted little time
in making sure people complied.
   Five minutes after the law went into effect at midnight, police
officer Giuseppe Baccolini spotted an offender, and in the next
hour he issued 11 other tickets, according to the ANSA news agency.
   Fines range from about $9 to $37.
   The law requires the driver and front-seat passenger to wear
seat belts at all times. Babies and toddlers must be strapped into
car seats and children under 12 must sit in the back seat.
</TEXT>
