<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs     04-27 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two-Day Drug Crackdown Brings in Pushers, Addicts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian authorities arrested 792 drug
pushers and addicts in a two-day nationwide narcotics sweep,
state-run Tehran Radio reported Thursday.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, said two notorious drug
smugglers were among those arrested in southeast Kerman province,
along with 165 pounds of opium and a large quantity of cash.
   Since a new anti-narcotics law went into effect on Jan. 21, more
than 2,000 people allegedly involved in drug abuse have been
arrested. The law carries the death sentence for possession of even
small quantities of drugs.
   According to official reports, 416 people have been convicted of
drug offenses and executed.
   Most arrests made since January were in provinces along the
border with Pakistan and Afghanistan, from where authorities say
most of the drugs are smuggled into Iran.
   Officials have estimated that 1 million of Iran's 50 million
people are drug addicts but unofficial estimates put the number at
twice that.
</TEXT>
