<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2001EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TankerSpill     04-27 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scarecrows, Fireworks to be Used to Try to Scare Birds from Oily
Sound</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Cordova town meeting scheduled 11:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On one side of Prince William Sound,
wildlife agents set up scarecrows and fireworks Thursday to scare
migratory birds from landing on oily beaches.
   A different kind of fireworks was being planned on the other
side of the sound, where residents of Cordova prepared for a town
meeting Thursday night with officials of Exxon, the Coast Guard and
others involved in cleaning the nation's worst oil spill.
   ``The mood here is people are really concerned,'' said Nancy
Bird, a resident who has started a weekly newsletter on the oil
spill and its effect on the small fishing community of about 2,500
people about 50 miles southeast of Valdez.
   Bird said some of the concerns likely to be expressed at the
meeting were:
   _Cannery workers want to know why they're being asked to release
Exxon of liability for canceling the herring season in order to get
claims checks.
   _Businesses want to know why they aren't being reimbursed for
their loss of business.
   _Fishermen are concerned that the Exxon Valdez still is leaking
and want it moved from one side of Naked Island to the other so
crude won't flow directly toward hatcheries.
   ``Last time we talked with Exxon everyone was very frustrated,''
Bird said. ``The frustration level is still pretty high, but it's
kind of matured. We don't expect things to change very fast.
They're so disorganized.''
   Heavy fog canceled spotter flights Thursday and kept skimmers in
port.
   Wildlife agents arrived Wednesday on Green Island and were
setting up propane cannons, scarecrows and other devices to scare
migratory birds away.
   The plywood scarecrows also will eventually be erected on Seal
Island, another favorite stopover for seabirds headed north,
officials said.
   ``We went to the Salvation Army store in Anchorage and bought 36
sets of clothes'' to outfit the scarecrows, said David McGillivary,
a U.S. Fish &amp; Wildlife biologist in Valdez. The life-sized
scarecrows with painted faces were made with only half-length arms
so that shirt sleeves flap in the wind.
   Exxon scientist Al Maki said Wednesday the hazing program,
financed by the company, is a contingency plan.
   ``We could have that oil up before the majority of the birds
arrive,'' he said. Exxon officials said cleanup of the islands
would begin within days.
   The Fish &amp; Wildlife Service said some migratory birds have
arrived, but most of the tens of thousands that pass through the
area won't do so until early May.
   An official of the National Audubon Society said he doubts the
usefulness of the program, but doesn't fault the Fish &amp; Wildlife
Service for preparing it.
   ``It's something that we support reluctantly,'' said David
Cline, the society's vice president for Alaska.
   The scare tactics are unlikely to have an impact because they
will be conducted in a very small part of the vast sound, and
because the birds heading off to breeding grounds are ``genetically
and physically programmed'' to go certain places, Cline said.
``It's extremely difficult to deter them.''
   A Fish &amp; Wildlife Service spokesman at the agency's regional
office in Anchorage defended the hazing program.
   ``Basically, the methods they will be using have been used
extensively in the Lower 48,'' spokesman Craig Rieben said.
   More than 10 million gallons of oil spilled when a tanker ran
aground on Bligh Reef on March 24. Exxon and the state dispute the
amount of the spill, with the oil company setting the figure at
10.1 million gallons and the state at 10.9 million.
</TEXT>
