<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Spearfishing     04-27 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spearfishing,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters May Continue Lakeside Demonstrations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WOODRUFF, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are arresting non-Indian protesters
at a record pace at lakes where the Chippewa Indians are spearing
fish under the guarantee of 19th-century treaties, state officials
said Thursday.
   An organizer of a sit-in protest at which 35 people were
arrested Wednesday night said more opponents of the Chippewa's
court-affirmed treaty rights are willing to go to jail, and similar
protests may be staged.
   The arrests were made when crowds gathered at boat landings on
northern Wisconsin lakes where the annual Chippewa spearing season
began last weekend prior to the fishing season for non-Indians.
   Dean Crist, a spokesman for Stop Treaty Abuse-Wisconsin and one
of those arrested, criticized Oneida County Sheriff Charles Crofoot
for roping off boat landings where the Chippewa were spearing, thus
restricting protesters from the lakes.
   ``If Sheriff Crofoot doesn't come around we might try it (a
protest) with 300'' people, Crist said. ``What we would like is
equal access to the landings. We're not trying to test the jails.''
   This is the fifth spring that Wisconsin's six Chippewa bands
have speared fish since a federal court ruled in 1983 that the
tribe retained the right to gather food off-reservation. The right
was guaranteed under 19th-century treaties that ceded much of
northern Wisconsin to the United States.
   Spearfishing critics say the three-pronged spears used by the
Indians leave too few trophy-size walleyed pike for non-Indian
anglers when the rod-and-reel season begins in early May.
   Tom Maulson, a member of the Lac Du Flambeau Chippewa who helps
organize the tribe's spearfishing activities, said police were
``doing a fantastic job'' protecting the Indian spearers.
   But tensions between the Chippewa and non-Indians were at an
all-time high, he added.
   ``I don't think it can get any worse than this,'' he said. ``All
we can do is hope.''
   Twenty-six of those arrested were charged Thursday in Oneida
County Circuit Court with violating a county disorderly conduct
ordinance and released on signature bonds, District Attorney Brian
Maloney said.
   Nine others were released from jail after posting bond and will
be charged at a later date, he said.
   In all, 43 protesters were arrested at three lakes Wednesday
night, raising the total number of arrests to 46 since the Chippewa
began their spearfishing season Sunday night.
   In Madison, Ralph Christensen, chief warden for the state
Department of Natural Resources, said Thursday it was ``clearly the
case'' that police would arrest a record number of protesters this
season.
   Christensen said Wednesday's protests marked the first organized
civil disobedience involving treaty rights opponents.
   George Meyer, DNR chief of enforcement, said crowds of
protesters at boat landings this year have been ``more emotional
and larger than at this time in other years.''
   The Wisconsin Natural Resource Board on Thursday approved an
emergency rule that authorizes the state to sharply reduce bag
limits for non-Indian anglers who fish lakes that are also speared
by the Chippewa.
   Under the rule, the state will reduce the number of walleye
taken daily by anglers from five to three or less on the 254 lakes
that the Chippewa plan to spear this spring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
