<DOCNO> AP890427-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1723EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUDOfficials-Audit     04-27 0993</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Officials-Audit,960</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe Reveals Former Officials Profited from HUD Contracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigation into a federal housing
renovation program has revealed a pattern in which former Reagan
administration officials raked in handsome profits on contracts to
rehabilitate subsidized apartments for the poor.
   The inspector general of the Department of Housing and Urban
Development drew a comparison with the Pentagon procurement
scandal, with former government officials drawing big fees as
consultants to developers seeking government contracts.
   But Inspector General Paul Adams said he had found no evidence
that active HUD officials had been involved in influence-peddling
and made no charges of criminal activity.
   The investigation by the department's inspector general,
announced Wednesday, also listed several former top-level HUD
officials who later won contracts as developers of rehabilitation
projects.
   The consultants _ who charged fees up to $1.3 million _ included
President Reagan's first interior secretary, James Watt; the late
John Mitchell, attorney general under President Nixon; former
Republican Sen. Ed Brooke of Massachusetts, and former Kentucky
Gov. Louis Nunn, also a Republican.
   Adams, in an interview Thursday, said that while he had found no
illegality or criminal activity in the investigation into HUD's
Moderate Rehabilitation Program, contracts had been distributed in
ways that suggested favoritism and insider information was used to
direct HUD awards for projects.
   Money for over half the units audited went to just 10 states,
who by HUD formula were fairly entitled only 16 percent.
   Adams said he had turned over the 700-page investigative report
to the Justice Department's public integrity branch for review.
   The rehab program is a $225 million a year endeavor that has
survived in Congress despite efforts by the Reagan administration
to kill it. Through it, developers win contracts to acquire and
renovate existing housing and receive HUD guarantees of subsidized
rents for 15 years.
   Adams said in a memo to HUD Secretary Jack Kemp that developers
and local public housing agencies ``were led to believe the
consultants enjoyed a special relationship with persons making
recommendations and decisions.''
   Interviews with housing officials suggested favoritism in the
program was widely suspected.
   ``This is not news to me; it was suspected,'' said Gordon
Cavanaugh, attorney for the Council of Large Public Housing
Authorities.
   One HUD official, speaking only on the condition of anonymity,
said, ``This was the road to the gravy train _ you come in here and
work a few years and then get out and make millions in mod-rehab.''
   Addressing the Pentagon purchasing scandal, Adams said in his
memo:
   ``In Defense, the contractors were paying consultants to obtain
information to influence contract awards. At HUD, the developers
were paying consultants to influence awards of moderate
rehabilitation units to public housing authorities.
   ``The difference between the two situations is that the
investigation at Defense was able to prove that the consultants
paid government employees for information and for selecting a
particular contractor. Our investigation at HUD was unable to
substantiate that government employees received any financial
consideration from the consultants.''
   Adams' report questioned the role of Thomas T. Demery, the
former assistant secretary and federal housing commissioner, who
was responsible for the program's beginning in 1986. The
investigation looked into contracts going back to 1984.
   Investigators found that a nonprofit charity, FOOD for Africa,
which Demery headed before joining HUD, received $290,000 from
recipients of HUD contracts under the program. Efforts to locate
Demery were unsuccessful Thursday.
   Kemp, expressing shock at the ``fundamental flaws'' and
mismanagement revealed by the investigation, ordered a halt to 35
pending awards worth $100 million, his aide, Mary Brunette, said
Thursday. Eight contracts already executed in the current fiscal
year will be allowed to continue but will be audited, as will
nearly 300 existing contracts.
   Investigators found nearly $59 million in excess subsidies paid
by HUD and said if the pattern existed throughout the program, the
figure would reach $413 million.
   On Capitol Hill, the House Banking chairman, Rep. Henry B.
Gonzales, D-Texas, said the report showed the program ``was misused
to feather the financial nest of HUD and (Reagan) administration
favorites.''
   He praised Kemp's actions, announced intentions to hold hearings
on the investigation and said he would ask the Office of Government
Ethics to examine the reports on former HUD officials.
   Adams' report named 11 former HUD officials who participated in
project contracts as developers and owners, consultants, or
representatives of lenders.
   Among them was former Under Secretary Philip Abrams and former
Assistant Secretary for Housing Philip Winn. Both were presidential
appointees under then-HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce, and later became
owner-developers in half a dozen rehabilitation projects.
   Winn is now the U.S. ambassador to Switzerland; efforts to reach
him through the State Department were unsuccessful.
   Abrams did not return a reporter's call to his Colorado office.
   Others included Joseph Strauss, a former special assistant to
Pierce, who the report said collected $1.3 million in consultant
fees on such projects. Pierce's one-time executive assistant, Lance
Wilson, was identified as an owner-developer in six projects.
   Watt collected a $300,000 fee as a consultant on a 312-unit
project in Essex, Md. Investigators reported that he ``said that
his role was to talk to the `right people' and convice them that
the project was needed,'' the report said.
   It said Nunn was paid $375,000 as attorney and consultant on a
1984 Miami project in which he in turn paid Mitchell $75,000 for
his assistance.
   ``Nunn claimed Mitchell told him he had HUD contacts from the
top on down, because he and (Pierce) ... were friends,'' the report
said. Pierce told investigators that he knew Mitchell but that
Mitchell had never discussed HUD matters with him.
   Brooke was paid $183,000 as consultant, most of that in a Lynn,
Mass., deal. Also named as a consultant who received $260,000 in
fees was Frederick Bush, no relation to the president, who has been
nominated as ambassador to Luxembourg.
   Calls to Watt, Nunn and Brooke were not immediately returned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
