<FIRST>r i AM-EastGermany-Troops     04-27 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany-Troops,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honecker: 11,500 Soldiers To Be Employed In Economy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leader Erich Honecker said
Thursday that East Germany will reduce its armed forces by 11,500
men and assign them to jobs in the economy.
   The state-run news agency ADN said Honecker described the move
as a gesture of good will. It comes in addition to cuts of 10,000
men, 600 tanks and 50 planes announced in January.
   Honecker made the announcement during talks in East Berlin with
Ernst Albrecht, governor of the West German state of Lower Saxony.
Albrecht, at a news conference, later confirmed the ADN report.
   ADN said 11,500 men will spend three months receiving basic
military training and will then be sent to different jobs in the
economy for the remainder of their obligatory 15-month service.
   The agency did not specify when the cuts will be implemented and
did not say in which economic sectors the future recruits would be
employed.
   According to Western estimates, East Germany has about 175,000
men under arms.
   When he announced the troop and equipment cuts in January,
Honecker also said the country would reduce its military budget by
10 percent. ADN said the reductions will begin on Friday and will
be completed by 1990.
</TEXT>
