<FIRST>r w AM-ReporterDetained     04-27 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reporter Detained,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Blasts Panama For Detaining U.S. Reporter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department criticized the government
of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega of Panama on Thursday for detaining
an American reporter who allegedly passed a dollar that had
anti-Noriega slogans on it.
   Spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Charles Lane, a Newsweek
reporter based in El Salvador, was taken into custody Wednesday and
held for several hours by the Panama Defense Forces. He was
unharmed.
   ``At no time were there any charges against Mr. Lane,'' Ms.
Tutwiler said, calling the incident ``a typical instance of an
absence of political freedom and basic civil liberties in Panama.''
   She said the Panamanians staged a ``deliberate effort to
intimidate an independent journalist in the context of a national
election which Gen. Noriega would have the world believe will
represent the free expression of the will of the people of Panama,
its domestic opponents and those able to give a true picture of the
Noriega regime to the world.''
   Presidential elections are scheduled in Panama for May 7.
   Bob Rivard, chief of correspondents for Newsweek, said in a
telephone interview from New York that Lane had been held for six
hours and interrogated several times.
   ``The editors of Newsweek regard Chuck's detention as
unwarranted and a very cynical exercise on the part of the
military,'' Rivard said. ``He had done nothing wrong.''
</TEXT>
