<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TridentSubmarines     04-27 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trident Submarines,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Democrats Ask Reconsideration of Naval Strategic Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democrats concerned about a naval
strategic modernization plan's compatability with a U.S.-Soviet
arms control treaty sent a letter Thursday to President Bush urging
him to review the proposal.
   Navy officials have told Congress they want a force of at least
20 Trident submarines equipped with a high number of missile tubes
_ 24 _ rather than more submarines with fewer tubes.
   In the letter, the lawmakers asked for a better plan ``in order
to maintain a robust naval strategic fleet _ and strengthen our
current arms control negotiating posture.''
   ``Under the scenarios proposed to Congress, the Navy would
retain over 4,000 strategic warheads,'' the lawmakers said.
``However, the proposals _ or the Trident's missile tube
configuration _ may need to be revised.''
   Former President Reagan and Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev agreed to limit each country to 4,900 ballistic missile
warheads. Under a U.S.-Soviet strategic arms reduction treaty, the
Navy plan would leave fewer than 900 warheads for land-based
missiles, the lawmakers said.
   ``If we continue to procure one Trident per year, as currently
configured, we may end up buying Tridents in excess of those we
would deploy under START,'' the letter also says. ``This may force
premature retirements of one or more Tridents _ forfeiting a
multibillion-dollar expenditure.''
   Among the possible options, the letter suggests, is redesign of
the Trident to carry fewer missile tubes, research on a smaller
strategic submarine or slowing down production of the Trident.
   ``I am concerned that the Navy may be going down a blind alley
with its strategic modernization plan,'' said Rep. Tom Foglietta,
D-Pa., one of the signees of the letter. ``It appears incompatible
with the current arms control framework.''
   Rep. Charles Bennett, D-Fla., chairman of the House Armed
Services seapower subcommittee, raised the issue with the deputy
chief of naval operations for plans, policy and operations at a
congressional hearing.
   Vice Adm. Charles R. Larson said the Trident gives the Navy the
necessary flexibility and survivability, and another witness _
Robert G. Joseph, deputy assistant secretary of defense for nuclear
forces and arms control policy _ cautioned against strategy based
on a U.S.-Soviet treaty.
   ``The last thing we want to do now is act as if we have an
agreement in START,'' Joseph said.
   In addition to Foglietta, the House members who signed the
letter were Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the Armed Services
Committee; John M. Spratt, D-S.C., Ronald Dellums, D-Calif.;
Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass.; Barbara Boxer, D-Calif.; Albert G.
Bustamante, D-Texas; and Martin Olav Sabo, D-Minn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
