<DOCNO> AP890427-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Students-Sabotage     04-27 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Students-Sabotage,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some High School Seniors Sabotage State Test</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Kelle in 13th graf is correct.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORRANCE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seniors at a high-achieving high school
sabotaged their answers on a test that measures the school's
academic quality, and one said the diminished scores were a
rebellion against pressure to perform.
   Administrators at West High School denied there was too much
pressure, and a spokeswoman for the State Department of Education
suggested that dragging down the school's score on the California
Assessment Test may have been sparked by something else.
   ``I think it would be interesting to know what else is going on
at that campus. The last time this happened at a school a few years
ago, students were mad at the administration for putting speed
bumps in the parking lot,'' said state Department of Education
spokeswoman Susie Lange.
   She said officials at the education department's testing office
have talked to the school, and said there was no chance of getting
a second test.
   The results are used to determine a school's academic placement
compared to other schools in the state. The results are published
in newspapers and are considered by the state for achievement
awards and grants. Home buyers use the results when a good school
district is a consideration.
   Reading scores at West High School dropped from the 85th
percentile statewide last year to the 51st percentile this year and
math scores fell from the 95th percentile in 1987-88 to 71st
percentile this year.
   ``We thought that it was the wrong high school,'' said Principal
William Bawden. ``And then we got some rumors that maybe some of
the seniors had sabotaged the test.''
   He said a check of students' test booklets, which are not
signed, showed an unusual number of wrong answers in 18 booklets,
including some booklets that contained no right answers. Bawden
said one student admitted deliberately doing badly on the test. He
denied extraordinary pressure was placed on students to do well.
   Bill Franchini, head of the Torrance Teacher Association, said
Thursday he had talked to teachers at West High School in this Los
Angeles suburb, and said he was unaware of any extra problems or
pressure that would have caused the sabotage.
   But Franchini said the CAP test is a ripe target for angry
students, since names are not on the tests and the results are
averaged for the entire school.
   ``A lot of these seniors have been tested, perhaps over
tested,'' said Franchini. ``They have the California Test of Basic
Skills, the Scholastic Aptitude Test, and various achievement
tests. They are tested, tested, tested. So when this one comes
along and it doesn't have their name on it, they may think `Well,
so what?'''
   Student body President Kelle Price said Tuesday some seniors
became disgruntled when teachers interrupted classes to prepare
students for the test and when administrators visited classes
stressing the importance of doing well.
   ``They said this is the test that is the school's report card,''
said Ms. Price, ``and West is a really good school and that we all
want to keep it up. I think a lot of people resented that.'' She
said she did not participate in the sabotage.
   Franchini disagreed with Ms. Price's allegation that
extraordinary pressure was brought on students.
   Lange said the last time a test was sabotaged was in 1984-85,
when CAP scores were tied to state cash bonuses to the schools.
That program has been cancelled. She said the students at one
school said they would do poorly on the test to protest speed bumps
placed in their parking lot.
   ``The damage is done,'' she said of the results at West. ``It's
not hurting them, its hurting their younger brothers and sisters.
They have broken the school's trend.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
