<FIRST>r w AM-US-Soviets     04-27 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviets,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rowny Challenges Soviets On Arms Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward L. Rowny, a senior U.S. arms control
adviser, accused the Soviet Union on Thursday of seeking military
advantage even as it appeals to public opinion seeking arms
reductions.
   Rowny said in a speech prepared for delivery in San Antonio the
Soviets ``play to the grandstand of public opinion while masking
their own very real efforts to achieve military advantage.''
   The former U.S. negotiator, who advises President Bush and
Secretary of State James A. Baker III on arms control issues, said
the Soviets were trying to promote a positive image in the West and
divide the NATO alliance at the same time.
   In the speech to the National War College Alumni Association,
Rowny challenged Soviet sincerity on withdrawing tanks from Eastern
Europe and on the issue of short-range nuclear missiles.
   While Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev said in January that
none of the 10,000 tanks to be withdrawn would remain in the Soviet
military inventory, Rowny quoted Gen. B.V. Snetkov, the Soviet
commander in East Germany, as saying last week that some of the
tanks would remain in the Soviet arsenal.
   On short-range missiles, Rowny accused the Soviets of
propaganda. He said while Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
has objected to improving NATO's weapons the Soviets have been
modernizing their own missiles for a decade.
   Rowny said the Soviets are replacing the SS-23 missiles banned
by the U.S.-Soviet Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces Treaty with
SCUDs that have a range of 300 miles and have been replacing FROG
missiles with SS-21s with potentially greater range and accuracy.
   The Warsaw Pact has an advantage of at least 16 to 1 over the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization in missiles below the range of
315 miles, Rowny said.
   Within the NATO alliance, West Germany is resisting U.S. efforts
to extend the range of Lance missiles and has called for U.S.
negotiations with the Soviets to scale back such weapons. The Bush
administration, with support from Britain and France, has rejected
the West German overture.
   ``On this issue,'' Rowny said, ``the Soviets have created a
credibility gap so wide one could drive a tank through it.''
   He said the Soviets have tried to make arms control the main
focus of their relations with the United States because they
believe that serves Soviet interests.
   ``Preoccupation with arms control diverts attention from the
critical underlying causes of East-West tension which the Soviets
cleary recognize __ the differences in the values of our respective
social systems,'' Rowny said.
</TEXT>
