<FIRST>u i AM-SatanicVerses     04-27 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Police Spirited Rushdie Away From Dinner Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Salman Rushdie, in hiding under death
threats from Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, was spirited away
from a dinner by police worried about Moslem students nearby, a
newspaper said Thursday.
   The Daily Mail said Rushdie was attending a private dinner party
with professors at an Oxford University college.
   It said detectives spotted Moslem students near the college and
``fearing an attempt on his life, the officers interrupted the
author during the party with dons (instructors) and spirited him
out of a side entrance.''
   The paper said Rushdie was driven away in an armored car, and
officers worried whether a security lapse had led to details of the
party leaking out.
   The Mail did not say when the reported incident occurred, and
police declined comment. The office of Rushdie's agent, Gillon
Aitken, who acts as his spokesman, did not return a phone call.
   Rushdie went into hiding 10 weeks ago after Khomeini ruled that
his novel, ``The Satanic Verses,'' blasphemed Islam and ordered
Moslems to find him and kill him.
   Many Moslems contend the book is blasphemous because it includes
a scene in which prostitutes take the names of the prophet
Mohammed's wives, and it suggests Mohammed wrote the holy Koran
instead of receiving it from Allah.
   On Wednesday night, five Moslem women protesting a new play
defending the right of Rushdie and other writers to freedom of
expression invaded the stage at London's Royal Court Theater and
halted the performance for 10 minutes.
   The one-act play, ``Iranian Nights,'' was nearly over when the
women staged their peaceful protest, a theater spokesman said on
condition of anonymity.
   Attendants escorted the women off the stage and out of the
theater, and the play resumed without further interruption. No
arrests were made.
   The play is by dramatist Howard Brenton and Tariq Ali, a
well-known left-wing student activist in London in the 1960s. It
covers issues raised by the events surrounding Rushdie and ``The
Satanic Verses.''
   The Times of London, meanwhile, quoted Rushdie's agent Aitken
Thursday as saying he believed Rushdie was eager for his book to be
published in paperback toward the end of the year, despite warnings
from Moslem leaders in Britain that it would inflame the
controversy.
   Aitken was quoted as saying there had been little discussion
with Rushdie about paperback publication, but ``I think he is keen
that this book should be published in the way that his other books
have been published.''
   Viking Penguin, Rushdie's hardcover and paperback publisher,
said there were no plans at this stage for a paperback edition.
   The Times said Rushdie telephones Aitken at his office about
twice a week to discuss the book's sales.
   On March 17, Iran broke diplomatic ties with Britain after
British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe defended Rushdie's
right to freedom of speech and to publish his book.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government subsequently
ordered the expulsion of 18 Iranians from Britain, saying they were
perceived as a security threat. Iran retaliated by ordering 18
Britons either to be expelled from Iran or not allowed back into
Britain.
   In Barcelona, Spain, 18 companies said Thursday they planned to
jointly publish a Spanish edition of ``The Satanic Verses.''
</TEXT>
