<FIRST>r w AM-US-ArabLeague     04-27 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Arab League,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Envoys Call on Baker to Discuss Lebanon, PLO and West Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab League delegation failed Thursday to
persuade Secretary of State James A. Baker III to reopen the
Palestine Liberation Organization office here.
   ``There is no change in our policy,'' a State Department
official said after the 45-minute meeting.
   Clovis Maksoud, the Arab League's representative here, said he
had ``the impression'' Baker was not opposed to reopening the
office. ``But he wants to have the proper timing and the proper
circumstances,'' Maksoud told reporters.
   The office was closed in March 1988 after Congress declared the
PLO a terrorist organization. Since then, however, the United
States has held a series of meetings with the PLO and is seeking
its support for Mideast peace talks.
   Maksoud said the Arab delegation told Baker the office should be
reopened in light of the talks begun by the Reagan administration
in December.
   However, a State Department official, who spoke to a reporter on
condition of anonymity, said no change was contemplated.
   The delegation also disagreed with Baker on a proposal by
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to have Palestinian Arabs on
the West Bank and in Gaza elect leaders to negotiate an interim
self-rule arrangement.
   President Bush and Baker have endorsed the proposal as a useful
and encouraging step toward an Arab-Israeli settlement.
   But Maksoud said it was an attempt by Israel ``to frustrate the
international outrage concerning the practices of Israel in the
occupied territories.''
   He called the proposal ``a charade'' designed to undermine the
PLO, which the Arab League has declared the only legitimate
representative of Palestinians.
   On a third point, there was apparent agreement.
   Maksoud and Ambassadors Saud al-Sabah of Kuwait and Mohsin A.
Alaini of North Yemen described to Baker a plan by the Arab League
to enforce a cease-fire in Lebanon with soldiers from several Arab
countries.
   Maksoud said Baker ``expressed appreciation'' for the league's
efforts, while the U.S. official said Baker had ``restated strong
support'' for the peace initiative and a need for a cease-fire.
   The country is torn by warfare between Christian and Moslem
factions, with 40,000 Syrian troops playing a dominant role in much
of the country.
</TEXT>
