<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-EthiopianJews     04-27 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopian Jews,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman: Ethiopian President Favors Reunification Of Jews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia's president is willing to allow
Ethiopian Jews to emigrate and rejoin families from whom they have
been separated since a secret airlift to Israel was halted, a
congressman said Thursday.
   Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, the chairman of the House Select
Committee on Hunger, said he received the assurances of President
Mengistu Haile Mariam at a meeting in Addis Ababa during Congress'
Easter recess.
   Leland also defended Ethiopia's role in efforts to deliver
emergency food supplies to thousands of starving people in
rebel-held southern Sudan.
   While acknowledging that Ethiopia wasn't working with the United
Nations relief efforts, Leland claimed they were taking other steps
to help get food across the border before the rainy season arrives
in May and makes roads impassable.
   ``Recognition of Ethiopia's cooperation in the urgent
humanitarian mission to save the people of southern Sudan is
imperative to future efforts towards establishing peace throughout
the Horn of Africa,'' Leland told a news conference.
   Leland said some news reports have unfairly painted
Soviet-backed Ethiopia as a ``villain'' in the emergency relief
effort to supply food to Sudanese people caught in the country's
civil war.
   Although Ethiopia is not working with the U.N. ``Operation
Lifeline,'' Leland said 5,000 to 7,000 metric tons of food is en
route to Sudan under a joint relief program of private, voluntary
and church organizations headquartered in the capital of Addis
Ababa.
   Roughly 120 trucks are needed for the joint-relief effort
separate from the UN's mission, and Leland said Ethiopia is
providing at least half of those vehicles.
   ``They are allowing for cross-border operations to happen, just
not under the auspices of the UN,'' said Leland, who also visited
Sudan to assess the situation. ``When it comes to feeding the
hungry, we should not take potshots because (Ethiopia) doesn't
agree with us ideologically.''
   On the issue of Ethiopian Jews, Leland said in an interview that
Mengistu assured him recently in that he is committed to ``family
reunification'' and that the issue is ``a project we can work on
mutually.''
   ``There are families who are being reunited,'' Leland said.
``The Ethiopian government has been forthcoming about allowing
families to be reunified and I expect more of that will be realized
as time goes on.''
   Like the Soviet Union, Ethiopia restricts the emigration of its
people.
   More than 10,000 Ethiopian Jews remain in what Leland said is
the poorest country in the world, peasants who were left behind
after an exodus in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
   Between November 1984 and the first days of 1985, an estimated
7,000 Ethiopian Jews were airlifted to Israel, joining about 6,000
who had made their way to Israel earlier, before Ethiopia imposed
emigration restrictions.
   The secret operation in late 1984 was stopped when the Belgian
charter company flying the refugees to Israel through Europe balked
at the publicity in the international press.
   The Ethiopian Jews trace their roots in Judaism back 2,600
years. American Jews have supported efforts to bring the Ethiopian
Jews to Israel.
   Leland said he did not ask Mengistu for any numbers on how many
Ethiopian Jews had been reunited with their families in Israel and
elsewhere in the world.
</TEXT>
