<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Railroads-Drugs     04-27 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Railroads-Drugs,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unions Ask Congressman To Ax Random Testing From Railroad-Drug Use
Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Random drug testing is ``nothing more than
looking for a needle in a haystack'' and isn't necessary to prevent
drug- and alcohol-related train accidents, railroad unions told
Congress on Thursday.
   The unions told Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, he could accomplish
his goal of safer railways without making workers go through
unnecessary tests.
   ``There comes a point where enough is enough,'' said James
Kennedy Jr. of the Railway Labor Executives' Association, which
represents 17 unions.
   ``Rail workers now are subjected to numerous potential alcohol
and drug tests each year,'' he said in testimony to the House
Transportation and Hazardous Materials Subcommittee.
   New employees are screened for drugs before they're hired, he
said. Once on the job, workers are tested after accidents, during
physicals, when they return to work after illnesses and when
there's some suspicion of impairment.
   A bill proposed by Luken would require drug testing of all
railroad workers with ``safety sensitive'' jobs, set standards for
the labs that do the testing and require that railroads maintain
rehabilitation programs.
   The Supreme Court ruled March 21 that the Federal Railroad
Administration's current drug-testing regulations are
constitutional.
   The random drug-testing allowed under the Supreme Court decision
would be limited under Luken's bill.
   S. Mark Lindsey, the FRA's chief counsel, told the subcommittee
the bill would ``set in concrete'' some testing options that
``could far exceed actual safety needs.''
   The administration favors no changes to the policies supported
by the high court, he said.
   United Transportation Union President Fred Hardin said he feared
mandatory random drug and alcohol testing would give railroads an
excuse to cancel costly rehabilitation programs.
   Hardin compared rail workers to long-haul independent truckers.
   ``There are thousands of `gypsy' truck drivers operating their
trucks over our nation's highways utilizing medicinal aids to stay
awake and continue driving their trucks for unrealistic periods of
time,'' he told the subcommittee, which Luken heads.
   ``Why not propose requirements for random testing of both truck
and automobile drivers?''
   The Association of American Railroads said it supported the idea
of random drug testing but didn't like Luken's plan because it
singles out railroads from other forms of transportation.
   Association President William Dempsey also said he disagreed
with a proposal to force railroads to guarantee that workers who
have completed drug or alcohol rehabilitation are reinstated in
their jobs.
   Luken interpreted the complaints from both labor and ownership
as a positive sign.
   ``Frankly, that tells me that we are on to something here,'' he
said.
   His bill duplicates a measure that passed the House in the last
session.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
