<FIRST>r w AM-FAAFine     04-27 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FAA Fine,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Seeks Fine Agaisnt Air Wisconsin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration on
Thursday announced $200,000 in fines against Air Wisconsin for
failure to conduct required inspections on three of its aircraft
after repairs.
   The FAA does not consider planes to be airworthy until repairs
have been inspected by qualified personnel other than those who
made the repairs.
   In one instance, a fuel control lever was unsafely wired during
maintenance, resulting in the right engine of a two-engine plane
being stuck at an 80 percent power level, the FAA said, adding that
an inspection would have caught the error.
   The FAA charged Air Wisconsin in an April 14 letter with using
three of its aircraft on several passenger-carrying flights after
failing to check repairs.
   Two of the aircraft had received unverified repairs after being
hit by birds, and one was hit by lightning, the FAA said.
</TEXT>
