<FIRST>u i AM-Jordan 1stLd-Writethru a0633 04-27 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jordan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jordan Gets New Prime Minister After Riots</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with official announcements, details.
No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein swore in his tough former army
commander as prime minister Thursday after widespread rioting and
told him to reorganize the government and prepare for Jordan's
first general elections in 22 years.
   State-run Jordan TV showed the swearing-in ceremony for Zeid Bin
Shaker and said Hussein issued 19 directives to the new government,
including calls for freedom of the press, support for the PLO and
stamping out corruption.
   But the king also told the government to ``put an end to the
involvement of religion in politics,'' an apparent reference to
Islamic fundamentalists accused of encouraging the unrest.
   Bin Shaker takes office after the kingdom's worst domestic
violence since 1971. Riots stemming from government price increases
and economic difficulties killed at least nine people last week in
southern Jordan. Government buildings and banks were attacked in
dozens of cities and villages.
   The new government ``will be a temporary one'' charged with
``overseeing the general elections which will take place very
soon,'' Hussein was quoted as telling the Kuwaiti newspaper
Al-Seyassah.
   The 24-man Cabinet includes seven Palestinian-born men, down
from 10 in the previous 26-member cabinet.
   But that appeared enough to assert Hussein's continuing claim to
represent Palestinians in the kingdom despite his decision to sever
ties with the West Bank last year. Palestinians make up half of
Jordan's population of 3 million.
   The king vowed continued support for the Palestine Liberation
Organization and ``non-interference in their local affairs,''
distancing himself further from the West Bank he ruled until 1967,
when it was seized by Israel.
   The new government includes nine Cabinet holdovers, including
Foreign Minister Marwan Kassem.
   Bin Shaker, 55, a longtime friend and adviser of the king, is
best known for his military role in crushing Palestinian guerrillas
in Jordan in 1970 and 1971. He was armed forces commander in chief
until last year, when Hussein made him chief of palace advisers and
special adviser on security affairs. He still holds field marshal's
rank and enjoys high prestige in the army.
   In Thursday's message, Hussein alluded to charges of corruption
and profiteering leveled against Zaid Rifai, the replaced prime
minister whose name was chanted in rage by rioters.
   Hussein ordered his ministers to re-examine Jordan's tax laws
with an eye to fairness and ``to uproot corruption wherever it is.''
   He demanded stronger channels of communication between the
people and the government, including ``the right of expression and
freedom of the press.'' Rifai, who resigned on Monday, nationalized
Jordan's already docile newspapers during his four-year tenure.
   The riots were set off by 10 to 50 percent price rises for
gasoline and cigarettes and other commodities on top of an economic
slide that cut yearly per capita income to about $1,200 from $2,000.
   Al-Seyassah quoted Hussein as saying ``an accumulation of
factors'' led to the four days of riots and that the outgoing
government ``was unable to communicate to the public an explanation
of the recent economic measures.''
   Hussein also was quoted as saying Israel ``had a hand'' in
spurring the riots to draw attention from the 16-month Palestinian
uprising in Israeli-occupied territories.
   In Jerusalem, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin retorted
Thursday on state-owned Israel radio, ``If he said these things,
then it is absurd, almost ridiculous.''
   Both Bin Shaker and Hussein were educated at Victoria College in
Egypt, and at Britain's Sandhurst military academy.
   Bin Shaker joined the army in 1953, the year Hussein came to
power, and was by the king's side when Hussein drove out to meet
his troops amid gunfire and rallied them against an attempted coup
in 1957.
   Bin Shaker commanded an armored brigade in the 1967 war with
Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
