<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Collaborators 1stLd-Writethru   04-27 0851</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Collaborators, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0661,0869</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Step Up Attacks On Collaborators With Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS graf after 3rd, `Six additional...' to UPDATE with stabbing.
Pick up 4th pvs, `The pace...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian enforcers have stepped up a
self-policing campaign, targeting Arabs who collaborate with Israel
or defy policies of the underground leadership.
   An Israeli Defense Ministry report obtained by The Associated
Press said 960 attacks have been carried out on Palestinians by
other Arabs with 33 killed and 63 wounded between the start of the
uprising in December 1987 and the beginning of April 1989.
   Six additional Palestinians were killed in recent days, some
accused of spying for Israel and others the target of a new
underground ``vice squad'' that has singled out drug dealers and
prostitutes.
   On Thursday night, an Arab policeman, Jamil Sheik Hallil, 37,
was stabbed by masked Palestinians in the West Bank village of
Nazlat Iza for continuing to work with the Israeli government
despite warnings to quit, Arab reporters said. He was taken to a
hospital in Israel for treatment, they said.
   The pace and severity of such attacks intensified this week as
the pro-PLO underground called in an underground leaflet for a
``day of accounting for the collaborators.''
   Israeli officials claim Palestinian underground leaders are
creating a climate of fear in which moderates are intimidated from
speaking freely or challenging the policies of Yasser Arafat's
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   ``We believe such violence has an impact on the voices we can
hear coming from the Palestinian population and its leaders. It has
an impact on political behavior and expressions,'' said Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Alon Liel.
   Palestinians reject such claims, saying a wide variety of
political views are expressed in public as evidenced by a recent
debate on whether Palestinians should agree to an Israeli proposal
for elections.
   ``I don't think we are in Switzerland where there is a
completely free flow of ideas. But considering all the constraints,
Palestinians have an ample opportunity to give opinions. Look at
the elections, people publicly expressed various points of view,''
said Daoud Kuttab, a Palestinian journalist.
   Palestinian sources who spoke on condition of anonymity defended
the actions of the clandestine hit teams that ``cleanse the
community'' of informers who risk the lives of anti-Israeli
activists sought by Israeli security authorities.
   The most recent victim was Fayek Erar, who allegedly forged
deeds and sold land to Israelis. He died in a barrage of bullets
fired by three masked men who came to his house in the West Bank
village of Ras Atiya on Wednesday.
   In Gaza City, the body of Jamal Abdul Hamid El Nadi, 39, was
found stabbed and beaten March 25. A leaflet pinned to his chest
was signed by the ``strike forces of the State of Palestine'' and
said: ``This is the fate of all who collaborate with the Zionists
and deal with drugs.''
   Palestinians sources who spoke on condition of anonymity fearing
reprisal said suspected collaborators were were amply warned and
given a chance to repent. They also noted that underground trials
were conducted in which testimony was tape recorded.
   Sabah Kanaan, 32, said 10 Palestinian activists, their faces
concealed by checkered headdresses, broke into her home in the West
Bank City of Nablus on April 21, beat her and sexually assaulted
her. She said in a telephone interview that they demanded
information about an acquaintance they suspected of collaborating.
   ``They stormed into my house carrying sticks and covering their
faces. They beat me and threatened to take my life if I did not
cooperate and tell them,'' said Ms. Kanaan, who was hospitalized in
Ramallah with bruises on the legs and arms.
   ``This is the ugly face of the intefadeh,'' said Col. Renaan
Gissin, the deputy army spokesman, using the Arabic word for
uprising. ``For some months now, violence and intimidation have
been used to enforce the policies and orders of the underground
leadership.''
   The Defense Ministry report said frequent targets of threats
were the 18,000 Palestinians who work for the army-run civil
administration, which administers the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   For example, a threatening leaflet from the pro-PLO United
National Leadership of the Uprising forced the resignation of 450
Arab policemen, especially after warnings were underlined by the
killing of Jericho policeman whose body was left on the doorstep of
his house in March 1988.
   Israeli-appointed mayors, city council members and village
leaders were also targeted. Three mukhtars, traditional village
leaders, were assassinated in June 1988 and El-Bireh Mayor Hassan
Tawil was stabbed in the chest.
   Noting such attacks predated the uprising, an army briefing
paper said: ``The PLO always regarded the involvement of a local
leadership in the territories (of the West Bank and Gaza) as a
threat.''
   When Bethlehem Mayor Elias Freij proposed a ceasefire in the
uprising in exchange for prisoner releases and the opening of
universities, spray-painted graffiti condemned him as a ``traitor''
and threatened him with death. PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat warned
anyone trying to stop the revolt ``exposes himself to the bullets
of our people.''
</TEXT>
