<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0682 04-27 1059</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0682,1,070</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urges US Companies to Work Harder to Prevent Chemicals from
Use in Cocaine</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts 2 grafs after 9th graf bgng, `The association,' to UPDATE
with details of objections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Using the bully pulpit of the White House,
President Bush urged parents and stockholders Thursday to demand
that American companies ``act responsibly'' to prevent U.S.
chemicals from being used to produce cocaine.
   ``No chemicals, no cocaine,'' Bush told an international drug
enforcement conference attended by delegates from 30 nations.
   Cocaine producers use ether, acetone, hydrochloric acid, a
chemical known as MEK and other products to refine their drug from
coca leaves.
   ``Few Americans are aware that illegally diverted barrels of
dangerous chemicals _ clearly marked with U.S. corporate logos _
are routinely seized in the jungles of Colombia,'' Bush said.
   Although Bush referred in his speech to illegal diversions of
chemicals, Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said U.S.
companies currently are free to sell all their products to other
countries.
   As a result of last year's new drug law, however, federal
regulations are being drafted that would require the companies to
tell the Drug Enforcement Agency of the ultimate destination and
use of export shipments of seven products that could be used in
making cocaine, Runkel said. DEA would have 15 days to review the
paperwork and could stop shipments, he said.
   Runkel said chemical companies have filed a stack of objections
four inches high to the rules, but that they were expected to be in
place by May 15 anyway.
   In Washington, the Chemical Manufacturers Association issued a
statement saying the industry ``is already at the front lines'' in
the war against drugs.
   The association, which is made up of companies that manufacture
industrial chemicals, said the industry supported passage of last
year's anti-drug law. Even before the law was passed, the group
said, the industry was already working with law enforcement
officials to ``identify and stop illegal shipments of our
products.''
   Association spokesman Jeff Van said his organization's
objections center on DEA's attempts to take actions that Congress
rejected in previous legislation.
   Primarily, he said, the DEA wants to require chemical companies
to provide detailed reports on their regular customers, while
Congress required only that they list the customers; and the DEA
wants to force the chemical industry to provide statements
certifying that the chemicals are being used lawfully, a proposal
which he said Congress also has turned down.
   Bush made his comments in a speech on the final day of a hectic
four-day trek, visiting nine cities in six states from Virginia to
California and back.
   Although the trip was marred by scheduling problems and did not
make much news nationally, White House Chief of Staff John Sununu
said Bush was satisfied.
   ``He really feels it's important for him to go out and let the
folks see the president,'' Sununu said. ``You just don't always
focus on getting 15 or 30 seconds on the national news.''
   More than 100 Eastern Airlines strikers and their supporters
demonstrated noisily against Eastern chief Frank Lorenzo outside
the Miami hotel where Bush spoke.
   They waved signs with ban-Lorenzo symbols, chanted ``just say
no'' and gave a thumbs-down salute to Bush as his motorcade rode by.
   Bush, who has refused to intervene to end the strike, waved back
at them.
   Bush told the drug conference that ``by and large'' the chemical
industry has supported efforts to halt the flow of U.S. chemicals.
``We've been getting good support from most of the chemical
industry.''
   However, he said, ``industry's got to do more.
   ``And I hope that parents' groups and stockholders are listening
today. We should demand that United States corporations act
responsibly and that they not tolerate their chemicals ending up in
criminal hands.''
   Bush said he would like to see ``U.S. chemical manufacturers
demonstrate their courage and civic responsibility by entering into
a true partnership with our government as we try to stop narcotics
at the source.''
   ``These companies can make an important contribution to our
nation's fight against illegal drugs. They should make it their job
to join in.''
   Sununu told reporters that the chemical companies deserve
recognition for their voluntary efforts. However, he said,
``There's no question that there are still some strange purchases
of chemicals that take place.''
   Asked if Bush was suggesting complicity by some drug companies
in the use of chemicals to refine cocaine, Sununu replied, ``I
don't think that was the suggestion at all. It's just a call for
additional cooperation above and beyond the normal.''
   Bush said the products used to produce cocaine are ``chemical
time bombs.''
   In Peru, for example, he said 175,000 pounds of sulfuric acid
are dumped each year into tributaries of the Upper Huallaga Valley.
   ``Anyone concerned about the legacy of defoliation in Southeast
Asia ought to go see what illegally diverted chemicals are
beginning to do to the Andes right now,'' he said.
   In the United States, drug agents busted a houseboat lab on
California's Sacramento River that was dumping hydrochloric acid
and other waste into water within splashing distance of children
swimming, Bush said.
   ``Today I pledge to you that the United States will lead the
fight against illicit shipments of precursor chemicals,'' the
president said.
   He said drug-producing nations _ in Latin America _ and
drug-consuming nations _ chiefly the United States _ should stop
blaming each other for the drug scourge.
   ``Ultimately, the solution to the United States drug problem
lies within our own borders: stepped-up enforcement, education and
treatment as well.''
   Bush said that casual cocaine users ``can no longer claim
non-combatant status'' in the war on drugs. ``There is blood on
their hands.''
   He said that realization ``has begun to sear the consciences of
the stockbrokers and the students, the lawyers and the homemakers
and the athletes who finance our common enemy.''
   In a separate appearance in Miami, Bush dedicated a high-tech
center run by the Coast Guard and Customs Service to spot drug
traffickers in the air and at sea.
   ``Think of this as one of America's drug war situation rooms, as
our early warning network against narcotics,'' Bush said.
   Before returning to Washington, Bush stopped in Palm Harbor in
Pinellas County to dedicate a 51-bed care center at a retirement
center for victims of Alzheimers Disease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
