<FIRST>r i AM-Chile-Cabinet     04-27 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Cabinet,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pinochet Changes Education, Mining Ministers But Keeps Interior Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military President Augusto Pinochet's
office said Thursday he will name new ministers of education and
mining, but it indicated no plans to replace Interior Minister
Carlos Caceres.
   Local press and radio had predicted Caceres' departure in a
conflict with Pinochet over proposed democratic reforms.
   On Wednesday, Gen. Pinochet asked all 15 members of his Cabinet
to hand in their resignations to give him ``freedom of action'' in
making changes, a spokesman said.
   On Thursday, his press office said he accepted the resignations
only of Education Minister Juan Guzman and Mining Minister Pablo
Baraona.
   According to local press reports that the government has not
denied, Caceres and Pinochet disagreed over the extent of proposed
amendments to the 1980 Constitution and other legal reforms sought
by the opposition.
   Caceres has been negotiating the changes with civilian
politicians, and he said last week he is ready to make a firm
proposal for the changes.
   The reforms would include modifying a constitutional ban on
Marxism and altering Congress and a powerful military-controlled
National Security Council. Opposition parties are pressing for the
reforms before scheduled Dec. 14 national elections to pick a
successor to Pinochet and a Congress.
   Pinochet, the army commander, seized power in a 1973 coup. He
proposed in a referendum last October to remain in power until
1997. Voters rejected the proposal, obliging him to call elections.
   Caceres was named interior minister, the top political position
in the Cabinet, shortly after the referendum.
   Patricio Aylwin, spokesman for an opposition coalition of 17
parties, said the retention of Caceres is ``probably a good
indication, showing a willingness by the government to reach an
agreement on constitutional changes.''
   Andres Allamand, secretary general of the pro-goverment National
Renovation, said Pinochet's decision to keep Caceres ``guarantees
that there will be substantial constitutional changes.''
</TEXT>
