<FIRST>r w AM-Soviets-Grain     04-27 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviets-Grain,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Want More Grain Than U.S. Will Sell, Congressman Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government on Thursday raised the
amount of grain the Soviet Union can purchase this year to 24
million metric tons, but a farm state congressman said Soviet
negotiators aren't happy with the deal.
   The Soviets, who previously had a limit of 20 million tons on
the amount of U.S. grain they could buy this year, wanted to expand
the amount to 30 million tons under the Export Enhancement Program,
said Rep. David Nagle, D-Iowa.
   Nagle, who is a member of the House Agriculture Committee, said
U.S. negotiators told the Soviets they could not use the subsidy
program.
   Attempts to contact Soviet officials at their embassy in
Washington were unsuccessful.
   Kelly Shipp, press secretary to Agriculture Secretary Clayton
Yeutter, said the agreement does not stipulate whether the Export
Enhancement Program will be used during the sale. She said the
talks were about the amount of grain the Soviets could buy, not its
price.
   An Agriculture Department official told a Senate subcommittee
last week that EEP sales had been put on hold pending a budget
review, an announcement that stirred controversy for the program.
   The program is popular with foreign buyers because it makes U.S.
commodities cheaper. It also helps the United States stay
competitive with countries that heavily subsidize their exports.
   But no EEP applications have been processed since the end of
February.
   Members of Congress say they have tried unsuccessfully to find
out whether the Bush administration has suspended the program as
part of negotiations in the Uruguay Round trade talks. The U.S.
position at those talks is that all countries should remove or
drastically reduce subsidies on their exports.
   Shipp, Yeutter's spokeswoman, said the program has been slowed
down because of weather and stock conditions and because there is a
new administration, but it has not been suspended.
   She noted that domestic wheat supplies are lower than they have
been in 15 years and the EEP program draws on those stocks.
   Nagle said his sources told him Vice President Dan Quayle, who
arrived in Australia on Wednesday, assured the Australians that the
United States was backing off the export subsidy program.
   Australia also wants other countries to remove such subsidies
and has been pursuing that end even more aggressively than the
United States.
   Meanwhile, the Agriculture Department also announced Thursday
that the Soviet Union has bought an additional 150,000 metric tons
of corn for delivery this year under its long-term supply agreement
with the United States.
   Officials said the latest sales brought total corn sold to the
Soviets for delivery in 1988-89 to more than 13.2 million tons.
   In addition to the wheat and corn, sales include 450,000 tons of
soybeans, 1.4 million tons of soybean meal and 507,400 of grain
sorghum.
   The latest corn sale and the other grain is for delivery by
Sept. 30, the end of the sixth year of a long-term grain supply
agreement.
   The original agreement said the Soviets could purchase 12
million tons of grain, but would be able to come back periodically
to request more.
</TEXT>
