<FIRST>u a AM-Brawley     04-27 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brawley,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Tawana Admits Hoax; Advisers Denounce Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY20</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tawana Brawley, the black teen-ager who made
national headlines after claiming she was abducted and raped by a
gang of white men, admitted to her boyfriend that she and her
mother made up the story, a newspaper reported Thursday.
   Miss Brawley made the admission two weeks ago to Daryl T.
Rodriguez, 19, who became her boyfriend a few weeks before the
alleged abduction in Wappingers Falls on Nov. 24, 1987, when Miss
Brawley was 15, New York Newsday reported.
   A grand jury concluded last year that Miss Brawley, who was
found in a plastic garbage bag, smeared with feces and with racial
epithets scrawled on her body, had faked being raped.
   The Newsday story ``tends to corroborate everything that the
grand jury discovered and the conclusions it reached,'' said Tim
Gilles, speaking for state Attorney General Robert Abrams, the
special prosecutor who handled the case.
   Gilles said that although there no longer was a question of
criminal prosecution in the case, the attorney general wanted to
interview Rodriguez to confirm the story because ``it would be in
the public interest and satisfying to everyone to fill in some of
the final pieces.''
   The story, written by Newsday's assistant managing editor, Les
Payne, was denounced in a radio interview by two of Miss Brawley's
advisers, Alton Maddox and the Rev. Al Sharpton. They accused the
newspaper of trying to divert attention from what they called white
establishment lies about the recent Central Park gang rape case.
   Miss Brawley, who lives in Virginia Beach, Va., denied the
account and said she hadn't seen Rodriguez since last summer, the
newspaper said.
   Newsday said Miss Brawley told Rodriguez that she and her
mother, Glenda, invented the story to keep Ralph King, her mother's
lover, from beating the girl.
   Sharpton and two lawyers, Maddox and C. Vernon Mason, kept Miss
Brawley and her mother away from the grand jury while conducting a
publicity campaign that depicted the state investigation as a
coverup to protect the rapists, among whom they alleged were a
police officer and an assistant district attorney.
   Sharpton said the Newsday story, coming as the Central Park
``wilding'' rampage by black youths unfolds, was meant to deflect
the public from making comparisons ``between how the justice system
responds to the rape of a black girl and the rape of a white
woman.''
   Maddox, sounding the same theme in an interview on WLIB, said
that so far there ``hasn't been any evidence of a rape or of this
woman being assaulted or attacked at all'' in Central Park.
   ``We don't even know if she's over at Metropolitan Hospital or
not,'' yet that is accepted as true, while Miss Brawley's case is
branded a hoax, Maddox said.
</TEXT>
