<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Gingrich     04-27 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gingrich,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Says GOP Must Build `Caring, Humanitarian' Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four House Democrats on Thursday called for
the appointment of an outside counsel to investigate allegations
that Republican Whip Newt Gingrich violated House rules in his
financial dealings.
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., filed a formal complaint with the
House ethics committee earlier this month alleging 10 apparent rule
violations in the formation and operation of a limited partnership
set up to promote a 1984 book co-authored by Gingrich.
   But Reps. Barney Frank of Massachusetts, Larry Smith of Florida,
Pat Schroeder of Colorado and Albert Bustamante of Texas, are
asking Democratic colleagues to support their letter to the ethics
panel chairman, Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., calling for an outside
counsel.
   In the letter to Dixon, the Democrats said such an appointment
to investigate the charges against Gingrich would ``preserve the
integrity of the committee's consideration process from
politicization and outside pressure.''
   The committee has not indicated whether it will launch a formal
investigation of Alexander's complaint, which was filed as the
committee neared the end of the investigation Gingrich initiated of
House Speaker Jim Wright.
   Gingrich earlier this week denied any wrongdoing in connection
with the partnership and released nearly 400 pages of documents
detailing its financial and incorporation history.
   The partnership was formed with $5,000 investments from 18
individuals and three corporations. Many of the investors were
wealthy Republicans who regularly contributed to Gingrich's
campaigns. In return for promoting the book, the partnership was to
have received half the publisher's profits, but the publisher lost
money and the investors ended up with tax writeoffs.
   Earlier Thursday, Gingrich used a National Press Club luncheon
to outline the message of Democratic corruption and Republican
opportunity that he has used to propel himself into the House GOP
leadership.
   He said the GOP must build a ``caring, humanitarian, reform''
party to offer voters an alternative to a Democratic party that is
``committed to propping up a system that's dying.''
   ``Every conservative in America must confront the reality that
the great age of opposition conservatism is over,'' he said.
``Goldwater and Reagan won the argument and now the country wants
us to govern. We must come up with a wave of reforms of
extraordinary scale.''
   Gingrich, who instigated the investigation that resulted in
Wright's being the first speaker ever charged with violating House
rules, said that America must undergo dramatic change to meet the
challenges of the 1990s, and that change must be focused on the
system rather than on personalities.
   ``I don't think any person in America can look at our
competitive situation in the world market, can look at the
pressures of high technology, can look at the rate of change in the
Soviet Union and China and then turn to our major cities and not
come to the conclusion that we are on the verge of absolutely
catastrophic decay in the 1990s,'' he said.
   The reasons for that decay, Gingrich argued, are drugs and
violent crime, the collapse of education systems in major cities,
the inability of unionized city bureaucracies to meet the needs of
the urban poor, the penetration of labor unions and city
governments by organized crime and the Democratic domination of
Congress.
   Gingrich said Democrats have so insulated themselves on Capitol
Hill that Soviet provincial leaders were 16 times more likely to be
defeated this year than were incumbent members of Congress.
   ``That is a fundamental insult to the constitutional freedoms of
American and it is nothing more than a game written on Capitol Hill
by a left-wing party that knows it cannot possibly survive in fair
elections in this country, and therefore they cheat every day,'' he
said.
   As an example of such ``Democratic cheating,'' Gingrich cited
franking rules that he said permitted Congress to spend ``more
money last year on franked mail than every challenger for the House
and Senate spent on everything.''
</TEXT>
