<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WinerySlayings     04-27 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Winery Slayings,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ramon Salcido's Ex-Wife Recounts Violence and Fear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first wife of confessed mass slayer
Ramon Salcido said the former winery worker terrorized her and once
threatened to kill her, a newspaper reported Thursday.
   Debra Salcido, 27, hid in terror during the three days and
nights her ex-husband was on the run and says that if their
daughter asks about her father, she will tell her he is dead,
according to a report in The Fresno Bee.
   ``When she comes of age I don't know what I'm going to tell
her,'' Debra Salcido said of the couple's 4-year-old daughter, who
does not know who her father is. ``I can't tell her her father's a
killer. If I can do it, I'm going to tell her he's dead. I hope by
then he will be.''
   After learning that her ex-husband was suspected of the slayings
in California's picturesque wine country, she fled with her
daughter and a 3-year-old son from a subsequent marriage.
   Ramon Salcido has been accused of slashing or shooting to death
seven people on April 14, including his wife, Angela, two of his
three young daughters, his mother-in-law, two young sisters-in-law
and his boss.
   He is being held in isolation in Sonoma County Jail.
   In her only interview since the slayings, Debra Salcido
described the frequent beatings she experienced during her brief
marriage to the man who now faces possible execution if convicted
of his alleged crimes.
   One incident occurred in late 1983 or early 1984 at the couple's
home in Sonoma, during which she said Ramon Salcido's
alcohol-fueled temper exploded.
   ``He got me onto the floor and put his knees on my arms,'' she
said. ``He took a pair of scissors and put them right to my throat
and said `I could kill you,''' while dripping saliva on her face.
   On another occasion, she said, Salcido came home drunk, and when
she refused to say where she had been that day, he took a
.22-caliber rifle from beneath the sofa and waved it wildly.
   Three weeks later, after she learned she was pregnant, she left
Salcido.
   During the agonizing international manhunt for the suspected
killer, Debra Salcido moved with her family to a Fresno motel,
where they learned that Ramon Salcido's three daughters were found
with their throats slit in a county dump. Only one of the victims,
Carmina, survived the attack. Panicked, Mrs. Salcido had a friend
pick up her daughter.
   In the years since the couple's separation and divorce, Mrs.
Salcido had a son by a man who was murdered in Mexico in January
1986.
   After she moved to Fresno and began collecting welfare, the
local district attorney pressed for child support from Ramon
Salcido for care of the couple's little girl.
   Authorities believe this dispute may have ignited the rage that
led to the murders. Ramon Salcido confessed to the slayings after
he was captured April 19 in his native Mexico.
   Following the killings, Salcido's blood-spattered car was found
with a note that read, in Spanish: ``Forgive me God, but this law
made me do it. We could live better, me and my children, but what
can I do.''
   Salcido's wife, Angela, called Debra Salcido about five weeks
ago and asked why Debra had filed the complaint, which sought
$5,807 in back payments and monthly payments of $511, Debra Salcido
said.
   ``Angela asked whether I would be willing to go to the DA's
office and say that the child was not his and that I had made a
mistake on the birth certificate,'' said Salcido, who refused the
request.
   Her account contradicts earlier reports that Angela was unaware
until the day before the murders that Ramon Salcido had been
married previously.
   Investigators have also speculated that the motive for the
killings was Ramon Salcido's belief that Angela was having an
affair.
</TEXT>
