<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Budget     04-27 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Budget,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Finance Minister Presents Budget Amid Calls For Resignation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Figures are in U.S. dollars.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance Minister Michael Wilson delivered a widely
criticized federal budget to the House of Commons on Thursday, and
opposition members walked out to protest the leak of the budget to
the media a day earlier.
   The combination of a new 9 percent sales tax on most goods and
services, higher income and corporate taxes and spending cuts
disappointed taxpayers, labor organizations and business groups.
   Wilson released the budget late Wednesday night after leaked
details were broadcast by Global Television.
   Commons Speaker John Fraser went so far as to suspend the House
of Commons to decide whether to allow Wilson to present his budget.
He later permitted Wilson to present it despite protests from the
opposition Liberals and New Democrats, who said the finance
minister had soiled parliamentary tradition by refusing to resign
after the leak.
   Only one opposition member, the Reform Party's Deborah Grey,
remained in the House for Wilson's 10-minute speech.
   Conservative Prime Minister Brian Mulroney defended his finance
minister, blaming an unidentified bureaucrat for the leak, and said
he would not accept his resignation.
   Wilson said the leak ``did not result from negligence ... or
lack of proper security arrangements'' and its premature release
appeared to have resulted from ``a breach of trust, a willful
criminal act.''
   The budget itself, which has a $26.5 billion deficit, did little
to improve the stature of Wilson, a 51-year-old Toronto
stockbroker, within the Canadian business community.
   ``What a mockery is going to be made of us on the world stage,''
said Stephen Wateridge of the Bank of Montreal. The Canadian
Chamber of Commerce called it a disappointment and a lost
opportunity for deficit reduction.
   The budget called for increased taxes on cigarettes, alcohol and
gasoline as well as increases of $1 billion in corporate taxes and
$1.2 billion in personal taxes.
   Plans to develop a nuclear-powered submarine fleet will be
shelved under a strategy to save $2.2 billion in defense spending
over the next five years. In addition, 14 military bases across
Canada are to be closed or scaled down.
   Under the $6.7 billion submarine program, the government was
considering building 10 to 12 vessels according to designs
purchased from France _ for its Rubis-Amethyste-class boat _ or
from Britain, for its Trafalgar-class vessel.
   The budget promises to cut the $26.5 billion deficit in half by
1993-94. It drastically shrinks the proposed national child-care
program. About $1.9 billion in tax breaks for parents will remain,
but $3.4 billion cost-sharing proposal with the Canadian provinces
will be put on hold.
   The leak resulted in the government's rushing out the budget and
forced Wilson to dismantle careful plans to release the budget in
its most favorable light.
   Mulroney blamed an unidentified whistle-blower who he said
leaked the budget to a television reporter.
   Responding to calls for Wilson's resignation, he shouted across
the floor to opponents, ``You should be worried about the guy who
stole the property.''
   Liberal leader John Turner sharply criticized Wilson for not
resigning. He said the rights of every Canadian had been violated
because the leak might have been used for personal gain by those
who had advance notice of the budget contents.
   Neither Turner nor any other opposition member had any evidence
that anyone gained from the budget leak.
   New Democrat Leader Ed Broadbent said Wilson's credibility ``is
now completely shot'' and that the government should withdraw the
budget and present another one later.
   Investigations were being conducted Thursday into the
possibility that people used the advance information in the budget
to make profits on the stock market.
   Police were questioning anyone involved in printing the budget.
Supply Minister Paul Dick told the Commons that ``every single
individual'' among the more than 200 people involved in printing
the budget had been cleared to handle secret material.
</TEXT>
