<FIRST>r a AM-President'sBugs     04-27 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-President's Bugs,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Bush's Elm Tree Came With Tiny Bugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American elm tree President Bush
planted on the state Capitol grounds amid great fanfare this week
came with some uninvited guests _ tiny bugs a forester said could
be destructive gypsy moth larvae.
   Bush, who was guest of honor at a tree-planting ceremony Monday
afternoon, brought along the elm, which he said was a descendant of
a tree President John Quincy Adams planted on the White House
grounds.
   Paul Blumhardt, Bismarck city forester, reluctantly confirmed
several tiny, caterpillar-like bugs were picked off the tree after
it was planted.
   ``The tree wasn't unwrapped two minutes when we noticed it,''
Blumhardt said Wednesday. He believes the critters are gypsy moth
larvae, but tests to determine exactly what they are were not
finished, Blumhardt said.
   ``I don't think it's worth causing embarrassment to the
president,'' the forester said. ``He'll say, `The next time I'm
invited to North Dakota, to hell with them.'''
   The ceremony was part of North Dakota's celebration of its 100th
anniversary of statehood. Officials hope to plant 100 million trees
in the state by the year 2,000 as part of the celebration.
   The gypsy moth is common in the northeastern United States. Its
larvae, which can grow to more than 2 inches long, defoliate trees
by eating the leaves.
   The bugs found on Bush's elm tree were less than an eighth of an
inch long, so tiny a microscope was used to get a good look at
them, Blumhardt said.
   The forester said the visible bugs were picked off the tree, and
it was sprayed with an insecticide, as was the truck the tree was
transported in and the burlap in which it was wrapped.
   In six or seven weeks, monitoring traps will be set up around
the tree to make sure there are not any adult gypsy moths around,
Blumhardt said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
