<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0713 04-27 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockets Fall, But Rival Lebanese Governments, Syria Back Truce Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with all sides declaring support
for cease-fire. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite shellfire still rocking Beirut,
Lebanon's rival Christian and Moslem governments and Syria declared
support for the Arab League's call on Thursday for a cease-fire to
halt the seven-week bloodbath.
   Their separate statements came as Syrian and Christian gunners
dueled with mortars and rockets across Beirut's dividing Green Line
_ well after Arab foreign ministers appealed at their meeting in
Tunis for a truce in Lebanon.
   One man was killed and two were wounded in the fighting, which
sent thousands of people scurrying for cover in basements and
underground bomb shelters.
   The Christian Cabinet under army commander Gen. Michel Aoun
pledged to cooperate with a 312-man observer force the Arab League
will send here to monitor the cease-fire, called for noon Friday (6
a.m. EDT).
   ``It is a modest step in the right direction to lift the Syrian
hegemony off Lebanon,'' said a statement issued by Aoun's three-man
military Cabinet after a late-night session.
   The Cabinet welcomed the Arab League call to lift air, land and
sea blockades imposed in the latest round of Lebanon's 14-year-old
civil war.
   It ordered that Beirut International Airport, closed since March
12, be reopened simultaenously with the cease-fire deadline.
   The Aoun Cabinet also said it will ask the U.N. Security Council
to meet in New York to ``work out a mechanism to implement its
Resolution 425 which calls for Israel to withdraw'' from a border
strip it occupies in south Lebanon.
   Rival acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads a mainly
Moslem Cabinet, issued a statement in Moslem west Beirut pledging
full cooperation with the Arab League observer force.
   In Damascus, the capital of Syria, the official Syrian Arab News
Agency said the government of President Hafez Assad was
``satisified with resolutions announced by the Arab League on
Lebanon.''
   It quoted unidentified observers as saying the resolutions were
tantamount to a ``slap to Aoun and his isolationist, Zionist gang.''
   Whether the carnage actually would stop after Thursday's
welcoming statements by the warring factions was another question.
Three previous cease-fire calls by the Arab League failed to halt
the fighting.
   The 22-member Arab League's effort to end Lebanon's worst
outbreak of violence in four years came at a two-day emergency
meeting in the Tunisian capital.
   Aoun's 20,000-strong army has been locked since March 8 in
ferocious fighting with an alliance of Syrian troops and Druse
Moslem militiamen.
   By police count, 273 people have been killed and 993 wounded in
the clashes. Most of the victims have been civilians who fell in
the indiscriminate shelling of population centers in and around the
capital.
   Radio stations in the Moslem and Christian sectors of Beirut
interrupted regular programming Thursday to broadcast the Arab
League resolutions.
   Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, has been insisting that the Arab
League make a direct reference to Syrian involvement in the
fighting, instead of portraying the crisis as one between Lebanese
Christains and Moslems.
   He also wants the League to pressure Syria to withdraw an
estimated 40,000 troops stationed in Moslem regions under a 1976
Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   The Arab League final statement in Tunis said an observer force,
to be commanded by a Kuwaiti officer, would deploy along the
demarcation line between the battling factions, keep points of
passage open and identify the party responsible for any violation.
   It said the League would make $3 million available immediately
to cover start-up costs for the observers, and that full financing
from member countries should be put in place by May 10.
   The mission was set for three months.
   Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa told reporters Syria was
ready to give any aid requested by a special six-member Arab League
committee charged with resolving the civil war.
   Fighting broke out two days after Aoun clamped a blockade on
illegal ports run by Moslem militias south of Beirut in an attempt
to restore the long-eroded authority of the state.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt retaliated by shelling the
310-square-mile Christian enclave. The Syrians later joined the
bombardment and besieged the Christians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
