<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-WarCriminal     04-27 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-War Criminal,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch War Criminal Dies After His Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Aus der Fuenten, a war
criminal jailed for 43 years for his role in deporting tens of
thousands of Dutch Jews to Nazi extermination camps, died less than
three months after his release from a Dutch prison, Dutch
television reported Thursday. He was 79.
   The report, attributed to the prison warden, said Aus der
Fuenten died in West Germany eight days ago and has already been
buried, but it gave no details.
   A telephone operator at the prison in Breda in the southern
Netherlands, where Aus der Fuenten served his term after World War
II, said the warden was not available for comment.
   Aus der Fuenten was released and expelled to West Germany on
Jan. 27 with another convicted war criminal, 87-year-old Franz
Fischer.
   Known as the ``Breda Two,'' they were the world's longest-held
war criminals.
   Their release followed an unusual vote in the Dutch Parliament
and brought angry protest by the nation's still-vocal organizations
of resistance fighters.
   During the war, Aus der Fuenten was an SS administrator of a
body that oversaw the mass deportations of Dutch Jews. Of a prewar
population of 100,000 Dutch Jews, only 10,000 returned from the
death camps.
   A Dutch court sentenced Aus der Fuenten to death in 1950, but
his sentence was commuted the same year.
   In the parliamentary debate that resulted in their release,
Justice Minister Frits Korthals Altes said Aus der Fuenten and
Fischer were ``symbols of Nazi evil and an unending source of of
sorrow and strife. ... Let's rid our society of the miserable
remainder of the two war criminals' lives.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
