<HEAD>Eastwood Denies Claims of Lawsuit by Actress Sondra Locke</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Sondra is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clint Eastwood on Thursday denied claims made
by his longtime companion Sondra Locke in a lawsuit that contended
the tough-guy actor promised to support her for life but has kicked
her out.
   ``I am deeply disappointed and saddened that she's taken this
kind of action,'' Eastwood said in a statement issued by publicist
Deborah Kelman.
   ``It will soon come to light that these accusations are
unfounded and without merit, however, this matter will be dealt
with in an appropriate legal arena. Beyond that I have no
comment,'' Eastwood said.
   Miss Locke, 41, filed the lawsuit Wednesday in Superior Court,
seeking unspecified damages, title to the two homes and an equal
division of property acquired during the couple's 10-year
relationship.
   The lawsuit also claims Eastwood, 58, persuaded Miss Locke, an
actress and director, to undergo two abortions and a sterility
operation because he did not want children.
   Miss Locke, nominated for an Academy Award for the 1968 movie,
``The Heart is a Lonely Hunter,'' co-starred with Eastwood in
``Gauntlet'' ``The Outlaw Josey Wales'' and several other movies.
   According to the lawsuit, Miss Locke began living with Eastwood
in 1978.
   She claimed they broke up in December and that on April 10,
Eastwood removed her clothing, pet parrot and other items from a
Bel-Air home where she was living alone.
