<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Soviet-Scientist 1stLd-Writethru a0677 04-27 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Scientist, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resolution Calls 20 Deaths in Soviet Georgia a Criminal Act</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: CORRECTS spelling to Sagdeyev throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Academy of Sciences passed a
resolution last week declaring that the deaths of 20 demonstrators
in Soviet Georgia constituted a ``criminal act'' that signaled
danger to Kremlin reforms, a prominent Soviet space scientist said
Thursday.
   Roald Sagdeyev, a Soviet reformer elected last month to the
newly created Congress of Peoples' Deputies, released the text of
the resolution here.
   Sagdeyev was one of three members of the Soviet Academy of
Sciences, along with human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov and
Russian historian Dmitri S. Likhachev, who were elected to the
congress and agreed to serve on a parliamentary investigating panel.
   ``The tragic events in Tbilisi (capital of Soviet Georgia)
confirm the sad fact that perestroika is in danger,'' said the
resolution, using the Russian name for Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reforms.
   Special uniformed troops under the Soviet Interior Ministry, or
MVD, were responsible for using poisonous chemicals, shovels and
clubs to suppress the demonstrations in Tbilisi on April 9, killing
20 people, the statement said.
   ``This unusually cruel act has evoked the deep indignation and
outrage of our entire society,'' said the resolution, which
Sagdeyev said was passed at a meeting of the entire Academy of
Sciences April 21.
   ``It completely contradicts'' the reform program, ``is
completely incompatible with the accepted moral and legal norms of
a civilized government, and must be seen as a criminal act against
the people,'' the resolution said.
   Sagdeyev said the events in Tbilisi were especially troubling
because ``it was the suppression of ethnic Georgians by ethnic
Russian troops'' from the city of Gorky, in central Russia.
   Ethnic Russians form about half the 280 million population in
the Soviet Union, and their political power is far greater than the
numbers would suggest.
   Much of the unrest that has gripped the Soviet Union since
Gorbachev rose to power four years ago has come from residents of
the 14 non-Russian republics who, like the Georgians who
demonstrated, would like greater autonomy from Russian rule.
   The head of the Communist Party in Georgia, Givi Gumbaridze,
newly appointed after the April 9 deaths, has confirmed reports
that some of the demonstrators were killed by a toxic gas, the
exact nature of which has not been disclosed.
   Sagdeyev said it appeared final approval for using the MVD
troops against the demonstrators came from local officials in
Georgia.
   ``I do not think we should put all the blame on central
authorities,'' he said.
   Unrest in Georgia took a violent turn in part because of young
extremists among the demonstrators and in part because local
Communist Party officials were out of step with the populace, he
said.
   Far larger demonstrations in the Baltic republics of Lithuania,
Latvia and Estonia by and large have not resulted in violence, with
the exception of a police crackdown in Lithuania in September 1988
that resulted in no deaths but led to the removal of the local
party chief.
   ``I think that there is much better understanding in the Baltic
republics between the communist authorities and the popular
fronts'' which have been formed there, he said.
   Sagdeyev said the paramilitary anti-riot units involved in the
Georgian violence were formed under the MVD last July after the
Supreme Soviet drafted legislation banning anti-Soviet
demonstrations. Sagdeyev was one of 31 members of the Supreme
Soviet or parliament who voted against the legislation when it was
passed last October. Sagdeyev said he viewed the law as a threat to
reform and would seek to have it repealed.
   ``The anti-perestroika forces are becoming stronger and more
active than we would like to believe. Their main weapon is the
concealment and distortion of truthful information,'' said the
Academy of Sciences resolution, which was drafted in large part by
Sagdeyev.
   Gorbachev, president of the Soviet Union and general secretary
of the Communist Party, consolidated his rule on Tuesday by
accepting the resignations of 74 aged voting members of the
301-member Central Committee.
   Those who resigned had lost the party or government jobs that
had won them spots on the Central Committee, and were viewed widely
as potential threats to Gorbachev's reform.
</TEXT>
