<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Coulouris     04-27 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Coulouris,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor George Coulouris Dies At 85</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor George Coulouris, who played cold-hearted
lawyer Walter Parks Thatcher in the 1941 Orson Welles' movie
classic ``Citizen Kane'' and specialized in villains throughout his
career, has died, his wife said Thursday.
   English-born Coulouris, who spent more than 20 years in the
United States and worked in Hollywood in its heyday, died Tuesday
of heart failure brought on by Parkinson's disease, Elizabeth
Coulouris said from their north London home.
   His notable roles included a blackmailing Romanian count in the
1943 movie ``Watch on the Rhine,'' a Nazi posing as a Belgian
patriot in ``The Master Race'' in 1944, a treacherous territorial
magnate in the 1946 western ``California,'' and the bogus
psychiatrist who invites Claudette Colbert to commit suicide in
``Sleep My Love'' in 1948.
   Later films in which he appeared included Carol Reed's ``An
Outcast of the Islands'' in 1951, ``Papillon'' in 1973, ``Mahler''
in 1974, and ``Murder on the Orient Express'' also in 1974.
   Coulouris was also an accomplished stage actor. In the 1930s, he
appeared with the Mercury Theater company founded by Welles, and
gave arresting stage performances in London as a ruthless agent in
Clifford Odet's ``The Big Knife'' in 1954 and as Gen. Sikorski in
Rolf Hochhuth's controversial ``Soldiers'' in 1968.
   Born Oct. 1, 1903 to a Greek father and English mother in
Salford in northern England, Coulouris ran away from home to become
an actor against his businessman father's wishes.
   Tall, impressive and with powerful hooded eyes, he attended the
prestigious Central School of Speech and Drama in London, studying
with Peggy Ashcroft and Laurence Olivier.
   He made his London stage debut in Shakespeare's ``Henry V'' in
1926, went to New York in 1929 and landed his first major stage
roles.
   He made friends with Welles while appearing in the Broadway play
``Ten Million Ghosts'' and later recalled in an interview how he
delighted in taking the American actor, producer and director
``down a peg or two.''
   In 1943, Coulouris mounted and starred in his own Broadway
production of Shakespeare's ``Richard III'' but for once his relish
for villainy took him too far. One critic described him playing the
evil hunchback king as ``a screen Bela Lugosi crossed with a
grand-opera Quasimodo.''
   In the early 1950s, Coulouris returned to live in Britain,
joining the Bristol Old Vic theater company where he played the
name role in French playwright Moliere's famous 17th century comedy
``Tartuffe.'' In 1970 he played Big Daddy in a London stage
production of Tennessee Williams' ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof.''
   He appeared in many British films, stepping out of his sinister
acting persona to play comedy in the 1954 movie ``Doctor in the
House.''
   In the the 1960s and 1970s he tried his hand at horror movies,
appearing in ``The Skull'' in 1965, ``Blood of the Mummy's Tomb''
in 1971 and ``The Antichrist'' in 1975.
   Coulouris once told an interviewer: ``I'm never in line for an
ordinary part _ an English barrister (lawyer), say, with some
sensible line to deliver. Some silly bastard always says:
Coulouris? He's a foreigner, isn't he?''
   He once listed his favorite stage roles as Othello, Macbeth and
King Lear.
   The large, powerful performer disliked television, claiming its
small screen restricted an actor's range. ``Television has wrecked
acting because it's impossible to make a stirring success,'' he
said in an interview.
   He is survived by a son and a daughter from his first wife,
Louise, who died in 1976.
</TEXT>
