<HEAD>Guerrillas Kill Congressman</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0768 to restore writethru designation</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details, mine strike. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shining Path guerrillas shot and killed a
leftist congressman Thursday, the government news agency said. He
was the highest-ranking official assassinated in the nine-year
insurgency.
   Eriberto Arroyo was slain in Chaclacayo, a surburb on Lima's
outskirts, the Andina news agency quoted police as saying.
   The news agency blamed the Maoist guerrillas, but a member of
Arroyo's United Left Party, Sen. Edmundo Murrugarra, blamed the
anti-guerilla death squad, the Rodrigo Franco Command.
   The Franco Command surfaced a year ago, vowing to kill people it
considers leftist guerrillas or their supporters. The government
has denied opposition charges that the group is linked to the
governing center-left Aprista Party.
   Arroyo was a congressional deputy from the United Left, a
coalition of Marxist parties and Peru's second strongest party in
Congress. He was the first legislator killed in the insurgency.
   Murrugarra said a gunman in a vehicle with three others opened
fire as Arroyo and his wife were dropping their three children off
at school.
   The other members of Arroyo's family were uninjured, Radio
Programas said.
   The Shining Path, which seeks to impose Marxist rule, has
assassinated scores of politicians. Most have been from the Aprista
party but officials from the United Left and other parties also
have been slain. None have been congressmen, however.
   In the Amazon jungle, a woman was killed and five people wounded
when a column of pro-Cuban guerrillas raided a river town and held
it for four hours, the Lima newspaper El Comercio said Thursday.
   The respected Lima daily said at least 150 members of the Tupac
Amaru Revolutionary Movement stormed Contamana on the Ucayali
River, 390 miles northeast of Lima, late Tuesday.
   The Interior Ministry said it could not confirm the report.
   Ten defenders in the town's police post traded shots with the
attackers for an hour before running out of ammunition and fleeing
into the surrounding dense jungles, El Comercio said.
   The guerrillas robbed three banks and bombed several government
offices before withdrawing, El Comercio said.
   The Tupac Amaru group, which endorses a Cuba-style Marxism, has
been active since 1984. The group is not connected to the larger
Shining Path.
   Also Thursday, miners across Peru began a three-day strike
demanding that mine owners agree to negotiate all labor contracts
jointly, the union said.
   It was not known how many of the nation's estimated 70,000
miners joined the walkout.
   The National Federation of Mine Workers, which called the
strike, held two strikes over the same issue in the past year.
   Mining was paralyzed mining for three months and losses reached
$400 million, one-third of the annual exports from Peru's most
important industry.
   But the walkouts failed to force private mine owners to accept
the federation demand that labor contracts of mine unions be
negotiated jointly rather than on the current company-by-company
basis.
</TEXT>
