<FIRST>r a AM-Techno-Bandit     04-27 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Techno-Bandit,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Techno-Bandit Sentenced to 30 Months for Escape Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German whom U.S. authorities
call ``the world's top techno-bandit'' was sentenced Thursday to 30
additional months in federal prison and a $40,100 fine in a daring,
ill-fated helicopter escape attempt from a federal prison.
   Werner Bruchhausen, 49, was given 30-month concurrent sentences
on both of two counts of conspiracy to escape, in addition to the
15-year term imposed on Bruchhausen for sales of classified
technology to Soviet bloc countries.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Steve Dobson urged U.S. District Judge
William Stafford to exceed the sentencing guidelines for the
attempted escape, discounting the defense contention that
Bruchhausen was entrapped.
   Defense attorney Bruce Culpepper asked the judge to stay within
the guidelines, which called for a maximum sentence of 30 months.
He said no decision had been made on an appeal.
   Authorities foiled Bruchhausen's escape by setting up a U.S.
Customs helicopter as the escape aircraft. He had reportedly
offered to pay up to $250,000 for assistance.
   Bruchhausen was taken into custody by an FBI agent and four
prison officers as he started toward the aircraft that swooped down
over the softball field in the prison recreation yard last August.
   Bruchhausen began serving his 15-year sentence for sales of
classified technology at the Tallahassee prison in May 1987.
   Bruchhausen and three others were indicted in August 1981 in Los
Angeles on charges of conspiracy and violating the Export
Administration Act, the Arms Export and Control Act and federal
income tax laws.
   The 60-count indictment charged that from January 1977 through
June 5, 1980, Bruchhausen and the others ``conspired to export from
the United States various high technology commodities'' to East
Germany and elsewhere without export licenses from the State
Department and Commerce Department.
   Dubbed the ``techno-bandit'' by the U.S. Customs Service, he was
arrested May 8, 1985, in London, extradited the following year and
convicted of wire fraud in 1987.
   Bruchhausen allegedly smuggled a microwave receiver system,
semiconductor manufacturing equipment, a computer system and other
military and scientific items to the Soviet bloc through dummy
corporations in California and West Germany.
</TEXT>
