<HEAD>Jackpot Tops $115 Million, Prize Claimants Step Forward</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd, `The big ..., and SUBS 18th graf,
`Reports also ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE with two other ticket holders
claiming to be winners; picks up 19th graf pvs: `A week ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH KIRKPATRICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen winning tickets were picked in
the state's record $115 million lottery jackpot, a computer
analysis showed Thursday, and two winners quickly were claimed by a
group of Ohio factory workers and a Pennsylvania family.
   The big jackpot was totaled at $115,578,980.14, about 30 minutes
after 14 workers from a Windham, Ohio, brick factory arrived to
claim a share of it, said Jim Scroggins, lottery executive director.
   People from Washington, Pa., and East Windsor, N.J., also
claimed to hold winning tickets, but did not arrive at lottery
headquarters Thursday.
   ``I couldn't believe it. I still don't,'' said brick worker
Butch Shavers, 38, of Warren, Ohio.
   Also arriving to claim a winning ticket were Alverto Handel, 65,
of Portage; her son, Jim, 39, of Summer Hill, and her daughter,
Nancy Williams, 34, of Fort Montgomery, N.Y.
   Mrs. Williams said she got six of the winning numbers from a
computerized palm reader at an open-air bazaar when she and her
husband were vacationing in mid-March in the Bahamas.
   ``I didn't believe in them,'' Mrs Williams said of the palm
reader. ``I believe it was just luck.''
   Mrs. Handel added the seventh number, 24, based on the number of
tickets they had purchased.
   Jim Handel is a coal miner, Mrs. Williams is a library
technician at the West Point Military Academy and Mrs. Handel is a
retired house keeper.
   Mrs. Handel said the winning ticket was the first one that she
checked after the numbers were drawn Wednesday night.
   ``I went down the line, sinking my pencil in. Tears came to my
eyes and I couldn't even look at the tickets,'' Mrs. Handel said.
   Scroggins said lottery officials would not be able to confirm
the winning tickets until a second computer analysis is completed.
   Scroggins said each of the 14 jackpot tickets will be worth
$317,524.67 a year, or more than $8.2 million paid out over 26
years.
   The workers from the Harbison-Walker brick factory arrived at
the lottery's headquarters in Middletown, outside Harrisburg, in a
four-vehicle caravan, setting off a wild dash by reporters and
photographers as lottery officials tried to herd the potential
winners into the office by a back door.
   The workers said that they had bought $140 worth of tickets.
Each of them contributed $10 to the pool.
   Scroggins said that it may take until early next week to
validate the ticket presented by the workers, in part because they
do not have a signed, legal agreement among themselves on how their
share of the prize will be distributed.
   In most cases, Scroggins said, jackpot winners call the lottery
first and are told of the necessity of having a lawyer draw up a
dispersement agreement. In this case, he said, the workers did not
call.
   ``They got excited ... and headed on down,'' Scroggins said.
   In Washington in western Pennsylvania, Ed Trapuzzano Sr., said
his niece, Sylvia Ann Trapuzzano, 34, was heading to lottery
headquarters with what she believes is a winning ticket from
Wednesday's drawing.
   However, lottery officials said Thursday afternoon they had not
heard from the woman.
   In East Windsor, N.J., Jay Rosen showed a reporter from New
Jersey Network News a ticket that matched seven of the winning
numbers drawn. Rosen said he owns the ticket with his parents, a
brother and a sister.
   He said the family waited in line one hour too buy $80 worth of
tickets.
   A week of millionaire fantasies ended Wednesday night with the
drawing of the 11 Super 7 numbers. The numbers were
06-16-24-34-35-37-40-41-45-60-71.
   Smaller payouts for matching four, five or six numbers will be
determined by Friday. Prizes for matching six numbers are usually
several thousand dollars; for five they are usually several hundred
dollars and the prize for matching four numbers is $7.
   Lottery security was tightened last year after a bogus jackpot
ticket was presented to lottery officials and a check was issued.
Further checks revealed the ticket was fake, prepared by a computer
technician with access to the lottery system.
   Payment was stopped before the check was cashed and the
technician and an accomplice who claimed the prize were prosecuted.
Two lottery officials were reprimanded.
   ``The validation process is not a two-minute thing,'' Andersen
said. ``It's more like two days. There are extensive security
provisions in place and they will all be followed.''
   The long lines at the state's 3,400 on-line lottery outlets were
generally quieter Thursday.
   ``It's like going from a New Year's Eve party to the morning
after,'' said Rich Mazzocca, manager of a book and card shop in
Palmyra.
</TEXT>
