<FIRST>r w AM-US-Pickens     04-27 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Pickens,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Millionaire Says He's Insulted by Japanese Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. corporate takeover strategist T. Boone
Pickens Jr., saying he's ``offended'' by the treatment he received
from a major Japanese auto parts company, served notice Thursday he
will pursue his claim to management rights in the company.
   ``Frankly, I was offended'' by the ``brazen'' action of Japan's
Koito Manufacturing Co. to question his ownership of the largest
single block _ 20.2 percent _ of its stock in refusing him three
seats on its board of directors earlier this month, Pickens told
reporters at the Washington foreign press center.
   He also described it as ``frankly, insulting'' to him as the
largest stockholder to have to read in the newspapers rather than
being told personally that his stock ownership was being challenged.
   ``I not going to walk away from this issue, and neither, I
believe, is Washington,'' Pickens said, describing talks with U.S.
government leaders and members of Congress.
   The millionaire Texas oilman said he is asking neither the U.S.
nor Japanese government ``to bail me out of anything I'm in. I can
take care of myself.''
   But the reaction is very strong in both the administration and
Congress that ``something must be done as far as opening up''
Japanese financial markets to equality for foreign buyers, he added.
   ``I don't think the Japanese are going to be able to sit back
and continue to pick and choose in our country what they want to
buy, what they want to invest in and want to own without having the
same opportunities for Americans in Japan,'' he said. ``It's that
simple.''
   ``I don't think you're going to be able to do much about the $55
billion trade deficit with the Japanese unless you do something to
open up markets.''
   Pickens said he reported on his experiences in Japan to Japanese
Ambassador Nobuo Matsunaga in addition to U.S. Commerce Secretary
Robert Mosbacher, Trade Representative Carla Hills, other U.S.
officials and members of Congress.
   Legislation already has been suggested to establish reciprocity
in financial markets, Pickens said, adding, ``I wouldn't want to
see anything foolish'' proposed, and the best thing would be for
the two countries to cooperate in opening markets.
   ``I see the Japanese pouring $15 billion into our country buying
real estate and ranches, other ownership. They're treated just
exactly like other stockholders in this country, but ... there's
some reason we're not wanted in Japan.'' Reports from Tokyo said a
tenet of Japanese business culture is that enterprises belong
basically to their employees rather than stockholders.
   ``I plan to attend the annual meeting of Koito in Japan June 29
and will continue to assert my rights as a shareholder, in fact,
the largest one in the company,'' Pickens said.
   He said he purchased the 20.2 percent stock interest in Koito on
March 16 with the knowledge of the Japanese finance ministry which
cleared the purchase two weeks later.
   The company carried out the stock transfer and after that, ``It
is not the management's business'' to question the intention or
circumstances of purchase, he said.
   ``We don't have specific plans to change management or accuse
them of anything, other than I have reason to feel offended by the
way they have treated their largest stockholder,'' Pickens
continued. ``We said we were not hostile. We mean it. We said were
longterm. We mean it. We said we want to work with management and
expand markets. We mean it.
   ``I was told you don't understand Japanese customs. ... I said
maybe not customs, but I understand ownership, and we are your
largest owner.''
</TEXT>
