<FIRST>r a AM-HighwayKillings     04-27 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Killings,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Serial Killer's Ninth Victim Identified As Mother of Two Boys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ninth victim of a serial killer apparently
preying on prostitutes and drug users in the seaport of New Bedford
was identified Thursday as a 25-year-old New Bedford woman with two
sons.
   Sandra Botelho was reported missing by her family last August,
and investigators said she probably was killed at that time. Her
body was largely decomposed when highway workers discovered it
Monday in the brush along Interstate 195 in Marion.
   Martin said both the circumstances of Botelho's disappearance
and the location of her body were similar to the other eight
victims. All were women between the ages of 25 and 36 who lived in
the New Bedford area and had ties to that city's Weld Square, a
neighborhood known for prostitution and drug sales.
   Martin said Botelho also ``had a history of drug use,'' but he
declined to comment on whether she was a prostitute.
   Botelho's family, meanwhile, struggled to tell her 4- and
6-year-old sons what happened, said her brother, Phillip Amaral.
   ``We told them that their mother didn't run away,'' he said,
crying. ``We told them basically just somebody took their mother
and he was bad to her and hurt her and now their mother died and
went to heaven.''
   Dr. Stanley Schwartz, a forensic dentist at Tufts University,
used dental records to identify the remains at his Boston
laboratory.
   All the victims found so far disappeared from New Bedford
between April and September of last year. The first body was
discovered last July, and the rest have turned up periodically
since. All have been found along highways within a radius of about
10 miles from the center of New Bedford.
   Botelho was one of three missing women whose families had been
awaiting word on identification of the body.
   Bristol County District Attorney Ronald A. Pina has said he has
several suspects, and a grand jury has been hearing evidence in the
case, but no one has been indicted.
   State police using five search dogs continued combing roadsides
for more bodies Thursday.
</TEXT>
