<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Submarines     04-27 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Submarines,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada May Ask Allies To Help Defend It in Arctic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense minister indicated Thursday Canada may
have to ask the United States to help defend its Arctic areas
because a $6.7 billion plan to develop a nuclear-powered submarine
fleet was left out of this year's budget.
   Asked how Canada could enforce its sovereignty claim over the
Arctic, Defense Minister Bill McKnight said, ``I believe there's an
opportunity through cooperation. We may have to rely more on allies.
   ``There are better was of defending northern sovereignty but
unfortunately we cannot afford those ways,'' McKnight said.
   The United States has a large fleet of nuclear-powered
submarines that have sailed under the polar ice cap, provoking
Canadian protests.
   Only nuclear-powered submarines can patrol the waters under the
polar ice cap. Reactors powering the subs allow them to stay under
water for long periods without having to surface.
   William Rompkey of the opposition Liberal Party said it was
incredible that Canada might have to rely on the United States to
defend Canadian territory.
   ``The whole point of the Conservative policy was to show the
Americans that we are in there defending ourselves. Now they've
done a 180-degree turn and said `leave it to the Americans,''' he
said.
   Since 1987, when the plan to build the submarines was announced,
Conservative ministers insisted the submarines were essential to
assert sovereignty in the Arctic.
   Polls showed that 70 percent of Canadians were opposed to buying
nuclear submarines.
   But McKnight said public opposition had nothing to do with the
decision, which he said was purely economic.
   Peace activists, meanwhile, praised the decision to shelve the
nuclear submarine project.
   ``It proves that organized, sustained public opposition can
indeed make a difference,'' said Ish Theilheimer, head of the peace
group Operation Dismantle, which gathered at its headquarters to
celebrate.
   John Lamb, director of a think tank called the Canadian Center
for Arms Control and Disarmament, congratulated the government for
scrapping the subs but said the decision shouldn't be viewed as a
step toward unilateral disarmament.
   The British and French firms that vied to sell their submarine
designs to Canada issued terse statements expressing disappointment
at the decision.
   Richard Sharpe, editor of the authoritative defense publication
Jane's Fighting Ships, said the decision was ``a disappointment to
(NATO and) all those who believe it is necessary to be able to
contain the Soviet submarine threat.''
   He said Canada's plan to buy either British Trafalgar or French
Amethyste submarines would have been ``a major contribution towards
NATO's anti-submarine warfare capability.''
</TEXT>
