<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     04-27 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Accused of Spying for CIA May Be Freed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Nicaraguans convicted of spying
for the CIA may be pardoned under a presidential decree sent to the
legislature Thursday.
   The decree names Guillermo Quant Tai, Mario Baldizon and
Auxiliadora Rivas Urbina and was sent to the National Assembly's
Committee for Human Rights and Peace, headed by Nicaragua's former
ambassador in Washington, Carlos Tunnerman.
   The committee is to return its finding next Wednesday for debate
and a vote in the single-chamber assembly.
   Approval is virtually assured. The ruling Sandinista National
Liberation Front controls the assembly with 61 deputies to 35
deputies from six opposition parties.
   The move seems aimed at creating a more democratic image for the
leftist government of this Central American country and comes as
President Daniel Ortega tours Europe seeking more money for
economically distressed Nicaragua.
   Some of the 10 European countries on Ortega's itinerary have
said more aid to Nicaragua depends on government efforts toward
democratization.
   Quant, a Nicaraguan citizen of Taiwanese extraction, was vice
president of the Nicaraguan Chamber of Commerce when he was
arrested in September 1986 on charges of spying for the Central
Intelligence Agency.
   He was accused of being recruited in 1983 and then providing
economic information to the CIA. In a news conference at the time
of his arrest, Quant admitted giving information to the CIA, saying
he did it ``out of curiosity.''
   Baldizon, an official of the Interior Ministry, was arrested on
charges of being a CIA spy and of complicity in treason after his
brother, Lt. Alvaro Jose Baldizon, defected on July 1, 1985.
   He was sentenced on July 22, 1985, to 10 years in prison. A
spokeswoman at the Interior Ministry said Thursday he was released
from prison and placed under house arrest last March 17.
   Ms. Rivas, then a government employee, was sentenced to nine
years in prison on Jan. 9, 1985, on charges of belonging to the
U.S.-supported Nicaraguan guerrillas, known as Contras. The
spokeswoman said Ms. Rivas was allowed to leave prison in January
and live with her family under house arrest.
   On the political front, the government and opposition party
leaders have invited members of a private U.S. group, the
Washington-based Center for Democracy, to act as observers during
the Feb. 25, 1990, presidential election.
   Allen Weinstein, president of the non-profit organization, told
journalists in Managua Wednesday his group will decide by this
weekend if it will accept the invitation.
   Next year's election will be held under accords signed by the
five Central American presidents in El Salvador last Feburary.
Ortega moved up the elections by 10 months and promised to
institute democratic reforms here.
   The Bush administration has expressed doubts about Ortega's
democratic reform program.
   The Center for Democracy was formed by U.S. legislators,
business executives and others concerned about democracy worldwide.
It has sent observers in the past to oversee elections in other
nations.
</TEXT>
