<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Pollution     04-27 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Pollution,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Officials Says His Country Moves To Clean Up Its Act</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENE MURDOCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union releases 100 million
tons of waste into the air and water each year, but is working to
clean up its pollution, the leading Soviet environmental official
said Thursday.
   ``Damage to our environment costs the Soviet people at least 50
billion rubles ($80 billion) each year,'' said Dr. Feodor F.
Morgun, chairman of the Soviet Commission on the Environment.
   He refused to say, however, if Moscow was willing to join
Western countries in implementing a global ban on ozone-depleting
chemicals by the year 2000.
   Morgun said his commission was recently established to
consolidate the job of nine previous commissions and seven
ministries, some of which had vested interests in industry.
   Scientists and politicians were debating the question at
meetings in Helsinki, Finland. The head of the U.N. Environment
Program said Wednesday that disagreement with the Soviets could
block agreement to phase out chlorofluorocarbons, which are blamed
for depleting the Earth's ozone layer.
   Morgun was in Stockholm for two days of talks with Swedish
officials. He is to sign a Swedish-Soviet agreement on
environmental issues Friday.
   His visit was timed to the third anniversary of the Chernobyl
nuclear plant explosion, which played havoc with reindeer herds in
northern Scandinavia and sent fallout over much of Europe.
   He said Chernobyl taught the Soviets not to decide major
projects without open discussion.
   ``I would not want any other country to go through what we
did,'' he added.
   In a talk at the Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences,
Morgun reported, ``Our country suffers a great deal from acid rain,
and 100 cities, with more than 50 million inhabitants, are the
worst affected.
   ``Environmental problems are extremely grave in the Ukraine and
other southern parts of the country.
   ``From now on industries which let out more waste than allowed
will have to pay fines, and these will be heavy,'' he said. He
declined to give specifics.
   The Soviet Union recently began cooperating with Finland on how
to curb pollution on the Kola Peninsula, where acid rain from
metals plants have caused acid rain and water pollution.
</TEXT>
