<FIRST>u a AM-WomanAssaulted 3rdLd-Writethru a0774 04-27 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Woman Assaulted, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0774,0868</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Yorkers Try To Make Sense of a Senseless Crime</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-7, `Two other ..., to CLARIFY that male jogger
eluded his attackers and reported the incident, and reflect that the woman
jogger was victimized later that evening.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several came from broken homes and all lived in
a neighborhood surrounded by drugs and crime, but the youths
accused of a savage gang rape of a Central Park jogger were
unlikely attackers, by some accounts.
   ``I deal with kids in trouble. These were not kids in trouble,''
said Bernard Diamond, principal of the junior high school two of
the accused boys attended. ``They come from homes of parents who
care, parents who are as shocked as we are.''
   The victim, a 28-year-old investment banker, remained in a coma
in critical condition Thursday and was on a respirator after
developing pneumonia.
   Eight of her alleged attackers, ages 14 to 17, are in custody.
Two were indicted Wednesday, and on Thursday a grand jury indicted
three more teen-agers who allegedly left her for dead. A fourth
teen-ager was released without bail after a prosecutor told the
judge the grand jury had taken no action in his case.
   When asked afterward by reporters if his client had made a deal
to testify or agreed to a plea bargain, the teen's defense attorney
said no.
   Two other teen-agers were indicted Thursday on charges involving
an earlier attack by the same group on a male jogger, who eluded
his assailants and reported the assault to park police.
   The female victim was jogging alone in the northern end of the
park later on the night of April 19 when she was attacked by a
gang, beaten unconscious with a pipe and heavy rock, raped and left
bound and naked on the ground.
   When she was found four hours later, her body temperature had
fallen to 85 degrees and much of her brain activity had stopped.
   Doctors at Metropolitan Hospital say she may survive, but it's
unlikely she will ever recover completely because of the injuries
to her brain.
   A CAT scan will be done Friday to find out if the woman's brain
swelling has gone down, doctors said Thursday.
   ``By the end of the weekend, we might have a clearer idea of
whether the damage is substantial,'' said Robert S. Kurtz,
assistant chief of surgery at Metropolitan Hospital. He said of
patients injured this badly: ``However `stable' we call them, their
life hangs by a thread.''
   Police said only one of the suspects _ 17-year-old Michael
Brisco _ had a police record. But friends said he was a frequent
churchgoer who played drums for the choir.
   Tim Burns, a 15-year-old schoolmate of suspect Anton McCrary,
15, said: ``He's a good kid, he just followed the wrong crowd. If
you're in the wrong crowd, this could happen to anybody. You have
to make your own decisions, that's all.''
   Lisa Whitten of the national board of the Association of Black
Psychologists said the violence of city life allowed the boys to
bury normal emotions in the frenzy of their attack.
   ``They're human beings who went berserk,'' she said. ``They had
fantasies in their minds _ of being like those on television, the
ones who shoot people, who are powerful, in control, macho,
aggressive, strong.''
   The suspects were being held on charges of attempted murder,
rape and assault and could face other charges.
   The woman apparently was one of several targets of the gang
going ``wilding'' that night.
   The term was new to police but not the activity: For years,
loosely organized packs of marauding youths have roamed the streets
and parks bullying, robbing and attacking victims at random.
   The assailants reportedly used racial epithets in one of eight
assaults during the rampage and discussed ``getting whitey'' or
``getting a white jogger.'' The victim is white and the accused
attackers are black.
   However, law-enforcement experts say victims of the so-called
``wolf packs'' are more often black than white.
   After their arrests, Brisco and Kharey Wise, 16, were roughed up
in an attack by several other inmates and Yusef Salaam, 15, was
attacked by another youth at the Spofford Juvenile Center.
   Questions about the assault reached Washington when a group of
freshmen Republican congressmen said Thursday the incident pointed
up the need for a tougher juvenile justice system.
   ``What we're saying is, If you're going to do big-boy crime,
you're going to do big-boy time,'' said Rep. Chuck Douglas, R-N.H.,
a former state Supreme Court justice. He and fellow members of the
Republican Research Committee Task Force on Crime said that from
age 14 on, youths who commit violent crimes such as rape, armed
robbery, murder or attempted murder should be punished as adults.
   Central Park has a reputation _ largely undeserved, police and
city officials say _ of being a dangerous place.
   ``If this had happened in the streets, it wouldn't be anything
like this,'' said Eva Haws, who takes tourists on carriage rides
through the park.
</TEXT>
