<FIRST>r a AM-TankerSpill-NTSB     04-27 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill-NTSB,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>NTSB Says Spill Fact-Finding Sessions Will Cover Alcohol Abuse</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hearings into the wreck of the Exxon
Valdez next month will examine alcohol abuse, timeliness of
emergency responses and Coast Guard staffing, the National
Transportation Safety Board said Thursday.
   The agency is to hold fact-finding sessions May 16-19 to
determine how the tanker ran aground May 24, spilling more than 10
million gallons of oil, and how to prevent a recurrence, said NTSB
spokesman Alan Pollock.
   Twenty witnesses are expected, although Capt. Joseph Hazelwood,
skipper of the Exxon Valdez, probably won't be one of them, Pollock
said. Hazelwood faces three misdemanor charges, including operating
the tanker while under the influence of alcohol.
   ``The hearing will be the same as the ones that come after a
plane crash,'' Pollock said. ``Our purpose is not to assess blame,
but to have an open hearing and gather facts.''
   Other issues to be explored include fatigue, human factors,
adequacy of the U.S. Coast Guard's drug and alcohol regulations and
the role of the Coast Guard's ``vessel traffic service,'' which
guides vessels through shipping channels in Prince William Sound.
   Also to be examined are the history of the channel where the
wreck occurred, Exxon's and the Coast Guard's policies for
emergency spill responses and reactions from officers on the bridge
of the tanker after the ship ran aground.
   Details of the spill cleanup will be covered by the
Environmental Protection Agency and won't be a part of the hearing,
Pollock said. NTSB member Lee Dickinson will lead the hearing and
be assisted by the agency staff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
