<DOCNO> AP890427-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0752EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w PM-100Days-BushCabinet Adv28   04-27 1126</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-100 Days-Bush Cabinet, Adv 28,1147</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Fri April 28 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Outsider In Bush Cabinet Most Visible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush brought to the White House a
Cabinet steeped in Washington experience, but it is one of his
outsiders, Samuel S. Skinner, who has taken the most visible role
100 days into his administration.
   The transportation secretary has taken charge in major aviation
and automobile issues. But he's also emerged as the
administration's point man in areas that stray into the territory
of others in the Bush Cabinet: the Alaska oil spill, the Eastern
Airlines strike, and fighting drugs and terrorism, to name a few.
   ``He's shown good instincts,'' said Norman Ornstein, scholar at
the American Enterprise Institute, a conservative think tank. But
Ornstein questions how much ``staying power'' the former federal
prosecutor and head of the Chicago mass transit system will have.
   Bush also came into office with a pledge to hit the ground
running, yet many of his department secretaries have moved slowly
in their new jobs.
   ``All of them are somewhat limited by the defining
characteristic of 1989 _ there ain't no money,'' said Stephen Hess,
senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, a liberal think tank.
   That financial reality of big deficits limits the initiatives
available to any of the administration's domestic Cabinet
secretaries.
   But even Bush's senior-most Cabinet member, Secretary of State
James Baker III, whose appointment was announced the day after
Bush's election, has moved slowly in building a team and taking
foreign-policy initatives.
   Many of the departments are still without confirmed appointees
in top-level jobs, with 49 nominations pending before the Senate
and more still to be made. Some of the independent agencies are
hampered too: the Federal Trade Commission has no chairman, and the
Consumer Product Safety Commission doesn't have enough members for
a quorum.
   Here is a brief look at the Cabinet:
   _State. Baker is an old Bush friend who ran his presidential
campaign and is a veteran of the Reagan administration. He has
concentrated on improving NATO ties but also started negotiations
in the Middle East and worked out a deal with Democrats in Congress
to permit non-lethal aid to the Nicaraguan Contras, at least until
the fall.
   So tightly have Baker and his closest aides held control that
experienced diplomats have grumbled that they were being ignored.
   _Defense. Dick Cheney has taken charge forcefully at the
Pentagon and helped the administration put behind the debacle of
John Tower's defeated nomination. In a month on the job, he has
faced a budget agreement requring him to find $10 billion worth of
cuts in next year's budget. He has moved to cut spending for the
``Star Wars'' nuclear defense, ship building, troop strength, and
the new stealth bomber, and he has put together a combined MX and
Midgetman missile program.
   _Transportation. When the Machinists Union walked out on
Eastern, Bush named Skinner to speak for the administration. He
rejected union appeals for the government to step in, and while the
strike drags on, it has brought no major disruption in air traffic.
   Bush also had Skinner, whose department includes the Coast
Guard, oversee the cleanup of oil spilled by the tanker Exxon
Valdez in Alaska's Prince William Sound. Skinner also has pushed
for tougher auto mileage standards.
   _Labor. Elizabeth Dole slipped into the background in the
Eastern strike, although it was threatening to spread and she had
the double qualification of being a former transportation
secretary. Still, she has led administration efforts in Congress to
limit a minimum wage increase and for its tax-credit child care
proposal.
   _Health and Human Services. Louis Sullivan has kept a low
profile after a bruising confirmation, when he was attacked by
abortion foes for remarks supporting a women's right to an
abortion. Sullivan apologized and said he had misspoken. Since
then, the White House has nominated assistants that are known for
anti-abortion views.
   _Justice. Dick Thornburgh, a Reagan holdover, is a moderate
former governor who has moved rightward as attorney general,
becoming the administration's advocate for drug testing and
overturning the Supreme Court's ruling that permits abortion.
   _Treasury. Nicholas Brady, another of the Reagan holdovers, has
won plaudits for tackling two of the toughest economic issues, how
to rescue the savings and loan industry and what to do about the
Third World debt crisis. But he's come in for criticism, in part
because of public miscues as the administration's chief economic
spokesman, giving what seemed to be indifferent responses regarding
problems of the deficit and inflation.
   _Commerce. Robert Mosbacher, a Texas oil millionaire and Bush
friend, fought to protect U.S. technology in the FSX fighter deal.
But he has not yet been elevated to the front-ranks of economic
decision-making.
   _Housing and Urban Development. Jack Kemp has drawn praise from
all sides for bringing attention to homelessness and other urban
ills, and has attacked drugs in public housing by moving to ease
evictions. He also won administration backing for tax credits for
urban enterprise zones. But urban advocates are waiting to see
money to go with his ``conservative war on poverty.'' The question
for Kemp is: Can he meet the expectations he has raised?
   _Interior. Manuel Lujan was frozen out of initial decisions on
the oil spill, while Skinner and EPA chief William Reilly
dominated. He's made public misstatements and been criticized as
uninformed by environmentalists.
   _Education. Lauro Cavazos has been more conciliatory and less
visible than his controversial predecessor, William Bennett. But he
has offered only a modest package of education initatives,
proposing spending that does not even keep up with inflation,
despite Bush's campaign pledge to be ``the education president.''
   At the other posts, James D. Watkins has yet to take a major
initiative at Energy, and Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter has
attacked foreign agriculture subsidies but also has been late in
hiring his team. At Veterans Affairs, the newest department, Ed
Derwinski has been praised by veterans' advocates for openness and
for winning approval from the White House to ask Congress for a
small supplemental appropriation this year.
   Office of Management and Budget Director Richard Darman has
Cabinet-level status, as does Trade Representative Carla Hills. She
has talked tough on the trade deficit but taken few real steps,
while Darman was chief architect of the White House budget
agreement with Congress. While it has been ridiculed as only
papering over the problem, it has allowed Bush to keep his
no-tax-increase pledge.
   Drug policy chief Bennett, while pointedly not given Cabinet
status, has drawn attention as if he had it, raising gun control as
an issue and winning at least a temporary ban on the importation of
semiautomatic weapons.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for PMs Fri April 28 and thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
