<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     04-27 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0837</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reported the U.S. economy
topped the $5 trillion mark for the first time last quarter,
powered by a strong 5.5 percent growth rate that caused some
analysts to express concern about rising inflation.
   Even discounting for a statistical bounceback from the 1988
drought, a major factor in the overall increase, the gross national
product grew at a solid 3 percent annual rate during the
January-March period, the Commerce Department reported Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Banking Committee members prayed for
God's help to rise above narrow self-interest and then began
exempting individual institutions from reform provisions in
President Bush's savings and loan reform plan.
   The panel started Wednesday what is expected to be at least two
days of work on the S&amp;L bill by exempting an institution in the
district of its chairman from provisions that would make each bank
or S&amp;L in a holding company liable when another commonly controlled
institution fails.
   The amendment, passed by 37-11 vote, is designed to help only
the Frost National Bank of San Antonio, Texas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines announced orders for as many as
370 Boeing aircraft valued at $15.74 billion, a gigantic deal
designed to ``make United the leading airline in our industry,''
said United Chairman Stephen Wolf.
   The package includes firm orders for 180 Boeing jetliners and
options on 190 others, Wolf said Wednesday.
   He said the order was the largest to a single manufacturer in
commercial aviation history. It comes just one week after Ireland's
GPA Group Ltd., an aircraft leasing firm, ordered $17 billion in
jets from Boeing Co., McDonnell Douglas Corp. and Europe's Airbus
Industrie.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another bid to finalize Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc.'s landmark settlement of civil securities fraud charges was
thwarted by a federal appeals court.
   But a Securities and Exchange Commission lawyer said Wednesday's
appeals court ruling doesn't foreclose all options for seeking
lower court approval of its deal with Drexel.
   Separately, a federal judge refused to let convicted stock
speculator Ivan F. Boesky out of prison, saying the 3-year sentence
he got in Wall Street's biggest insider trading scandal ``is not
unjust.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turner Broadcasting System Inc. made the
surprise announcement that it will offer a commercial-free news
program for schools to compete with the ad-supported service by
Whittle Communications LP.
   In a statement welcomed by educators, Turner Chairman Ted Turner
said Wednesday his Cable News Network would begin providing the
daily 15-minute news show, called CNN Newsroom, on Aug. 14.
   Turner originally had planned a school news show with ads,
similar to a test program pioneered by Whittle that has aroused
widespread criticism by educators for injecting commercials into
classrooms.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor looking for a place to put $1,000
in 1984 might not have thought of the Manila stock market, but if
he had taken the plunge he would have found the average return on
his investment at the end of last year to be $14,880, a study said.
   On U.S. markets, the average return for the four years _ the
value of the stocks themselves plus dividends _ would have been a
tame $1,910.
   The study released Wednesday by the International Finance Corp.
looked at stock markets in both major money centers and 31 Third
World countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Xerox Corp. chose National Secretary's Day to
unveil what it calls the world's quietest ribbon typewriter, a
machine nearly as quiet as a computer keyboard.
   The typewriters introduced Wednesday use a patented technology
that gives the printer heads the vibrational characteristics of a
hammer weighing nearly 35 pounds, Xerox said. That makes them
vibrate at a pitch nearly six octaves lower than usual, almost
inaudible to the human ear.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blimpie is going skimpy on calories.
   The fast-food restaurant known for submarines heaped with meats
and mayo said Wednesday it is expanding the menu to include
low-calorie sandwiches and salads in an attempt to woo
calorie-conscious consumers who might otherwise be avoiding fast
food.
   Experts said past attempts at healthier fast food have produced
mixed results, even though most chains now offer salads or other
``light'' items.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market struggled to record a small gain Wednesday in a
tepid response to the latest data on the state of the economy. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 2.20 points to
2,389.11.
   The dollar pushed higher against all major currencies. Gold
prices declined.
   Bond prices were narrowly lower but avoided a sharp drop.
   Platinum futures prices surged; gasoline futures rose sharply
while crude oil and heating oil prices fell; pork prices rallied
but cattle were little changed; grain and soybeans were mixed and
cocoa prices plunged.
</TEXT>
