<DOCNO> AP890427-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SteelImports Bjt   04-27 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Imports, Bjt,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steel Import Debate Splits U.S. Manufacturers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Business Mirror, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's steel-using manufacturers are split
over whether steel import quotas should be extended by the Bush
administration when they expire in the fall.
   A coalition of manufacturers opposed to the quotas got some
competition Wednesday when a rival group led by Chrysler, Maytag
and others was announced to lobby on behalf of the import curbs.
   The new group claimed to have enlisted 374 members, including
makers of automobiles, home appliances, marine products, beverage
cans, tableware and farm equipment.
   The only thing the two coalitions have in common is that all
their members use steel as a raw material.
   The Coalition for a Competitive America was unveiled at a
Capitol press conference Wednesday by Sen. Jay Rockefeller,
D-W.Va., and executives from Chrysler Corp. of Detroit, Crown Cork
and Seal Co. of Philadelphia, Milton Can Co. of Elizabeth, N.J.,
UNR-Leavitt of Chicago, Maytag Corp. of Newton, Iowa, and others.
   Organizers said the coalition was created to help make the case
for continuing steel import quotas due to expire Sept. 30.
   ``Domestic steel producers have proven they can compete with any
steel producer in the world,'' said Rockefeller, chairman of the
Senate Steel Caucus. ``But they cannot compete with foreign
governments that pump billions of dollars in subsidies into their
state-owned steel operations.''
   The Reagan administration negotiated five-year,
product-by-product ``voluntary restraint agreements'' in 1984 with
Japan, South Korea, Brazil, South Africa, the European Community
and other nations to limit the flow of foreign steel into the
United States.
   Three days before last November's election, President Bush
pledged to continue the restraints in some form. But with the U.S.
steel industry newly profitable, opponents of the curbs believe
they can make a case for ending the program, or at least narrowing
its scope.
   The quota opponents have been led in part by Caterpillar Inc. of
Peoria, Ill. Caterpillar is part of the Coalition of American Steel
Using Manufacturers, a 300-member group that claims quotas have
driven up steel prices and caused product shortages.
   Members of the new coalition said they formed the group to show
that steel-consuming manufacturers are not widely opposed to trade
protection, as the older group suggests.
   Chrysler spokesman Richard Muller, UNR-Leavitt President Roy A.
Herman, Maytag government affairs counsel Douglass Horstman and
Crown Cork and Seal Vice President-Purchasing Ronald Thoma released
statements chronicling how the quotas had helped turn the ailing
steel industry around.
   Bipartisan legislation has been introduced in the Senate and
House that would enable the Bush administration to begin
negotiating new quota agreements with America's steel-trading
partners.
   But Samuel Berger, counsel for the older Coalition of American
Steel Using Manufacturers, said in a telephone interview that the
new group was already on the defensive.
   ``I think they are concerned that the debate here has been
expanded beyond simply what's good for the steel industry. We've
succeeded in getting people to understand that the debate is over
what's good for the overall economy,'' Berger said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890427-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Bird's-EyeCrazy Bjt   04-27 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bird's-Eye Crazy, Bjt,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wood Fad Makes Maple Defect A Hot Seller</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Dooge in penultimate graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North American colonials viewed
bird's-eye maple as one of nature's defects, but today lumbermen
can't cut the trees fast enough.
   The specks and whirling disfigurations of bird's-eye have become
the fad of the wood world, foresters say.
   ``It's a very hot wood now. It's hard to say why,'' said Steve
Stanton, import veneers specialist for David R. Webb Co. Inc. in
Edinburgh, Ind. ``It will continue to be until some gentleman
decides the trendy wood is something else.''
   Foreign buyers are snapping up so much of the rare North
American wood that U.S. producers have had to turn away domestic
customers. The wood has become even harder to find in the last six
months, with Japan entering the market of would-be buyers.
   ``I think our shortage of bird's-eye is because we've shipped it
out. We can't satisfy the guitar makers, the clock manufacturers in
our own country,'' said Bob Owens of Owens Forest Products in
Duluth, Minn.
   Importers from Germany, Japan and Taiwan make up the bulk of the
foreign trade, Owens and Stanton said Wednesday. In Italy,
importers are dying the blond wood into all colors of the rainbow,
from pink to green.
   The supply of birdy maple _ as foresters call it _ is scarce,
limited to a narrow band through New England and the Great Lakes.
By most estimates, Michigan's Upper Peninsula produces the bulk of
the specialty wood.
   There, bird's-eye is selling for as high as $12.50 per board
foot, said Upper Peninsula forester Gary Willis.
   A conservation group trying to buy a 300-year-old virgin stand
of pines along the Upper Peninsula's northernmost shore gulped when
the timber company-owner named its price.
   The quote was steep, Willis said, not because the pines are ripe
for cutting, but because of the chance that bird's-eye maples are
among the scattered maples in the stand.
   ``They're drooling over the bird's-eye,'' Willis said.
   The price for long sections of bird's-eye veneer runs up to
$2.50 a square foot for a 10-foot panel. For comparison, walnut
veneer runs up to 50 cents a square foot, Stanton said.
   But 25 years ago, Boynton Glidden, president of GMC Hardwoods in
Dover, Mass., tossed his bird's-eye logs aside for pallet lumber.
``No one wanted bird's-eye at any price,'' Glidden said.
   ``Now, the yuppies, the wealthy, they think it's pretty. If
anyone has any, it's pretty easy to sell. And the price is going up
and up,'' he said.
   Some companies still throw bird's-eye out with their less
valuable boards. One of the most common places to find its dotted
planks is among the second-grade maple in gymnasium floors.
   Meanwhile, scientists remain unable to explain why it looks the
way it does.
   ``What causes bird's-eye? Don't ask me,'' said Dr. Henry Huber,
a forestry professor at Michigan State University. ``There are a
lot of theories _ maybe they are buds that didn't mature _ but none
of them has proven out. What can I say? Some trees have it, some
don't.''
   Bird's-eye maple is hard to cut and the delicate little eyes
tend to pop out during planing, wood products manufacturers said.
And not every log that looks like bird's-eye turns out to be
``birdy.''
   ``They're cruddy little nasty logs. You buy 20 logs and maybe
five of them have bird's eyes,'' said Sue Roberts of Dooge Veneers
in Grand Rapids, Mich. Yet Dooge Veneers sells every bird's-eye
maple log it can get.
   ``Nobody else has it,'' she said.
</TEXT>
