<DOCNO> AP890427-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Boesky Bjt   04-27 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boesky, Bjt,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Grant Boesky Early Release From Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge says convicted stock speculator
Ivan F. Boesky has already gotten a lot of breaks and doesn't
deserve to get out of prison early.
   U.S. District Judge Morris E. Lasker rejected a request by
Boesky, who has already served one year of a three-year prison
term, to cut his sentence to time served, paving the way for his
immediate release.
   ``I cannot in good conscience conclude that, commendable as
Boesky's behavior has been since he was sentenced, he should be
given further credit,'' Lasker ruled Wednesday.
   There was no answer at the offices of Boesky lawyers in New York
and Washington when called for comment Wednesday evening.
   Once one of the leading speculators on the stock of potential
takeover targets, Boesky pleaded guilty to one felony count as part
of a plea bargain. Boesky, 52, also agreed to pay a then-record
$100 million in 1986 to settle civil insider trading charges
brought by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   He has since supplied information used toward civil or criminal
charges in more than a dozen cases here and in Britain. In
exchange, he was allowed to plead guilty to one count of conspiracy
to lie to the SEC.
   The maximum penalty he faced was five years in prison, and
Lasker, who has a reputation as a lenient sentencer, handed Boesky
a three-year term.
   Lasker noted that even without any actions by him or the parole
board, ``Boesky will be released from custody less than a year from
today, which is to say, that the actual period he will have served
will be slightly more than two years. Such a sentence is not unjust
in the circumstances.''
   Boesky's earliest non-parole release date based on good behavior
is April 4, 1990.
   Boesky claimed that his help led to a record plea bargain deal
by Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and the subsequent indictment of its
junk bond chief, Michael Milken, and others on racketeering and
securities fraud charges.
   Lasker said he took Boesky's ``unprecedented'' cooperation into
account when he passed sentence.
   Federal prosecutors took no stand on releasing Boesky early but
they noted in a letter to Lasker, who sentenced Boesky Dec. 18,
1987, that the Milken indictment and the $650 million tentative
settlement of criminal charges Drexel reached with the government
was ``the centerpiece of Boesky's cooperation.''
   The letter continued: ``Boesky's disclosures were the essential
catalyst for all that has been and remains to be revealed in those
cases. Other investigations arising directly from Boesky's
disclosures have also matured since Boesky's sentencing.''
   But it added that ``the government nevertheless articulated the
value of that cooperation in unqualified terms when Boesky was
sentenced.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890427-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Judge     04-27 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Judge,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bid To Finalize Drexel-SEC Deal Again Delayed By Appeals Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is
planning another try at finalizing its settlement of civil
securities fraud charges against Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   A federal appeals court ruled Wednesday that it did not have the
authority to switch judges on the case.
   But an SEC lawyer said the ruling left open an option for
seeking lower court approval of its deal with Drexel.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals previously barred Judge
Milton Pollack, who is assigned to the case, from conducting
hearings on the proposed settlement because his impartiality is
being challenged before the U.S. Supreme Court by former Drexel
junk bond chief Michael Milken, who is not part of the settlement.
   Until the high court decides whether to consider Milken's
appeal, Pollack cannot take any action in the Drexel case.
   The SEC and Drexel tried to bypass the delay, which could take
months, by asking the 2nd Circuit to modify its stay and allow
another judge to consider and possibly approve the settlement.
   The appeals court, however, said ``that decision does not rest
with us,'' adding that the final word on assigning the case to
another judge ``rests with Judge Pollack or with those responsible
for the assignment of cases'' at the district court level in New
York.
   In Washington, SEC Solicitor Paul Gonson said the commission
would not ask Pollack to step aside. ``Rather, we're going to be
asking the proper authorities to assign that part of the case to a
second judge for the sole purpose of considering the settlement,''
said Gonson, who oversees appeals for the SEC.
   Gonson would not comment on what action the SEC planned to take,
but a three-judge district court panel, the committee on
assignments, normally would consider requests for reassignments of
cases.
   Chief Judge Charles L. Brieant Jr., who chairs the committee,
said that if the SEC requested an assignment change, the panel
would consult with Pollack before making a decision.
   The appeals court's refusal to assign a different judge
continues to delay the landmark civil settlement as well as
Drexel's record plea bargain to criminal charges.
   Resolution of the SEC pact also is needed before Drexel can
formally plead guilty to six felonies and pay $650 million to
settle criminal charges brought by the Manhattan U.S. attorneys
office.
   A Drexel spokesman, Steven Anreder said: ``We're going to be
consulting with our counsel to see what options we have. We believe
the settlement should be implemented because it's in the best
interest of everybody.''
   Drexel originally battled to get Pollack to excuse himself from
the case for an alleged conflict of interest because his wife
stands to make a hefty profit from a debt-financed acquisition
Drexel helped finance.
   Pollack refused to step down from the case and the 2nd Circuit,
which delayed further district court proceedings pending its
decision, upheld Pollack in November.
   Drexel eventually dropped its objections to Pollack but the
delay was extended when Milken and his brother Lowell, who were
both indicted for racketeering and securities law violations last
month, sought to argue the issue before the Sumpreme Court.
   The 2nd Circuit has delayed all proceedings before Pollack
pending a decision by the Supreme Court, which has not yet decided
whether it will hear the appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
