<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest     04-27 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snags Don't Prevent Davis From Bringing His Case To Shareholders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marvin Davis launched his proxy fight to
unseat the board of directors at Northwest Airlines' parent company
despite a conflict with the state commerce commissioner, who is
threatening to block Davis' tender offer in Minnesota.
   Davis had until 2 p.m. today to supply ``objective facts'' to
Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch describing how he will operate
the nation's fourth-largest airline if his $2.7 billion tender
offer is successful.
   Hatch said Wednesday he will suspend the tender offer in
Minnesota if the deadline is not met, blocking the estimated 1,900
shareholders in the state from selling their 1.3 million shares to
Davis.
   There was no immediate reaction from Davis. Hatch gave Davis the
option of asking for another hearing on the issue, which would be
held tonight.
   Meanwhile, the Los Angeles-based billionaire proceeded with his
proxy fight Wednesday by mailing letters to those who hold the 29.1
million shares of NWA Inc., the airline's parent.
   Davis is lobbying for votes in the election of 11 board members
at NWA's May 15 annual meeting. The Davis nominees would review
``all bona fide offers'' to buy the airline company, including
Davis' offer, he wrote.
   ``By voting for our slate, you can mandate the sale of the
company,'' Davis said in his letter.
   NWA's board has rejected Davis' $90-a-share offer but has
pledged to explore alternatives that would maximize shareholder
value. Davis, who owns about 2.8 percent of NWA's shares, said in
his letter that he is skeptical of the claim.
   He cited the company's refusal to withdraw its ``poison pill''
takeover defense plan and a requirement that Northwest suitors sign
a restrictive confidentiality agreement.
   Kurt Rivard, an analyst for Minneapolis-based Dain Bosworth
Inc., said the odds are against Davis winning the proxy fight.
   ``To oust an existing management is an uphill battle,'' Rivard
said.
   Davis would be helped if nine dissident shareholders succeed in
their attempt to force NWA to change proxy documents that limit the
voting to those who held the stock as of March 17.
   Hennepin County District Judge Delila Pierce said Wednesday that
the request deserves a hearing next week.
   Karl Cambronne, an attorney for the shareholders, said because
more than 65 percent of NWA stock has changed hands since March 17.
Rivard said new owners would be more likely to vote for Davis'
slate of nominees because they bought the stock on takeover rumors.
   Working against Davis in his proxy fight is a provision in NWA's
``poison pill'' that would prevent Davis' proposed board from
selling the company for about six months. Davis sought to
invalidate the provision in a lawsuit he filed in the Court of
Chancery in Wilmington, Del. A judge on Tuesday denied his request.
NWA is incorporated in Delaware.
   Hatch said Davis must explain how he would operate the airline
in light of the large sum he proposes to borrow to buy it.
   ``Davis should objectively state whether (he) intends to demand
wage and salary, including productivity, concessions from NWA
employees,'' Hatch said. Davis has said he does not intend to sell
the airline's strategic assets, reduce payroll or move the
headquarters from suburban Eagan, but his lawyers have indicated he
may refinance or sell NWA's Tokyo real estate, reduce travel agent
commissions or change Northwest's in-flight service.
   NWA shares closed at $100 Wednesday, down 25 cents, on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
