<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-McClatchyNewspapers     04-27 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-McClatchy Newspapers,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Potts Named Chief Executive Officer of McClatchy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Erwin Potts, president of McClatchy
Newspapers, has been named chief executive officer by the company's
board of directors.
   The board also announced Wednesday that James B. McClatchy,
publisher of the newspaper group since 1987, was named chairman of
the board.
   The two posts had been held by C.K. McClatchy until his death
April 16 at age 62.
   C.K. McClatchy was also editor of McClatchy Newspapers, a post
which ``has not been dealt with as of this time,'' board counsel
Gary Pruitt said after the meeting.
   James McClatchy, 68, older brother of C.K. McClatchy, has served
as a director of McClatchy Newspapers since 1976 and previously
served as board chairman from 1980 until his appointment as
publisher in 1987.
   Potts, 57, joined McClatchy Newspapers in 1975 following 17
years with what was then the Knight Newspapers group. Potts has
been a member of the McClatchy board since 1976 and was named
president and chief operating officer in 1987.
   McClatchy Newspapers publish The Sacramento Bee and 11 other
newspapers in California, Washington state and Alaska.
