<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Reuters     04-27 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Reuters,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reuters Says Holders Approved Share Conversion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reuters Holdings PLC said its shareholders have
approved plans to simplify the news and communications company's
share structure by converting its closely held ``A'' shares into
its publicly-traded ``B'' shares.
   The changes, approved Wednesday, will create a single class of
Reuters ordinary shares with equal voting rights. The ``A'' shares
account for 23 percent of outstanding equity but represent 54
percent of the voting rights.
   Reuters hopes the changed share structure will increase the
marketability of its stock and facilitate new share issues. In
addition, analysts said the new structure should improve Reuters'
chances of gaining a listing on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   Reuters trustees will retain the so-called Founders Share, which
can be used to block a hostile takeover of the company.
   Reuters ``B'' shares were trading 29 cents higher at $12.39 late
Wednesday on London's Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
