<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-27 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was slightly lower this morning in
nervous European trading but failed to fall below a key resistance
level against the West German mark. Gold prices were higher.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar fell initially after
comments by Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita that central
banks were ready to intervene and unconfirmed reports of modest
dollar sales by the West German Deutsche Bundesbank.
   But the dollar remained confined to a fairly narrow trading
range because of its failure to break the key resistance level of
1.8800 marks.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6935, more expensive for
buyers than Wednesday's late $1.6932.
   Other mid-morning rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with
Tuesday's late rates, included: 1.8727 West German marks, down from
1.8770; 1.6547 Swiss francs, down from 1.6555; 6.3385 French
francs, down from 6.3395; 2.1087 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1150;
1,372.50 Italian lire, down from 1,374.00; 1.1955 Canadian dollars,
up from 1.1900.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar rose to 132.05 Japanese yen from
131.47 yen Wednesday. In London, the dollar traded higher at 132.25
yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $384.60, higher than
$384.25 late Wednesday. At mid-morning, bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $384.75.
   Zurich gold was trading at $384.70, up from a bid price of
$383.50 late Wednesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at $385.71, up from $385.59.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid $5.77 a troy ounce this
morning, unchanged from late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
