<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0743EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     04-27 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Against Yen, Stocks Hit Another High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose today against the Japanese
yen, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index finished at yet
another high.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 190.15 points
to a record 33,434.93 close Wednesday, added another 65.90 points,
or 0.20 percent, closing at 33,500.83.
   The index has been climbing since Tuesday, when Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita announced he would resign soon over a
stock-profiteering and bribery scandal.
   ``Alhough it (Takeshita's resignation announcement) was not good
news, it reassured investors, who thought they finally had got rid
of one negative element,'' said an analyst with Nomura Securities,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   But institutional investors remained on the sidelines, mainly
due to remaining uncertainties over politics and over interest
rates, the analyst said.
   Many market players speculate that the Bank of Japan may raise
interest rates soon to slow economic growth and combat inflation.
   Trying to anticipate ways the central bank might move, investors
are closely watching consumer price index figures due to be
announced Friday.
   Steel shares attracted investors in active trading, with first
section volume estimated at 1.2 billion shares Thursday.
   The dollar closed at 132.05 yen, up 0.58 yen from Wednesday's
131.47-yen close. After opening at 131.90 yen, the currency moved
from 131.70 yen to 132.25 yen.
   Traders said the dollar opened higher in Tokyo following its
strength in New York, where the announcement of robust U.S. gross
national product figure for January-March boosted dollar-buying.
   ``The market's demand for the dollar is still strong,'' said
Minori Takeuchi with Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   Meanwhile, Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita told a regular
news conference today he does not expect a rapid rise or wide
fluctuation of the dollar on overseas markets next week _ a series
of Japanese national holidays known as ``Golden Week.''
</TEXT>
