<DOCNO> AP890427-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 0848EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-IntelCuts     04-27 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Intel Cuts,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Intel To Cut 600 Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intel Corp. plans to eliminate 600
jobs nationwide, a cut that amounts to about 3 percent of the
semiconductor maker's workforce of 21,700.
   The company said on Wednesday it made the decision involving
five U.S facilities in order to reduce costs and remain competitive.
   ``We operate in an aggressive, unforgiving marketplace,'' said
Andy Grove, Intel's chief executive. ``While our financial position
is solid and demand for our products is strong, our objective is to
make sure we stay in good shape as we enter the '90s.''
   Apart from Silicon Valley, the job cuts affect Intel plants in
Rio Rancho, N.M., Chandler, Ariz., and Hillsboro, Ore. About 100
positions will be eliminated at the Santa Clara headquarters and a
manufacturing plant in Livermore.
   The Oregon plant will feel the least impact, said the company,
adding it will try to move employees into other job openings and
predicting that only a small number will be laid off.
   Intel also announced that the Chandler plant, which makes
older-technology logic chips and microcontrollers, has excess
production capacity. It will begin a five-day rather than six-day
work week.
   Intel two weeks ago reported first-quarter profits of $97
million _ a 3.5 percent jump over the year-earlier period.
   The company is the sole supplier of microprocessors for all
high-end personal computers that use IBM-compatible software.
</TEXT>
