<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today amid
increasing hopes for evidence of reduced inflationary pressures.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.68 to 2,394.79 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 4 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 511 up, 411 down and
524 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 24.83 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts expect a fresh sign of slowing economic growth when the
government reports Friday on the index of leading economic
indicators for March.
   The index, which is designed to detect future economic trends,
is expected to show a decline of about 0.6 percent, after falling
0.3 percent in February.
   That would provide some additional encouragement for the Federal
Reserve not to tighten credit in the immediate future.
   Wall Streeters generally agree that the Fed has lately been
following a neutral credit policy, watching to see the effects of a
year-long bout of credit-tightening intended to keep inflation in
check.
   Boeing, which received a big order for planes from United
Airlines on Wednesday, rose ~ to 74~ in active trading.
   Other gainers among the blue chips included Exxon, up [ at 43\;
General Electric, up [ at 48[, and Union Carbide, up ] at 31\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.24 to 171.99. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .27 at 343.14.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average edged up 2.20 to
2,389.11.
   Advancing issues just nosed out declines on the NYSE, with 719
up, 686 down and 537 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 146.09 million shares, against 165.43
million in the previous session.
