<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   04-27 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were mixed in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Trading was quiet at the opening bell following the National
Weather Service's six-to-10 day forecast, which called for no
additional rain in wheat growing states.
   Traders also were awaiting word on whether the United States
will subsidize additional grain sales to the Soviet Union.
   ``Egypt finally ended up buying red wheat and that gave some
reassurance that the export bonus program is still working,'' said
Jerry Gidel, an analyst with LIT America Inc., in Chicago.
   In the soybean pit, there were expectations that a dockworker's
strike in Brazil would boost demand for U.S. soybeans.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to { cent higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $4.11{ a bushel; corn was }
cent to 2{ cents higher with May at $2.68\ a bushel; oats were 1\
cents to 2\ cents lower with May at $1.81 a bushel; soybeans were 2
cents lower to 1\ cents higher with May at $7.40 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercan tile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent lower to .13 cent higher with June at
70.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with May at 75.70 cents a pound; hogs were .22 cent lower to
.05 cent higher with June at 46.62 ce nts a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .30 cent to .47 cent lower with May at 32.25 cents a
pound.
   Cattle settled mixed, but pork futures settled higher on
Wednesday.
