<FIRST>u f PM-United-JetOrder 1stLd-Writethru   04-27 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-United-Jet Order, 1st Ld-Writethru,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>United's $16 Billion Jet Order Partly Prompted By Safety Concerns</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS new 10th graf to UPDATE with KLM order for Boeing planes;
picks up 10th graf pvs bg'ng, United is ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines' $15.7 billion order for as many
as 370 Boeing aircraft was prompted in part by public perceptions
that new jets are safer than old ones, Chairman Stephen Wolf said.
   Wolf said Wednesday's order, the largest ever to a single
aircraft manufacturer, primarily reflects United's commitment to
expand its fleet and regain the title of America's largest airline.
   But United also will replace some of its aging planes, he said.
The Chicago-based airline has one of the oldest fleets in the
industry, with an average age of 13.5 years.
   Although Wolf said airplanes will fly ``forever'' if maintained
properly, the decision to replace some United jets was ``motivated
by two things: the cost of maintaining older aircraft and public
perception of older aircraft.''
   ``Some things have happened of late to focus the consumer and
focus Congress on the issue of aging aircraft,'' Wolf said. ``But
in terms of that being a prod, this is a business decision we were
flowing toward anyway.''
   Among the recent incidents focusing attention on aging aircraft
was a Feb. 24 accident in Hawaii involving a United Boeing 747. The
forward cargo door and part of the fuselage tore off shortly after
the plane left Honolulu, killing nine passengers.
   The National Transportation Safety Board finished a second day
of hearings into that accident Tuesday in Seattle, but officials of
United and Boeing said the timing of their announcement was purely
coincidental.
   The package includes firm orders for 180 Boeing jetliners and
options on 190 others.
   United's order came just one week after Ireland's GPA Group
Ltd., an aircraft leasing firm, ordered $17 billion in jets from
Boeing, McDonnell Douglas Corp. and Europe's Airbus Industrie.
   In another coup for Boeing, KLM Royal Dutch Airlines said today
it plans to spend around 2 billion Dutch guilders, or $940 million,
to buy five new Boeing 747-400s and ten new 737s. KLM said the
purchases are part of a program to standardize the type of planes
it flies.
   United is the nation's second-largest carrier, behind American
Airlines. During the first quarter of 1989, American flew 16.89
percent of the total domestic revenue passenger miles to United's
16.73 percent.
   United's order includes firm plans for 120 twin-engine Boeing
737s and 60 narrow-body 757s, plus options on 130 737s and 60 757s.
   United said it has ordered engines from CFM International, a
partnership of General Electric Co. and the French jet-engine maker
SNECMA, for the 737 jetliners. The order is potentially worth $2
billion, CFM officials said.
   The 757s will be powered by Pratt &amp; Whitney engines with a
potential total value of $1.4 billion.
   United spokeswoman Sara Dornacker said the engine costs were
included in United's $15.7 billion estimate for the entire package.
   It had been known for six months that United, a subsidiary of
UAL Corp., was preparing a large order for 737s and 757s. But the
airline wanted to hold off ordering while it tried to get contract
concessions from its pilots and flight attendants unions.
   The airline is still negotiating with those workers but has come
under increasing pressure to buy planes and lock in delivery
positions because its competitors _ including American, Delta Air
Lines and Trans World Airlines _ have placed orders in recent
months.
   ``I guess they've decided to go ahead and show their good
faith'' to the unions, said Louis Marckesano, an analyst who
follows airlines for Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. in Philadelphia.
   He said the size of the order was a surprise but ``it's what's
needed to maintain their growth and their position in the industry
in the next 10 years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
