<DOCNO> AP890427-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-S&amp;Ls 1stLd-Writethru   04-27 0906</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls, 1st Ld-Writethru,0931</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banking Panel Debates Stricter Capital Requirements</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 12 grafs new with committee action; picks up at pvs 6th
graf, S&amp;L supporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee today began
considering an administration-endorsed effort to make owners of
savings and loans put up more of their own actual money than
President Bush initially sought as the price for a $100 billion
taxpayer bailout of the industry.
   After closing a loophole that has allowed some nearly insolvent
thrifts to challenge in court their takeover by federal regulators,
the committee began debating a measure that would shift some of the
risk of S&amp;L lending from the government's insurance funds.
   ``Without real capital _ hard capital _ the taxpayers have no
protection,'' said Rep. Henry Gonzalez, D-Texas, the committee's
chairman.
   Gonzalez likened ``good will'' exemptions from hard cash, stock
or other equity capital requirements that the government over the
past eight years has granted to S&amp;Ls to ``a soft ice-cream cone in
the July sun.''
   ``Good will provides nothing if the institution goes down,'' he
said. ``This entire exercise is a sham unless we change the way the
savings and loans operate. We cannot in good conscience require the
taxpayers to pay out billions of dollars and at the same time tell
them they must bear all the future risks.''
   Earlier today, the committee approved an amendment specifying
that the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. has the authority to take
over sick S&amp;Ls even before they are technically insolvent.
   Two California thrifts are challenging in court their takeovers
earlier this year by the FDIC, which claims it already has that
authority although it is not spelled out specfically in the law.
   ``As long as somebody can go into court, they can get a week's
delay and essentially break the institution by selling off its
assets during that week,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who
sponsored the amendment. ``And who ends up paying is us.''
   The Banking Committee voted Wednesday to require the savings and
loan industry to pour $75 million a year of its profits into
low-income housing subsidies as another price for the bailout.
   The measure, approved on a 27-24 vote with four Democrats
joining all 20 committee Republicans in opposition, could provide
up to 500,000 home buyers a 2 percentage point discount on their
home mortgages, according to consumer groups.
   However, the political party lines are a little more obscure in
that fight over tougher capital standards.
   The administration, Gonzalez and the committee's ranking
Republican, Rep. Chalmers Wylie of Ohio, all favor making S&amp;L
owners put up $2.25 of their own ``real money'' or ``tangible''
capital for each $100 of lending.
   S&amp;L supporters, claiming a third of the 2,950 surviving thrifts
in the nation could be wiped out by that stiff a requirement, favor
a $1.50 ``tangible'' capital requirement adopted last week by the
Senate and earlier by the House panel's financial institutions
subcommittee.
   President Bush's original proposal had no tangible capital
requirement, but Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady said Wednesday
that the administration now believes there should now be a minimum
$3 tangible capital requirement for every $100 in loans.
   However, in a letter to Wylie, Brady called his and Gonzalez'
amendment calling for $2.25 ``a marked and welcome improvement.''
   Wylie led the opposition to Gonzalez' amendment to require the
12 regional Federal Home Loan Banks to set aside 5 percent of their
profits _ $1.5 billion last year _ for providing low-interest
mortgage loans to the working poor.
   The regional banks, although created by the federal government,
are owned by the S&amp;L industry and pass their profits on to
individual S&amp;Ls.
   The legislation already requires S&amp;Ls to put up $300,000 a year
through the regional banks as their contribution to the bailout's
costs. But taxpayers still will assume at least 70 percent of the
estimated $250 billion to $300 billion burden over the next 30
years.
   Democrats said the directed industry subsidies would restore the
original purpose of the Home Loan Bank system when it was
established in the 1930s to promote home ownership among working
families. Without it, they said, there's no reason for a separate
S&amp;L industry.
   ``We've invited the taxpayers to the bailout banquet and told
them they can pick up the tab, but they've got no silverware, no
salad, no entrees,'' said Rep. Gerald Kleczka, D-Wis. ``The least
we can give them is some of the leftovers.''
   Republicans, however, complained that making the industry devote
a portion of its profits is nothing more than an ``end-around
play'' for subsidized housing and called it a symbol of fiscal
irresponsibility.
   ``At stake in this bill is the safety and confidence in the
financial fabric of this nation,'' said Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa.
``To play social policy games with this legislation jeopardizes
confidence in the system.''
   The four Democrats siding with the GOP were Reps. Frank Annunzio
of Illinois, Stephen L. Neal of North Carolina, Carroll Hubbard Jr.
of Kentucky and Doug Barnard Jr. of Georgia.
   The committee also got into a First Amendment fight over trying
to stop advertising by some banks claiming that their federal
insurance fund is safer than the one protecting S&amp;L depositors
against losses of up to $100,000 each.
   It eventually voted 32-10 in favor of an amendment by Rep. David
Dreier, R-Calif., directing the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. to
outlaw ads that ``disparage the condition of either fund.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
