<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0303</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rallied sharply today amid
mounting hopes for evidence of reduced inflationary pressures.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 29.51 to
2,418.62 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 928 up, 376 down and
513 unchanged.
   Analysts expect a fresh sign of slowing economic growth when the
government reports Friday on the index of leading economic
indicators for March.
   The index, which is designed to detect future economic trends,
is expected to show a decline of about 0.6 percent, after falling
0.3 percent in February.
   That would provide some additional encouragement for the Federal
Reserve not to tighten credit in the immediate future.
   Wall Streeters generally agree that the Fed has lately been
following a neutral credit policy, watching to see the effects of a
year-long bout of credit-tightening intended to keep inflation in
check.
   Boeing, which received a big order for planes from United
Airlines on Wednesday, rose 1~ to 75~ in active trading. United
Technologies, whose Pratt &amp; Whitney subsidiary is to produce
engines for some of the aircraft, picked up 1~ to 50}.
   Other gainers among the blue chips included International
Business Machines, up 1[ at 115|; General Electric, up ~ at 48~;
Exxon, up ] at 43{, and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up } at 35[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
1.56 to 173.31. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .69 at 344.10.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 98.84 million shares at
noontime, up from 71.80 million at the same point Wednesday.
