<FIRST>u f PM-Earns-Autos 1stLd-Writethru   04-27 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Autos, 1st Ld-Writethru,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>REPEATING FOR ALL NEEDING</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ford Reports Earning $1.64 Billion In First Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to delete reference to first quarter 1988.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. today said its first-quarter
earnings rose nearly 1 percent to $1.64 billion, the second-most
profitable three-month period in automotive history.
   Ford, the nation's second-largest automaker, said its
first-quarter results translated to $3.44 per share, and compared
with earnings of $1.62 billion, or $3.31 per share, in the first
three months of 1988.
   Revenue totaled $25.87 billion, up 11.5 percent from $23.2
billion during the first three months of 1988.
   Ford set a quarterly industry earnings record during the second
quarter last year, posting $1.66 billion in profit.
   General Motors Corp. last week reported its first-quarter
earnings were $1.55 billion, 42.2 percent more than the same period
last year, when the company changed its accounting method. GM's
earnings came on revenue of $29.6 billion and worked out to $2.37 a
share.
   Chrysler Corp. is expected to release first-quarter results next
week.
   Ford said its first-quarter profit was buoyed by increased
profits overseas, a continuing source of money for the automaker.
The company said its U.S. profits fell 5.6 percent to $800 million
during the quarter, principally because of sluggish sales and costs
of incentives.
   On March 29, Ford set off the latest chain reaction of new
incentive programs by offering financing as low as 2.9 percent on
two-year loans and increasing cash rebates and the number of
vehicles covered by the program.
   GM followed a day later, and in less than a week, Chrysler
announced its own package, offering interest-free financing on
two-year notes.
   The costs of the incentives are borne almost entirely by
manufacturers. Although the programs were announced at the end of
the first quarter and the beginning of the second quarter, they
affect a large number of cars the Big Three produced during the
first three-month period of the year.
   Ford also said earnings by its financial services subsidiary,
which provides consumer car loans among other things, fell 41.3
percent to $141 million from $240 million. The company said profits
were squeezed by rising interest on the money it borrowed and lower
interest payments from the money it loaned, apparently through
incentives.
   The financial services made up 8.6 percent of Ford's profit,
while its automobile operations made up 91.4 percent. First-quarter
profits in the automotive sector rose 8.2 percent to $1.5 billion
from $1.38 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
