<DOCNO> AP890427-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Airlines     04-27 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Airlines,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brittan Says EEC Won't Repeat U.S. Air Deregulation Errors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community will
not make the same errors the United States did when it deregulated
the airlines in 1978, a senior EEC official said Wednesday.
   Sir Leon Brittan, the EEC's commissioner for competition policy,
told an International Civil Airports Association symposium ``the
challenge for the Community will be to learn from the U.S.
experience and avoid the pitfalls encountered there.''
   The EEC, or Common Market, plans to liberalize the European
airline industry as part of its plan to dismantle all internal
barriers to free movement of people, trade, services and capital by
1993.
   The two-day ICAA symposium, which ended Thursday, discussed the
implications for airports.
   Brittan said the EEC Commission, the 12-nation trading bloc's
executive body, would use its antitrust laws to ensure there was no
repetition of the ``spate of takeovers'' which occurred among U.S.
airlines.
   He said the Commission would look at proposed airline mergers on
a case-by-case basis, seeking the ``preservation and promotion of
the position of new entrants as well as smaller regional and
charter carriers.''
</TEXT>
