<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1445EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CustomsCrush     04-27 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Customs Crush,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delays, Diversions Possible Without More Customs Inspectors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boom in international charter traffic may
mean long delays and diversion of flights from the Orlando airport
this summer unless the U.S. Customs Service can increase the number
of inspectors, officials say.
   The bulk of international traffic here is handled by charter
carriers, and the staffing crunch for customs and immigration
inspectors affects only those flights, not scheduled international
service by carriers such as Delta Air Lines, British Airways, KLM
Royal Dutch Airlines and Icelandair.
   Local officials are lobbying Florida's congressional delegation
to get more inspectors assigned to Orlando, the gateway to Walt
Disney World, Sea World and other nearby attractions.
   The number of foreign travelers at Orlando International Airport
jumped 36 percent in 1988 to 742,786, and the rapid growth has
continued so far this year.
   ``We've done everything we can,'' said Dianne Zwicker, the
Custom Service's district director for north and central Florida.
``It's going to be real tight.''
   Customs has nine inspectors to process passengers, baggage and
cargo arriving on international charter flights. Immigration has 26
full- and part-time workers who process charter passengers.
   Airport officials said they expect federal legislation this year
to provide the needed inspectors, although it may not be quick
enough to prevent flights from being diverted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890427-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-P&amp;W-Conrail     04-27 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-P&amp;W-Conrail,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Providence &amp; Worcester RR Could Be Sold To Conrail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conrail has approached the Providence
and Worcester Railroad Co. about a possible merger and the two
companies are discussing both an acquisition and financial support
from Conrail for construction projects.
   P&amp;W and Conrail issued a joint statement Wednesday during P&amp;W's
annual shareholders' meeting saying the companies have begun talks
to ``explore the advantages of reaching an agreement which could
lead to the generation of additional freight traffic for the
benefit of both parties.''
   The talks could lead to P&amp;W's acquisition by Conrail; an
infusion of capital from Conrail to P&amp;W; or joint efforts to build
more freight facilities on P&amp;W lines, the statement said.
   P&amp;W won its independence from the old Penn Central railroad in a
1973 court ruling, and has grown since then from a 44-mile line
linking its namesake cities to a 375-mile system, with 175
employees, that serves Rhode Island, Massachusetts and Connecticut.
   Much of P&amp;W's growth has come by absorbing former Conrail lines
that the larger railroad abandoned as unprofitable. P&amp;W is now the
only freight railroad in Rhode Island.
   Conrail has 32,600 employees and operates on 13,100 miles of
track in the Northeast and Midwest. If it acquires the P&amp;W, it
would be Conrail's first acquisition of another railroad since it
was spun off from government control in 1987.
   P&amp;W posted net profits of $3.9 million, or $1.95 a share, last
year, on $21.4 million in revenue. Conrail's net profits were $306
million, or $4.44 a share, last year on revenues of almost $3.5
billion.
   Andrew Geller, a transportation analyst for Provident National
Bank in Philadelphia, where Conrail is headquartered, said P&amp;W's
revenues were ``almost insignificant'' to the larger railroad. ``My
guess is they want a specific line,'' he said.
   P&amp;W interchanges freight cars with Conrail in Worcester and the
two railroads recently completed New England's first facilities for
handling double-stacked container trains. The work included raising
bridges on Conrail's main line into New England and track
renovations on the P&amp;W's line here.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
