<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1448EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-ControlData 1stLd-Writethru   04-27 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Control Data, 1st Ld-Writethru,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Control Data Reports First-Quarter Earnings Decline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS lede to reflect that company had profit for first quarter,
sted loss.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp., which is shutting
down its supercomputer business, Thursday reported a 55 percent
decline in earnings in the first quarter.
   First-quarter earnings were $3.5 million, or 8 cents a share, on
revenues of $843.5 million, compared with earnings of $7.7 million,
or 18 cents a share, on revenues of $902.2 million for the same
period a year ago.
   Last week, Control Data said it would shut down its
supercomputer business, ETA Systems, and make other cuts that would
result in restructuring charges of $490 million and 3,100 layoffs.
   Of the estimated charges, $350 million was to be from
liquidation of ETA, the supercomputer subsidiary started in 1983 to
compete with Twin Cities rival Cray Research Inc. and other
supercomputer makers.
   The company also announced it would streamline the Cyber
mainframe business.
   ``With restructuring charges of approximately $490 million, we
will obviously report a large loss for the second quarter,'' Robert
M. Price, chairman and chief executive officer, said in a prepared
statement today.
   ``However, the actions we have taken enable Control Data to
focus on its Cyber mainframe customers' needs and to have a
profitable second half in 1989,'' Price said.
   ETA, which employed 800 people, lost $100 million in 1988 and
never made money for the company.
   Control Data provides computer products and services for
business, scientific and engineering applications worldwide.
   The company's last good year financially was 1983, when it
posted profits of $161.7 million. It earned $1.7 million last year
and $19.3 million in 1987 and lost a total of $832 million in 1986
and 1985. It also lost money in the last two quarters of 1988,
including a $12.8 million loss in the fourth quarter.
</TEXT>
