<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-27 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0239</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures prices rose Thursday on the Chicago
Board of Trade amid rumors that the Soviet Union was about to
announce a major corn purchase.
   Wheat futures prices dropped on rumors that the Bush
administration has suspended U.S. subsidies of foreign wheat sales.
Soybean prices closed lower.
   ``Corn was high because of rumors the USSR was going to buy 1.5
to 2 million (metric) tons,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with
Dean Witter Reynolds, Inc.
   Soybeans were under pressure throughout the day as word
circulated that the Brazilian courts were set to rule on the
legality of a dock strike that is holding up that country's soybean
exports.
   ``The thinking is the court is going to be against the
dockworkers and the army is going to be used to break up the strike
if it continues,'' Lespinasse said.
   An extended dockworkers strike in Brazil, the world's
second-largest soybean producer, could result in increased world
demand for U.S. soybeans.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents to 6 cents lower with the
contract for May delivery at $4.05 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 3
cents higher with May at $2.68} a bushel; oats were 3} to 5} lower
with May at $1.77{ a bushel; soybeans were 11{ cents lower to 1
cent higher with May at $7.29 a bushel.
