<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1551EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Kodak-Disney     04-27 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kodak-Disney,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak, Disney Sign 15-Year Promotion Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. and Walt Disney Co.
announced Thursday they had signed a 15-year promotional agreement
that is one of the longest and most comprehensive either company
has ever entered.
   ``There isn't a division of our company or a subdivision, for
that matter, that isn't involved in this agreement,'' said Frank
Wells, president and chief operating officer for Disney.
   Kodak will pay Disney an undisclosed ``multimillion-dollar''
amount for the various promotional opportunities and serve as
official supplier of film, batteries, cameras, still video and
other photographic products.
   Disney has agreed to exclusively use Kodak movie film at its
movie studios and exclusively sell Kodak photographic products when
available. Instant film, which Kodak does not sell, will be
supplied by Polaroid Corp.
   The old agreement, which was due to expire soon, only covered
the sale of film at Disneyland and Disney World and the use of
Disney characters.
   The key to the agreement, which enlarges an alliance the two
firms have had since the early 1980s, is EuroDisneyland, which is
scheduled to open in 1992.
   Kodak estimates that 5 percent of the 14 billion amateur
snapshots taken in the United States each year are snapped on
Disney property. That's roughly 700 million photos.
   ``If 5 percent of the pictures in the United States are taken at
Disney theme parks, we'd be delighted if 5 percent taken in Europe
were taken at Disney theme parks,'' said J. Phillip Samper, vice
chairman and executive officer at Kodak.
   Disney's Japanese park in Tokyo is not included in the
agreement, but the Spruce Goose and the Queen Mary, both
Disney-owned attractions in California, will be included.
   ``Because we've been together now for several years and have
gotten very used to each other, we knew we wanted to set a course
for many more years,'' Wells said after signing the contract
Wednesday.
   ``You get Kodak and Disney people together, thinking up ideas
and everything seems to multiply,'' said Samper.
   ``There is, I would dare say, twice the ways of reaching the
public in terms of the volume of what we do ... then when the
original agreement was done,'' Wells said.
   The companies have been involved with each other for more than
50 years.
   Kodak was an early participant at Disneyland, which opened in
1955, and was a sponsor of Disney's ``Wonderful World of Color''
television show in the late 1950s when only 700,000 color TV sets
existed in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
