<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-ANPA-Teens     04-27 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-ANPA-Teens,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Agers More Inclined To Radio Than Newspapers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teen-agers are more likely to listen to the radio
than to read a newspaper on an average day, says a survey presented
to the American Newspaper Publishers Association.
   Ninety-three percent of the young people surveyed, ages 12 to
17, said they listened to the radio during an average weekday.
Forty-one percent said they read a newspaper and 23 percent said
they watched an evening television news broadcast on an average
weekday.
   ``Radio is basically an entertainment media, a background
media,'' said Dotty Shea, senior project director for the Newspaper
Advertising Bureau.
   ``Many of teens that I talked to said, `Hey, I got the radio on
in the background while I'm doing my homework, talking to my
friend. They did not usually just sit there and listen to the radio
by itself. Reading a newspaper is a much more focused activity.''
   The survey, conducted by Simmons Media Research and the
Newspaper Advertising Bureau last year, was presented to the
publishers' group Wednesday, the final day of the ANPA convention.
   It was based on interviews with 1,074 teens in a period late
last year marked by Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's visit to
the United States, the earthquake in Soviet Armenia and a space
shuttle flight.
   Thirty-eight percent of the teen-agers surveyed said they could
think of a news item during that period that was notable to them.
Twenty-five percent listed newspapers as their prime source for the
time of interest while 47 percent gave television as their source.
   Teens tend to be introduced to newspapers through the comics,
said Leo Bogart, retiring executive vice president of the Newspaper
Advertising Bureau, who presented the survey to the publishers.
   He urged the publishers and editors to spread stories of
interest to teens throughout the paper and not ``assign them to an
editorial ghetto.''
   Christine Urban, a media consultant from Sharon, Mass., warned
publishers to stop ``tinkering at the margins'' of papers by making
editorial changes and, instead, to consider ``rethinking the whole
style, the whole presentation'' in trying to lure teens.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890427-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ConstructionStarts     04-27 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Construction Starts,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Works Projects Halt Decline In Construction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Friday AMs; Embargo set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spurt of public works projects in March halted
a decline in the value of the nation's construction contracts,
although housing and non-residential building projects continued to
slide, according to figures released Thursday.
   The F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information Services Co.
said the value of new construction edged up 1 percent to a
projected annual rate of $236.1 billion.
   The slight increase, which followed a 7 percent decline in
February, resulted from a 22 percent rise in non-building
construction from the previous month. For March, public works and
utilities construction climbed to an annualized total value of
$49.2 billion, compared with $40.3 billion in February.
   For the entire first quarter, however, the unadjusted total of
all newly started construction stood at $53 billion, a decline of 3
percent from the same period a year ago.
   ``First quarter data show that the 1989 rate of contracting was
nearly 10 percent below its peak reached in mid-1987,'' said George
Christie, F.W. Dodge's chief economist. ``Two-thirds of the cutback
since then can be accounted for by just two building types _
offices and apartments.''
   The unadjusted value of non-residential building construction
fell 4 percent in the first quarter to $18.6 billion, compared with
$19.3 billion in the first quarter last year.
   From February to March, the adjusted annual value of
non-residential building construction fell 5 percent to $78.4
billion. The annualized value of residential construction also
declined in March, falling 1 percent to $108.4 billion.
</TEXT>
