<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Autos     04-27 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Autos,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Earnings Up 0.8 Percent In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co.'s first quarter profit was
0.8 percent higher than in the same period last year as overseas
earnings offset a drop in domestic profits, the automaker reported
Thursday.
   Ford said its profit of $1.64 billion, or $3.44 a share, came on
revenue of $25.87 billion. That compared with a profit of $1.62
billion, or $3.31 per share, on revenue of $23.19 billion a year
earlier.
   A week ago, General Motors Corp. reported it earned $1.55
billion, or $2.37 per common share, on revenues of $29.6 billion
during the first three months of the year. Chrysler Corp. was
expected to announce its first-quarter results next week.
   At a news conference, Ford Vice President and Treasurer David
McCammon Ford's first-quarter profits were buoyed by a 10 percent
increase in overseas earnings. Earnings in the United States, the
basis for profit-sharing computations, fell 5.6 percent to $800
million and could continue to slump, he said.
   He said Ford was cutting about 2 percent from its second-quarter
production schedule, but much of it would come out of overtime.
   Ford also reported earnings for its car-financing arm, Ford
Motor Credit Co., dropped 49.1 percent to $101.6 million from
$199.7 million. Ford Motor Chairman William Odom said the decline
mainly stemmed from rising costs of borrowing and lower profit
margins, due partly to costs of buyer incentive programs.
   Odom said Ford's cost of borrowing in the first quarter this
year was 9.2 percent compared with 8 percent a year earlier.
   Rising interest rates _ prompted by Fed credit-tightening moves
aimed at slowing the economy to curb inflation _ and
slower-than-anticipated car and truck sales prompted Ford on March
29 to begin offering new buyer incentive programs featuring
cut-rate auto loans. GM and Chrysler followed suit with similar
programs.
   McCammon the company expected an economic slowdown over the rest
of the year, which would keep the Federal Reserve from pushing
interest rates higher. McCammon said he expected interest rates
actually to fall during the second half of the year.
   The costs of the latest incentives should affect the
corporation's second quarter earnings. Ford earnned an industry
record $1.66 billion in second quarter 1988. The incentives expire
May 31 but could be extended.
   Financial services made up 8.6 percent of Ford's profit, while
its automobile operations made up 91.4 percent. First-quarter
profits in the automotive sector rose 8.2 percent to $1.5 billion
from $1.38 billion.
   When asked if Ford's earnings for all of 1989 would be lower
than the $5.3 billion it earned last year, McCammon said, ``At this
point, that would be the guess.''
   During the first 20 days of April, with the incentives in full
force, Ford's car sales increased 27.3 percent over the same time
last year. Meanwhile, GM's sales rose 7.2 percent and Chrysler's
were off 1.2 percent compared with the same time last year.
   McCammon said he couldn't be specific about the costs of the
incentives, but the new package costs the company between $100 and
$150 a vehicle more than the previous package did.
   Accordingly, if Ford's estimate that 55 percent of the non-fleet
cars it sells are covered by the incentive package, the company has
paid an extra $7.6 million to $11.4 million in incentive costs for
the cars sold during the first 20 days of this month.
</TEXT>
