<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Allegheny     04-27 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Allegheny,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allegheny International Posts Quarterly Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troubled appliance maker Allegheny
International Inc. on Thursday reported a $4.6 million
second-quarter loss as the company's bankruptcy-related expenses
increased and competition toughened.
   The loss, in the fiscal period ended April 2, widened slightly
from a $4.5 million loss posted in the year-ago period.
   Sales during the period rose 5.3 percent to $268.3 million, from
$254.7 million a year ago.
   The company, which filed for reorganization under Chapter 11 of
the federal Bankruptcy Code in February 1988, has asked a
bankruptcy judge to approve a plan that would allow Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette to acquire a 62 percent stake in the company for
$750 million in cash and securities.
   Costs related to the bankruptcy increased from $1.8 million to
$5.1 million during the second quarter.
   The Pittsburgh-based company produces Oster and Sunbeam small
appliances, along with barbecue grills, lawn and patio furniture,
electric blankets, scales and instruments.
   Barbecue grill and outdoor furniture sales and operating income
improved over the 1988 period, but profit margins declined in small
appliances due to competition from other manufacturers, the company
said.
   For the first two fiscal quarters, Allegheny lost $2.83 million
on sales of $495.3 million, compared with a loss of $2.74 million
on sales of $511 million in the 1988 period.
</TEXT>
