consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 226.18 million shares.
   Analysts expect a fresh sign of slowing economic growth when the
government reports Friday on the index of leading economic
indicators for March.
   The index, which is designed to detect future economic trends,
is expected to show a decline of about 0.6 percent, after falling
0.3 percent in February.
   That would provide some additional encouragement for the Federal
Reserve not to tighten credit in the immediate future.
   Wall Streeters generally agree that the Fed has lately been
following a neutral credit policy, watching to see the effects of a
year-long bout of credit-tightening intended to keep inflation in
check.
   Buying by professional traders engaged in computer-program
strategies involving options and futures on stock indexes helped
fuel the market's advance, brokers said.
   Boeing, which received a big order for planes from United
Airlines on Wednesday, rose 1} to 75} in active trading.
   United Technologies gained 3{ to 52] and General Electric picked
up | to 48|. A GE venture and United Technologies's Pratt &amp; Whitney
subsidiary are to produce engines for the aircraft.
   All three stocks are components of the Dow Jones industrial
average. Other gainers among the blue chips included Philip Morris,
up 2{ at 127}; McDonald's, up 1[ at 54}; Procter &amp; Gamble, up ] at
95, and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up } at 35[.
   Delta, which reported sharply higher earnings for its latest
quarter, was off [ at 65[.
   Ford Motor dropped } to 47~. The company reported higher
first-quarter profits, but said its earnings for the full year
might not equal the record total reported for 1988.
   Clark Equipment, which posted a strong gain in its first-quarter
results from continuing operations, rose } to 38.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $22.84 billion, or
0.75 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 1.31 to 173.06.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 2.84 to 356.82, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up 2.65 at 309.58.
