<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-27 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished at varied levels against key
foreign currencies in light U.S. trading Thursday after a similar
performance overseas.
   Gold prices declined in the United States following modest rises
on foreign precious metals markets. Republic National Bank of New
York quoted a troy ounce of gold at $382.30 as of 4 p.m. EDT, down
from Wednesday's late bid of $384.50.
   Foreign exchange dealers around the world sold dollars on news
that West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl had confirmed his
government would repeal the country's 10 percent withholding tax on
interest income.
   The repeal, scheduled for July 1, would make the West German
mark and mark-denominated holdings more attractive.
   The dollar's downward move also was attributed to comments by an
official with West Germany's central bank, the Bundesbank. Lothar
Mueller said he would like to see the dollar decline to 1.80 marks.
   Despite this seemingly negative news for the U.S. currency, the
dollar recovered and ended trading above its lowest levels of the
day. Corporate demand was cited as a reason for the dollar's
renewed strength.
   Bank of Boston dealer Bob Morrissey said trading seemed subdued
after Wednesday's brisk business in response to the government's
gross national product report.
   The Commerce Department said the economy, as measured by GNP,
expanded at a 5.5 percent annual rate in the first three months of
1989, the fastest clip in over a year.
   Morrissey said the markets are awaiting fresh economic signals;
the Commerce Department on Friday is scheduled to issue its report
on the leading indicators for March.
   The dollar began its trading day in Tokyo by rising to 132.05
Japanese yen from 131.47 yen at Wednesday's close. Later, in
London, the dollar edged up further to 132.15 yen. the dollar
closed at 132.12 yen in later New York trading, up from 132.105 on
Wednesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6905, cheaper for buyers
than $1.6932 late Wednesday. Sterling rose to $1.691 in New York
from $1.6900 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's levels, included: 1.8760 West German marks, down from
1.8793; 1.65855 Swiss francs, up from 1.6580; 1.19195 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.18955; 6.3475 French francs, down from 6.3595;
and, 1,374.25 Italian lire, down from 1,377.375.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Wednesday's
levels included: 1.8756 West German marks, down from 1.8770; 1.6585
Swiss francs, up from 1.6555; 6.3455 French francs, up from 6.3395;
2.1150 Dutch guilders, unchanged; 1,373.50 Italian lire, down from
1,374.00; and, 1.1940 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1900.
   Gold bullion prices gave a mixed performance.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $383.30 a troy ounce, $2 lower than Wednesday's
settlement.
   Gold rose in Zurich to a late bid price of $384.25 a troy ounce,
up from $383.50 bid late Wednesday. In London, the metal also was
quoted at a late bid of $384.25, unchanged from Wednesday's late
bid.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $385.71 bid, up from
$385.59.
   Silver bullion prices also pulled back. On the New York Comex,
silver bullion for current delivery settled at $5.645 a troy ounce,
down from $5.763 at Wednesday's close. Silver bullion dipped in
London to a late bid of $5.76 a troy ounce, down from $5.77 bid
late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
