<FIRST>u f AM-ScandalsConference 1stLd-Writethru   04-27 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scandals Conference, 1st Ld-Writethru,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Securities Firms, Regulators Looking At Tougher Internal Compliance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS amount of Drexel fine to $650 million in 12th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street's three-year scandal binge, capped
by the recent Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. fraud case settlements,
has sapped investor confidence and forced investment firms and
securities regulators to re-examine compliance procedures, experts
said Thursday.
   ``Newspaper stories about Levine and Boesky, Wang and Drexel
Burnham hardly ensure deep confidence in the public in the
financial markets,'' said U.S. District Judge Kevin Duffy said,
referring to four of the decade's most prominent insider trading
cases.
   Duffy, a former Securities and Exchange Commission regional
director in New York, was one of more than 200 state regulators,
government prosecutors and investment executives attending a North
American Securities Administrators Association conference on the
impact of white-collar crime on public policy.
   Duffy and others called for greater self-policing by securities
and commodities firms to help prevent fraud.
   Under its landmark settlement of fraud and insider trading
charges with the SEC earlier this month, Drexel pledged to boost
its internal compliance measures and agreed to tight SEC monitoring
for three years.
   Securities regulators said implementation of the deal was being
closely watched for indications whether it prompts other firms to
toughen internal compliance measures as a deterrent to
market-related crime.
   ``Drexel will be an example for other companies who don't want
to be the next one,'' said Susan Bryant, securities administrator
for Oklahoma, who heads a panel preparing action by that state
against Drexel.
   She said amendments Congress approved last year to the 1934
Securities and Exchange Act also should put pressure on individual
firms. Brokerages now can be held liable for failing to enforce
their own internal control procedures.
   ``I think things like the Drexel settlement are just the
beginning,'' Bryant said. ``I think regulators are going to be
looking at these procedures to see if it works.''
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., a member of two House subcommittees
examining securities law reform, said Congress likely would be
pressed this term to boost SEC funding and allow the commission to
fine individuals up to $100,000 per violation and institutions up
to $500,000 for securities law violations.
   ``They don't have the resources to deal with two major cases at
once without the rest of the agency's caseload being altered,'' he
said.
   Wyden wouldn't characterize Drexel's SEC deal and its $650
million plea settlement with the Manhattan U.S. attorney's offices
as inadequate, but said:
   ``Certainly the sum of money is very large by anybody's
pocketbook calculation. But as incredible as it seems, it's about
in the ballpark of what Michael Milken makes in one year.''
   Milken is the former Drexel junk bond financier who was named in
the SEC suit against Drexel and later charged in a separate
98-count racketeering and fraud indictment. The government claims
he made more than $1 billion in four years, including $550 million
in 1987.
   Hardwick Simmons, vice chairman of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.,
a major Wall Street brokerage house, said the industry already
spends $300 million annually on self-regulation and routinely
cooperates with authorities.
   ``That doesn't mean we're going to catch all those who abuse
others and the system,'' he said. ``It does mean we'll do
everything we can to prevent it.''
   Duffy, a judge in the Southern District of New York, where the
major Wall Street securities fraud cases are being tried, said the
case of broker Dennis Levine _ whose revelations led prosecutors to
notorious insider trader Ivan Boesky _ was ``tied up with a bow and
delivered to the SEC'' because of internal compliance by Levine's
firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890427-0289 </DOCNO>
