<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Jets     04-27 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Jets,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Wants to Lease 14 Boeing 727s to Pan Am</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines, three days after
outlining a plan for cutting away $1.8 billion in assets, Thursday
announced a deal to lease 14 Boeing 727-200 planes to rival Pan
American World Airways.
   The $96.6 million, 5-year lease gives Pan Am an option to extend
the lease or buy the planes at a price to be negotiated, Eastern
spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said. The agreement must be approved by
the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New York, which has had oversight of
such deals since Eastern filed March 9 for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization and protection.
   ``We had indicated we would be raising about $1.8 billion
through assets sales,'' Ms. Ceremsak said. ``This is certainly the
first step in this direction for the new, reduced-size airline.''
   Eastern President Phil Bakes described the planned streamlining
of Eastern on Monday, after parent Texas Air Corp. ruled out a sale
of Eastern in its entirety. Bakes said Eastern would rebuild with a
smaller airline and pay its debts by slashing service 29 percent
from pre-strike levels and selling assets.
   Eastern's unions, on strike since March 4, continue to hope the
bankruptcy court and Eastern's creditors will call for a sale of
the airline. U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland has set for
May 3 a hearing on why Eastern shouldn't be sold to the highest
bidder in its entirety, including its Northeast shuttle service
slated to be sold to developer Donald Trump for $365 million.
   Ms. Ceremsak said there was considerable industry interest in
Eastern assets such as planes, airport gates and routes and that
the beleaguered company was receiving good offers.
   ``There's a tremendous demand right now for airplanes by other
carriers that are expanding,'' she said. ``The delivery positions
and orders are backed up in the factories.''
   She said she didn't have any information on other asset sales in
the works, but added, ``there have been many interested parties.
Obviously, there are going to be other transactions.''
   Eastern's plan calls for a fleet of 157 aircraft, down from
around 250 before the strike. If the 14 149-seat 727 planes are
leased to Pan Am at $115,000 a month and another 21 of the 727s are
sold to Trump in the planned shuttle sale, that would leave Eastern
with 60 other ``excess aircraft for sale or long-term lease,'' Ms.
Ceremsak said.
   Pilots union spokesman J.B. Stokes said the airline's unions
oppose any transfer of Eastern assets while hoping the bankruptcy
court will approve a buyout of the whole company.
   ``They can make all the plans they want,'' Stokes said. ``I
think they neglect to tell the people they must get approval from
the bankruptcy court. That's a fairly lengthy process and it's not
going to happen overnight.''
   The shuttle sale also must be approved by the court.
</TEXT>
