<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-27 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Silver Prices Drop On Supply Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Silver futures prices dropped sharply Thursday on New York's
Commodity Exchange on selling prompted by indications of ample
supplies.
   On other markets, gasoline and crude oil prices fell, cattle
lost ground while hog prices rallied, and wheat and soybean futures
slipped while corn rose.
   Silver settled 11.8 cents to 15.2 cents lower, with May at $5.64
a troy ounce.
   Pressure built in the silver market ahead of Friday, the first
day for traders to post their intention to deliver physical silver
against the May contract.
   ``The drop reflected the large deliveries expected,'' said
Stephen W. Platt, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago.
   A large number of delivery notices would suggest that producers
have adequate supplies of silver on hand.
   ``The downward pressure also tended to reflect the high
warehouse stocks,'' Platt said.
   Gold prices fell in sympathy with silver and on signs of selling
by gold dealers, Platt said.
   ``There is a general feeling that if the economy is slowing
down, metal finishing demand won't be there,'' he said.
   Gold settled $2.10 to $3.80 lower with June at $386.10 a troy
ounce.
   Petroleum futures settled mixed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange on position-evening ahead of the expiration Friday of the
gasoline and heating-oil contracts. Traders also were nervous over
the possibility that OPEC members may increase their crude-oil
production later this year.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 27 cents
lower with June at $20.92 a barrel; heating oil was .33 cent to .88
cent higher with May at 51.86 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.06 cent to .60 cent lower with June at 72.27 cents a gallon.
   Hogs were up, pork bellies were down and cattle futures were
narrowly mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   The recent rise in pork-market volatility reflects conflicting
views of whether cash prices for hogs have reached their normal
seasonal bottom.
   The hog market tends to make a bottom in late April, then trend
higher into the summer as the flow of hogs to slaughter slows.
   ``It has to do with the seasonality of the farrowing of pigs and
the seasonality of when they come to market,'' said Dale Durchholz,
an analyst with Agri-Visor Services Inc. in Bloomington, Ill.
   He said cash hog prices have recently approached $40 per
hundredweight, a signal that futures prices may be working higher,
but ``it's a little bit premature to say it with any real
conviction.''
   Live cattle settled .20 cent lower to .40 cent higher with June
at 70.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .08 cent lower to .05
cent higher with May at 75.82 cents a pound; live hogs were .18
cent lower to .40 cent higher with June at 47.07 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .28 cent to 1 cent lower with May at 32.37
cents a pound.
   Corn futures prices rose on the Chicago Board of Trade amid
rumors of a major corn purchase by the Soviet Union. After the
close, the Agriculture Department announced the Soviets had
purchased 150,000 metric tons of U.S. corn.
   Wheat futures prices dropped and soybean prices closed lower.
   Soybeans were under pressure throughout the day as word
circulated that the Brazilian courts were set to rule on the
legality of a dock strike that is holding up that country's soybean
exports and could lead to increased global demand for U.S. soybeans.
   ``The thinking is that the court is going to be against the
dockworkers and the army is going to be used to break up the strike
if it continues,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean
Witter in Chicago.
   Wheat settled 2\ cents to 6 cents lower with May at $4.05 a
bushel; corn was 1 cent to 3 cents higher with May at $2.68} a
bushel; oats were 3} cents to 6 cents lower with May at $1.77\ a
bushel; soybeans were 11 cents lower to 1 cent higher with May at
$7.29{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
