<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     04-27 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gasoline Prices Continue To Climb</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline futures prices closed flat to lower in
active trading Thursday, reversing the sharp runup of recent days.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May contract for
unleaded gasoline finished the day at 78.12 cents a gallon,
unchanged from Wednesday. The last time gasoline closed higher was
on Nov. 27, 1985, when it settled at 79 cents.
   Analysts said the weakness in gasoline was expected because
current price levels are exaggerated and could not be sustained
indefinitely. Gasoline futures have surged 65 percent since Jan. 1.
   Crude oil that is traded on the exchange was down across the
board. The June contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of crude oil fell 27 cents to $20.92 a barrel. Other contract
months lost as much as 19 cents.
   Heating oil for May delivery rose 0.88 cent to 51.86 cents a
gallon. Other contract months also gained.
   May contracts for heating oil and gasoline are scheduled to
expire on Friday.
   John H. O'Connell, analyst with Refco Inc., said softer gasoline
prices were not a surprise.
   ``I don't think the market can go straight up,'' O'Connell said.
``In the last few days, people who were short took a beating.''
   O'Connell said the fall in crude prices probably pressured the
gasoline market and reflected expectations of higher world
production.
   ``There is a belief in the market that the Saudis are signaling
a lifting of ceilings, making the market rethink its price
levels,'' O'Connell said.
   Consumer gasoline prices, which are usually more than 20 cents
below wholesale prices, have surged in recent weeks, playing
catchup to the sharp rise in crude prices since last December. Some
analysts predict a further rise in retail gas prices but at a
slower rate than in recent weeks as market conditions stabilize.
   Industry estimates put OPEC production at about 2 million
barrels a day higher than its self-imposed quota of 18.5 million
barrels. Saudi Arabia is the largest OPEC producer and the world's
largest exporter.
   Analysts say excess production from OPEC has offset much of the
supply disruptions stemming from the Alaska spill and last week's
North Sea gas explosion.
   The main factor driving up gasoline prices in recent weeks are
the new federal regulations scheduled to take effect this summer
lowering the amount of lead content in gasoline. The higher octane
formula requires the refining of more crude oil to make the new
gasoline.
   Since demand is perceived to be rising while the capacity of the
nation's refineries are thought to be declining, expectations of
possible tight supplies of gasoline have sent wholesale prices
soaring.
   But some observers believe that the current price rises are not
warranted and that refiners and wholesalers raised their prices
before a shortage or tightness actually occurred. A lot of oil and
oil products are actually in storage, analysts said.
   ``Despite the unpredictable events over the last several months,
we still do not see the fundamental support for recent price
levels, and we still anticipate a correction,'' the petroleum
consulting firm of Purvin &amp; Gertz Inc. said in its weekly analysis.
   The Department of Energy recently made what analysts said was a
substantial downward revision in its demand estimate for January.
The DOE also lowered refinery output but raised inventory estimates
to show a higher level than earlier recorded.
   Demand for February and March also are believed to be lower than
earlier predicted.
   Despite lower refinery capacity, analysts say that detailed
studies indicate that both volume and octane capabilities will be
sufficient to meet demand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
