<HEAD>Houghton Mifflin Stock Falls As Bass Cuts Stake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of Houghton Mifflin Co. stock dropped
sharply on Thursday as a group led by Texas investor Robert M. Bass
disclosed it has whittled its stake in the textbook publisher to
1.1 percent.
   The Bass Group said in a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission that it sold about 575,200 shares on Wednesday and
Thursday at prices ranging from $42.02 to $43.46 a share, leaving
it with 161,300 shares in the company.
   The group said it sold the stock because it appeared to be
``reasonably priced'' and added the group regards the company as
``one of the nation's leading publishers'' and said it is
``exceptionally well-managed.''
   Houghton Mifflin had no comment on the move. ``They've made
their comment,'' said Claudia Regan, a vice president.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Houghton Mifflin dropped down
$3.25 a share to $39.37{.
   In late January, the Bass Group disclosed it had boosted its
holdings in the Boston-based company to 5.6 percent, sending
Houghton Mifflin's stock sharply higher on speculation that a
takeover effort may be launched. The stock had been trading at
about $38 a share before the disclosure.
   At the time of the January filing, Houghton Mifflin downplayed
the move, saying Bass was a longtime investor in the company. The
company had adopted a poison-pill takeover defense plan in December.
   Houghton Mifflin is a leading educational publisher and also
publishes general interest books and educational and
word-processing software. The company earned $24.1 million, or
$1.70 per share on 1988 revenue of $368.3 million.
