<HEAD>Pennzoil Reports First Quarter Earnings Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennzoil Co. said Thursday its first-quarter
profit more than doubled in the first quarter due in part to a
sharp gain related to its 1988 legal settlement with Texaco Inc.
   For the three months ended March 31, Pennzoil said its net
earnings rose to $52.5 million, or $1.34 a share, from $11.3
million, or 18 cents a share, in the same period a year ago.
   Revenue rose to $673 million, from $485 million in the same 1988
period.
   The Houston-based energy products company, which received a $3
billion settlement from Texaco in April 1988, also cited
improvements in its sulphur and oil and gas divisions.
   Investment income, drawing from the Texaco settlement, grew from
$6.8 million in the first three months of 1988 to $52.2 million
during the same 1989 period, the company said.
   Pennzoil's sulphur unit, reporting increased prices and volume,
recorded $30.1 million in operating income, compared with $11.9
million in the first quarter of 1988. Sales volume totaled 608
million tons, up from 472 million during the previous year's
quarter.
   Randal B. McDonald, Pennzoil president and chief executive
officer, said lower exploration costs helped boost Pennzoil's oil
and gas income to $23.8 million during the January-March period, up
from $11.6 million in the same 1988 quarter.
