<FIRST>r f AM-Unisys     04-27 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unisys,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unisys Chairman Puts Hopes In New Mainframe Computers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. is poised to overcome a
first-quarter loss sustained during delays in putting a new
computer line on sale, Chairman W. Michael Blumenthal said Thursday.
   Sales of the new 2200 series mainframe computers and expected
gains in defense business _ despite tight military budgets and a
procurement investigation _ should reassure shareholders,
Blumenthal said.
   Unisys recently reported it lost $78.7 million in the first
quarter compared with net income of $149.3 million, or 72 cents a
share, in the first quarter of 1988.
   ``This was essentially an anomaly,'' he told a news conference.
``These products are now reaching the marketplace, and therefore
prospects are considerably brighter.''
   Blumenthal was in Detroit for Unisys' 1989 stockholders meeting.
   Unisys was formed when Burroughs Corp. took over Sperry Corp. in
a $4.8 billion deal in 1986.
   The company said orders for its 1100 series of mainframe
computers had fallen off and customers were still waiting for
shipments of the 2200 series introduced Feb. 21.
   Demand for mainframe computers has been flat, Blumenthal said.
``But that's a problem the entire industry has faced,'' he said.
   Blumenthal said companies may be holding off on major capital
expenditures out of fears of inflation or an impending economic
slowdown.
   The government's procurement investigation and the suspension of
three former Sperry divisions from military contracts also hurt
earnings, Blumenthal said.
   Allegations of overcharges in 1983 in connection with a Sperry
contract to upgrade the Air Force's worldwide computer system led
to a $700,000 cash settlement by Unisys in March and dismissal of
the government's charges.
   Blumenthal said Unisys incurred costs in cooperating with the
investigation, ``and making sure these particular things cannot
happen within the Unisys organization.''
   He said Unisys also hopes for gains, despite tight federal
budgets, through government contracts that can help cut spending
through efficient computer use.
   Unisys can get more business, he said, ``as the government looks
for areas where it can reduce its costs, and our people are a way
to do that.''
