<FIRST>r f AM-GannettShareholders     04-27 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gannett Shareholders,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gannett Tells Shareholders USA Today Moving Steadily toward Profitability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gannett Co. Inc.'s flagship USA Today is moving
steadily toward profitability, based on projections of increasing
circulation and higher prices to third-party buyers such as hotels,
company directors told shareholders Thursday.
   The shareholder meeting marked the formal passing of the
corporate baton from Allen Neuharth, founder of USA Today and
retiring chairman and chief executive officer, to successor John J.
Curley.
   Neuharth, who turned 65 last month, said he had been asked
repeatedly during the American Newspaper Publishers Association
convention this week for his feelings about retirement.
   ``I'm ecstatic about it,'' he said.
   Then, taking note of the run-up in Gannett Co. stock in recent
weeks, Neuharth added, ``If I had known that merely by retiring as
chairman, the stock would climb by 15 percent over the last month,
I would have done it earlier.''
   The company is riding a streak of 86 consecutive quarters of
record quarterly profits. Despite that performance, USA Today has
lost about $600 million _ before taxes _ since its September 1982
debut, recording just two quarterly profits during that stretch.
   Thomas Curley, president and chief operating officer of USA
Today, told shareholders he expected USA Today to be profitable in
both the second and fourth quarters of 1989.
   But he still predicted that ``for the full year, we should lose
a little, especially if the economy weakens. ... The goal for 1990
is to open the window of profit.''
   Thomas Curley said the newspaper's profitability would be
bolstered by an increase in the price of USA Today to suppliers who
give the newspapers away, with each increase of one cent worth
about $4 million in revenues.
   He also said circulation had climbed by 8.2 percent in 1988 for
the Friday-weekend edition and 6.1 percent for the remaining four
weekdays.
   John Quinn, who is editor-in-chief of USA Today, said he hoped
the meeting would end the ``dumb comparisons'' being made between
Neuharth and Curley, each of whom he lauded as the ``right man at
the right time.''
   And indeed, Curley proved just as adept at straight talk as
Neuharth while presiding over his first annual meeting and the
company's 22nd since going public.
   When Accuracy in Media's Reed Irvine said that a survey of
business executives revealed that most felt newspapers' coverage of
business and businessmen was biased, Curley replied:
   ``A lot of them (businessmen) are used to adulatory business
coverage by their own press departments and they may get a little
rabbit-eared because they're used to hearing what fine fellows they
are.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
