<FIRST>u f AM-LoralSale     04-27 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Loral Sale,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Loral's Schwartz Leads Group In $455 Million Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loral Corp. said Thursday it had completed the
$455 million sale of two divisions to a group led by Loral
executives and an investment bank.
   Sold were the Aircraft Braking Systems division based in Akron,
Ohio, and the Engineered Fabrics division based in Rockmart, Ga.
Loral acquired the units when it bought Goodyear Aerospace Corp.
from Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co. in 1987.
   The group was led by Bernard Schwartz, Loral's chairman and
chief executive, and Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings Inc. It
offered $425 million on March 27 but had to raise its offer after a
second, unidentified bidder emerged.
   The new offer is about $5 million more than the competing one,
Loral said. The bids were evaluated by a group of outside directors
and the firm of Lazard Freres &amp; Co.
   The sale helps Loral narrow down to its core business of
high-tech electronics, particularly defense electronics, while
raising money to pay off the debt from the Goodyear purchase, Loral
said.
   The Aircraft Braking Systems division has about 1,540 employees
and the Engineered Fabrics division has about 610. Their combined
sales are about $300 million. Loral said they were profitable but
required heavy investment.
   The $455 million purchase price is made up of $425 million in
cash and $30 million in notes that are convertible into 15 percent
of the stock in the buyout group, which is called Opus Acquisition
Corp.
