<FIRST>r f AM-WorldBank-Mexico     04-27 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Bank-Mexico,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Gets $250 Million from World Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico, trying to get $7 billion in help this
year, will receive a $250 million loan from the World Bank, the
bank announced Thursday.
   The loan is to be used for investment in the Mexican textiles,
auto parts and flowers industries.
   It is to be repaid in 17 years, including five years of grace
during which only interest will be due, at a variable rate now 7.65
percent a year.
   Mexico is the second largest debtor in the Third World with a
debt of about $107 billion. It is looking for help to compensate
for the billions it must pay out every year as interest and
principal.
   Last Friday, it was announced that commercial banks were being
asked to postpone until 1990 about $1.175 billion in payments of
principal due this year. A committee representing the banks backed
the request.
   Negotiations between the Mexican government and the commercial
banks on a broader financial package are continuing in New York.
   The staff of the International Monetary Fund, the World Bank's
sister organization, reached an agreement with Mexican authorities
that would provide $3.6 billion. This is subject to approval by the
151 governments in the fund, some of which _ notably Britain and
West Germany _ have expressed doubts about how some of the money
would be applied under the debt-relief proposal of Treasury
Secretary Nicholas F. Brady.
   A decision is expected at the end of May or early in June.
   Also under negotiation are three more loans from the World Bank
totaling $1.5 billion. The bank is the biggest source of aid loans
to Third World countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
