<DOCNO> AP890427-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1922EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     04-27 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Broad Money Supply Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two broadest measures of the nation's money
supply rose n the week ended April 17, the Federal Reserve Board
reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 rose to a seasonally
adjusted $3,087.1 billion from $3,083.6 billion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, rose to a seasonally adjusted
$3,971.1 billion from $3,965.6 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, fell to a
seasonally adjusted $781.6 billion from $782.0 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   The Fed in February reaffirmed a provisional target for 1989 of
3 percent to 7 percent growth in M2 and 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent
growth in M3. The Fed has not set a target for M1 growth since
early 1987.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $3,075.3 billion, a 1.9
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous
13 weeks. M3 averaged $3,945.7 billion, up 3.8 percent, while M1
fell 1.0 percent to an average of $785.6 billion.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window, excluding extended credit,
averaged $476 million a day in the week ended Wednesday, down from
$997 million the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $288.4 billion in the two-week period ended
Wednesday, up from $288.0 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890427-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-USShoe     04-27 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US Shoe,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Shoe Appalled At Sale's Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of United States Shoe Corp. say they
were stunned when Merrill Lynch Capital Partners Inc. pulled out of
its promise to buy the company's footwear division, but an analyst
says this gives other bidders a chance to make offers.
   The market apparently is looking at the failure of the proposed
$422.5 million sale as bad news, said Robert Byrne of the Advest
Inc. securities firm in Cincinnati. U.S. Shoe stock fell $1 a share
to $16.75 in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   ``My personal opinion is that maybe it's not bad news,'' Byrne
said. ``It means that somebody else might buy them. The stock has
been as high as 27 and it's trading down near its low. It certainly
would be a better buy down around where it is now.''
   U.S. Shoe, a Cincinnati-based shoe, apparel and eyewear company,
said Wednesday that Merrill Lynch does not intend to consummate the
previously announced agreement.
   Merrill Lynch and a group of management officials from the
footwear division announced on Feb. 27 that they had agreed to buy
the footwear group and U.S. Shoe's Cincinnati headquarters building
for $422.5 million in cash. The deal would have given U.S. Shoe the
right to buy as much as 17.5 percent of the purchasing
corporation's stock.
   Merrill Lynch, a New York-based buyout firm, decided that
certain conditions and obligations of the purchase agreement had
not been satisfied, U.S. Shoe said without elaborating.
   Philip G. Barach, U.S. Shoe chairman and chief executive
officer, said his company was surprised and disappointed.
   ``We disagree with their position and we believe that we have a
binding agreement to sell our footwear division. We shall continue
to explore our options with respect to the agreement,'' Barach said.
   He said U.S. Shoe already conducted a thorough auction process
for the division before reaching the deal with Capital Partners.
Therefore, Barach said, ``We do not intend to seek out potential
buyers and would rather operate this proven business.''
   The collapse of the sale agreement means U.S. Shoe will not
increase its annual dividend from 46 cents to $1 per share, as
previously had been announced.
   Jerome Fisher, chairman of the Fisher Camuto Group in Stamford,
Conn., said his company would be willing to pay more than the
proposed $422.5 million sale price, but was refused the financial
information he needed before making a bid. U.S. Shoe officials said
they were afraid that a deal with Fisher Camuto, which is a shoe
importer, would violate antitrust laws.
</TEXT>
