<FIRST>r f AM-UnionPacific     04-27 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Union Pacific,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Pacific Announces Buyback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Pacific Corp. will buy back up to
14.5 million shares of common stock in a $1 billion repurchase plan
and sell its real-estate subsidiary, the company announced Thursday.
   ``These actions are designed to enhance shareholder value,''
chief executive officer Drew Lewis said in a statement.
   But Standard and Poor's Corp. said in a statement from New York
that the announcement had ``negative implications'' for the
company's long-term debt, and it was placing the bond and
commercial paper issues on CreditWatch.
   The Bethlehem-based holding company has about $2 billion in
long-term debt, and its Omaha, Neb.-based railroad subsidiary has
$900 million, S&amp;P said.
   Union Pacific spokesman Harvey S. Turner declined comment on the
S&amp;P statement, issued after the stock markets closed Thursday.
   The company said its board of directors had authorized the
buyback offer to begin Friday and expire at midnight May 25. The
board also has authorized spending up to $528 million to buy back
additional shares in open market or other transactions after the
cash self-tender offer expires, the company said.
   Under the buyback plan, each of Union Pacific's 70,000
shareholders will be invited to name a price between $66 and $73
per share. The company will choose a price and buy up to 14.5
million shares tendered at or below that price.
   The offer is not conditioned on a minimum number of shares being
tendered.
   Analysts said the move appeared to be aimed at increasing
shareholder value, but disagreed on whether it might be a defensive
move against a possible takeover attempt.
   ``Takeover targets in the past have certainly included companies
with a diversified base,'' said Robert L. Decker, an analyst with
Duff &amp; Phelps in Chicago, who added he knew of no potential suitors.
   Union Pacific's subsidiaries include a major Western railroad,
trucking, real estate, natural resources and hazardous waste
disposal.
   ``I don't think it's a major takeover target,'' said Andrew
Geller, transportation analyst for Provident National Bank in
Philadelphia. Union Pacific had been trying to build its stock
price in part because of an incentive plan for top executives, he
said.
   Union Pacific Realty, has been based in Denver, but is scheduled
to move to new headquarters in Dallas by June 1, Turner said. It
has holdings in California, suburban Chicago, Washington, D.C.; Las
Vegas, Nev.; Denver and Houston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
