<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Northwest 2ndLd-Writethru   04-27 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rothmeier Says Northwest Has Up To Four Friendly Suitors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede EAGAN, Minn.</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with new grafs 1-4 to UPDATE with Commerce commissioner
blocking Davis offer; picks up 2nd graf pvs bg'ng, ``There are ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch late
Thursday blocked oil billionaire Marvin Davis' $2.7 billion tender
offer for Northwest Airlines in Minnesota.
   The suspension order blocks the estimated 1,900 shareholders in
the state from selling their 1.3 million shares to Davis.
   Hatch had given Davis the option of asking for another hearing
on the issue, which would have been held Thursday night, but Davis
did not request one by the 5 p.m. deadline, according to Lisa
Rotenberg, a spokesperson for the commissioner.
   In a related development Thursday, key legislators' questions
about the constitutionality of a proposed anti-takeover bill aimed
at placing roadblocks in the way of suitors for Northwest delayed a
vote on the measure by the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   Separately, NWA Inc. Chairman Steven Rothmeier said a
management-led buyout of Northwest is not in the works, but there
are as many as four friendly suitors interested in buying the
airline.
   ``There are a couple of friendly investors out there who could
do something significant for our shareholders,'' Rothmeier said at
his first news conference since the carrier became the target of a
hostile $2.7 billion takeover bid by oil mogul Marvin Davis.
``There are two very strong, friendly indications.''
   Rothmeier would not identify the suitors, but said he considers
a previously identified group led by Los Angeles investor Al
Checchi to be a potential ``white knight.'' Checchi's group, which
includes former NWA Inc. director Gary Wilson, holds a 4.9 percent
stake in the company.
   Wilson is a former Marriott Corp. executive and Rothmeier is a
friend of Willard Marriott, the company's chairman, said Alan
Muncaster, a Northwest spokesman.
   NWA shares jumped $2.37{ a share to $102.37{ in consolidated New
York Stock Exchange trading, remaining above Davis' $90-a-share
buyout proposal.
   Rothmeier said management is not pursuing a leveraged buyout and
has not hired an adviser to explore one, although such a
transaction has not be ruled out. In a leveraged buyout, investors
acquire a company mainly with borrowed funds that are repaid with
money raised by the target company's cash flow or the sale of its
assets.
   Ten to 15 groups have shown interest in buying or investing in
the airline and the NWA board has said it would consider all
serious offers. Non-public information about the airline will be
available beginning next week to groups who have signed a
confidentiality agreement.
   Rothmeier said the board would like to make a final decision as
soon as possible.
   Rothmeier repeated an earlier statement that a successful deal
with friendly suitors was contingent on a closed contract with the
airline's 5,000 pilots. Rothmeier has urged the pilots to expedite
negotiations, but union negotiators have declined.
   ``An open contract is an invitation to hostile money,''
Rothmeier said.
   If a hostile bidder acquires the airline and opens negotiations
with the pilots, the next offer ``will look like a TWA contract or
a Continental Airlines contract,'' Rothmeier said. Pilots at those
two carriers had to accept concessionary contracts after the
airlines were acquired.
   If the pilots reject such an offer and strike, the new
management would be inclined to say, ``Fine. I liquidate,''
Rothmeier said.
   Jim Halvorson, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association,
said the statements by Rothmeier were intended to pressure the
pilots into concessions.
   Davis has launched a proxy fight to unseat the NWA board at its
May 15 annual meeting, but Rothmeier discounted Davis' chances of
winning.
   ``Based on the proposal he has out there today, I don't think
he's got a lot of influence in the shareholder vote,'' Rothmeier
said.
   The $90 a share Davis offer, which includes less than 10 percent
equity, would hurt the carrier by loading it with debt, Rothmeier
said. He also disagreed with Davis' contentions that he could
operate the airline profitably with the minimal changes he has
proposed _ especially in an economic downturn.
   Rothmeier also said the value of NWA's Tokyo real estate has
been exaggerated. Davis has said he would consider refinancing or
selling the real estate, which analysts have said could bring up to
$500 million. But Rothmeier said the Japanese government could slap
a tax of up to 70 percent on the sale and must approve the sale
price.
</TEXT>
