<FILEID>AP-NR-04-27-89 2054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-S&amp;Ls 3rdLd-Writethru f0302 04-27 1297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0302,1329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Votes Tougher Standards But Extends Deadline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To CORRECT dates to 1995, SUBS 2nd graf, bgng, `Eleven Republicans,'
and 16th graf bgng, `Effectively, it.' Also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee voted Thursday to
make savings and loan owners put nearly $13 billion more of their
own money at risk as the price for a $90 billion federal bailout
but gave them 3{ more years than President Bush wants to do it.
   Eleven Republicans joined all but four Democrats in a 36-15 vote
to delay until January 1995 the June 1991 deadline that Bush had
proposed for S&amp;Ls to come up with 3 percent ``hard cash'' capital _
or $3 for every $100 they lend.
   ``Without real capital _ hard capital _ the taxpayers have no
protection'' from further raids on federal deposit insurance funds
by imprudent S&amp;L operators, said the committee's chairman, Rep.
Henry Gonzalez, D-Texas.
   Action on several weakening amendments was postponed until next
week. Nonetheless, administration officials hailed Thursday's vote
_ which doubles the capital requirements of a bill approved by the
Senate last week _ a major victory for Bush's plan.
   ``Requiring S&amp;Ls to put their own capital at risk ahead of the
taxpayers' money is the only way to prevent in the future the
unsound business practices that contributed to the current
crisis,'' said Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady.
   Assistant Treasury Secretary David Mullins told reporters
afterward that the panel's recognition of the need for a 3 percent
layer of protection between S&amp;L loans that could go sour and
federal insurance funds was more important than the timetable for
achieving it.
   ``We're happy to have that number up on the board now,'' he said.
   The committee later weakened the requirement slightly on a 26-24
vote on an amendment by Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., that would
allow S&amp;Ls to continue counting as capital their past direct
investments in subsidiaries engaged in real estate, insurance or
other businesses.
   But under the amendment, double leveraging of those investments
_ in what Mullins described as effectively a pyramid scheme _ to
support massive quantities of new lending would no longer be
allowed.
   Such direct investments by S&amp;Ls using little or none of their
own hard cash capital to support skyrocketing loan growth rates _
particularly in Texas, Florida and California _ have been blamed as
a major contributor to the thrift crisis.
   Through such schemes, the administration and others have argued,
a portion of the industry was able to lend hundreds of billions of
federally insured deposits for risky and often fraudulent real
estate and other ventures.
   Including interest, the taxpayer cost of backing up the federal
insurance guarantees to depositors whose money was lost is expected
to be well over $200 billion over the next 30 years under Bush's
bailout plan.
   Opponents of the plan said many of the nation's thrifts would be
forced out of business or into mergers by rapidly imposing stricter
capital standards. That, they argue, would require another taxpayer
bailout in the near future.
   ``If we force institutions by definition ... to double their
capital in two years, ... then it will not be the private sector
that puts it in; it may well be the government who puts it in,''
said Rep. John Hiler, R-Ind.
   Throgh an amendment by Rep. Bruce Vento, D-Minn., the committee
adopted a new capital requirement that the administration has been
pushing since late last week.
   Effectively, it would require S&amp;L owners to show by 1995 that
they have $3 of ``tangible'' capital in the form of cash or stock
of their own at risk for every $100 they lend. Otherwise, they
would be put under a broad measure of government controls.
   Vento's amendment slightly altered an administration-endorsed
version by Gonzalez and Rep. Chalmers Wylie of Ohio, the
committee's ranking Republican. It would have required $2.25 in
capital for each $100 of loans on an S&amp;L's books, with Bush's June
1991 deadline.
   The new version would give S&amp;L owners an additional 19 months to
reach the $2.25 plateau. It would also extend until January 1995
the required ``tangible'' capital level asked by the administration
and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   The administration had praised the Senate's action last week to
require S&amp;L owners to put up $1.50 in capital for each $100 in
loans they write. But it also immediately sought more in the form
of an amendment to the House version, vowing to ``take the case to
the taxpayers'' if its new demand was not met.
   Opponents, however, said the new infusions of cash investments
being demanded as a layer of protection between S&amp;L lending
practices and the government's deposit insurance funds would drive
600 to 700 moderately healthy thrifts out of business.
   ``Our choice is simple,'' said Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill. ``Do
we save the S&amp;L industry ... for the American people who want a
home ... or do we sell it out.''
   But Rep. Toby Roth, R-Wis., countered that any institution that
cannot raise its level of capital to $2.25 for every $100 in loans
on their books ``should not be in the business.''
   ``If we don't strengthen the capital requirement, this is going
to be a real wimpout,'' he told his colleagues. ``In fact the
definition of a wimp is going to become someone who serves on the
House Banking Committee.''
   Annunzio was the primary author of an amendment approved two
weeks ago that would require thrift owners within a year to show
they have $1.50 in ``tangible'' capital such as cash or stock
easily convertible to cash for every $100 they lend.
   While that has been characterized as both toughening and
weakening Bush's original proposal, the same figure was adopted by
the Senate but with fewer accounting loopholes that would prevent
federal regulators from recovering all that amount in the event of
an S&amp;L's failure.
   Gonzalez likened ``good will'' exemptions from hard cash, stock
or other equity capital requirements that the government has
granted S&amp;Ls over the last eight years to ``a soft ice-cream cone
in the July sun.''
   ``Good will provides nothing if the institution goes down,'' he
said. ``This entire exercise is a sham unless we change the way the
savings and loans operate. We cannot in good conscience require the
taxpayers to pay out billions of dollars and at the same time tell
them they must bear all the future risks.''
   Wylie said Brady had told him Thursday that Bush ``will take
their case to the taxpayers prior to a vote on the House floor'' if
the amendment was not adopted.
   According to the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, some 2,586 of the
remaining thrifts nationwide have some form of cash or tangible net
worth that could be tapped before government insurance funds were
needed if there was a run on deposits.
   But 323 of them with outstanding loans of more than $400 billion
have below the 1.5 percent, or $1.50, standard and another 478 are
now below the 2.25 percent, or $2.25, tangible capital level,
according to the U.S. League of Savings Institutions, the
industry's biggest trade organization.
   Jim Grohl, a league vice president, said the $1.50 capital
requirement would force the 323 solvent thrifts now below that
standard to come up with a total of $9.2 billion in new capital.
   The $2.25 standard, he said, would require the 801 institutions
with less than that now to raise a total of $12.8 billion over the
next two years.
   ``The solvent institutions earned only $3.4 billion last year,''
he said. ``Since 1980 and during some pretty good times, the
industry has been able to raise only $20 billion in new capital. A
lot of them just aren't going to make it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
