<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Airlines 2ndLd-Writethru f0313 04-27 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Airlines, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0313,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delta Earnings Soar, UAL's Fall in First Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead, ADDS 3 grafs to UPDATE with USAir earnings and
to CLARIFY that UAL was profitable on a continuing-operations basis.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First-quarter profits surged at Delta Air Lines
and USAir's parent company, while the parent of United Airlines
said Thursday its first-quarter profit on continuing operations
also increased.
   Delta said its strong first quarter was only partially a result
of the strike that virtually grounded rival Eastern Airlines.
   Delta said good economic conditions, continuing benefits from a
merger with Western Air Lines and growth in domestic and
international operations also contributed to the increase.
   Delta said earnings for the first quarter jumped to $85 million,
or $1.73 a share, from $56.1 million, or $1.15 a share, in the same
period of 1988.
   First-quarter revenue rose 19 percent to $2.04 billion.
   ``The key to the increased earnings was the 20 percent growth in
passenger revenues,'' said Thomas J. Roeck, senior vice president
for finance and chief financial officer of Delta.
   ``The strike against a major competitor during the month of
March resulted in increased revenue passenger miles,'' he said,
``but traffic growth was strong in January and February prior to
the strike, and in many markets not affected by the strike.''
   He said passenger traffic increased 13 percent in Atlanta, one
of the areas most affected by the Eastern strike.
   ``Yet traffic for the first three months of the year was up 8
percent in Dallas-Fort Worth, 37 percent in Honolulu, 15 percent in
Los Angeles and 10 percent in Salt Lake City _ all markets where
Eastern is not a competitor,'' Roeck said.
   For the nine months ended March 31, Delta earned $270.1 million,
or $5.49 a share, an increase of 33 percent over the same period in
the previous year.
   Nine-month revenue rose to $5.78 billion from $5.04 billion a
year earlier.
   At Chicago-based UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines, profit
for the first quarter was down sharply due to a one-time after-tax
gain of $548 million in last year's first quarter from the sale of
its Westin hotel unit.
   Profit for the first quarter totaled $65.4 million, or $3.03 per
share, down from $576.9 million, or $12.02 per share, in 1988's
first quarter.
   But comparing continuing operations, mainly the airline, UAL's
profit rose sharply in the first quarter to $65.4 million compared
with the year-ago profit of $27.9 million.
   The per-share earnings are not comparable because the average
number of common shares outstanding used in calculating the 1989
figure was 21.6 million, compared with 47.9 million for the first
quarter of 1988. The difference is due to UAL's purchase of 35.5
million shares of its common stock in March 1988.
   Revenue for the first quarter totaled $2.3 billion, up from
$2.06 billion in the 1988 quarter.
   UAL said passenger miles on United planes were up only slightly
but the company's yield per passenger increased 18 percent, largely
because of higher air fares.
   USAir Group Inc. reported earnings of $15.5 million, or 35 cents
a share, in the first quarter, compared with a loss of $18.8
million a year earlier.
   USAir had revenues of $1.48 billion, up 18 percent from $1.25
billion a year earlier. Traffic on USAir was up 34 percent in the
period and 8 percent on Piedmont, which is also owned by the
Arlington, Va.-based airline holding company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
